{"title_page": "Angela Billingham, Baroness Billingham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Official portrait of Baroness Billingham crop 2, 2019.jpg|thumb|right|Angela Billingham]]\n'''Angela Theodora Billingham, Baroness Billingham''' [[Justice of the peace|JP]] (born 31 July 1939) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[politician]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn Angela Theodora Case in [[Liverpool]], she was educated at [[Aylesbury Grammar School]], the [[Institute of Education]] and the Department of Education, [[Oxford University]]. She became a teacher, working in education for thirty five years until 1995.\n\n==Political career==\nBaroness Billingham was a councillor for many years. From 1970 until 1974, she served on [[Banbury]] [[Borough Council]], then from 1974 to 1984 on [[Cherwell (district)|Cherwell District]] Council. She was Mayor of Banbury in 1976. She was an [[Oxfordshire County Council|Oxfordshire]] [[county council]]lor 1993\u201394. She stood for Parliament in 1992 for [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury]], without success.\n\nBillingham was elected to the [[European Parliament]] for [[Northamptonshire and Blaby (European Parliament constituency)|Northamptonshire and Blaby]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite news | last =Foster | first =Jonathan | title =The European Elections: Working-class voters wooed back | work =The Independent | date =13 June 1994 }}</ref> In 1999 she unsuccessfully stood for the European Parliament in the new [[East Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|East Midlands]] Region. She was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baroness Billingham''', of Banbury in the County of Oxfordshire on 2 May 2000<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55846 |date=12 May 2000 |page=5243}}</ref> and sits on the Labour benches.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hartley-Brewer | first = Julia |author2=Woodward, Will | title =Policy and Politics: Blair `balances' Lords with 33 new peers | work =The Guardian | pages =11 | date =31 March 2000 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title =Life Peers | work =The Times (London) | pages =24 | date =4 May 2000 }}</ref>\n\n==Interests==\nShe has promoted sports for people with disabilities and is a regular on Sky News where she previews the following morning's newspapers. Angela also campaigns for reform of the current [[Daylight Saving]] system, arguing that lighter evenings could end the national scourge of [[childhood obesity]] by allowing children to do an extra hour of [[physical activity]] a day. She also cites economic, environmental and safety concerns as important reasons for reform of the current system. She is also a keen tennis player, and is Chair/Captain of the Commons and Lords Tennis Club and the Chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Tennis Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/register/memi543.htm |title=Register of All-Party Groups |date=24 February 2010 |work=House of Commons |accessdate=2 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327153909/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/register/memi543.htm |archivedate=27 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/8593098.stm |title=All-Party Tennis Group warns LTA over public profile |last=Slater |first=Matt |date=29 March 2010 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2 April 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100401121058/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/8593098.stm| archivedate= 1 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married Peter Billingham in 1962 and they had two daughters, Zo\u00eb and Caroline. Peter died in 1992. Zo\u00eb is married to Dennis Skinner, son of [[Dennis Skinner]], the long-serving Labour [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Bolsover (UK Parliament constituency)|Bolsover]].\n\n==Parliamentary expenses==\nSubsistence Allowances are designed to help peers who live in the country to attend late-night votes and debates in Parliament, Billingham, who has a flat in Hampstead and a country house in Suffolk claimed \u00a326,983 in 2006\u201307 in overnight allowances, prompting calls for an inquiry.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/feb/10/lords Peers face demand for expenses probe]</ref>\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/baroness_billingham Baroness Billingham page on theyworkforyou.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Billingham, Angela}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the UCL Institute of Education]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for England]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1994\u20131999]]\n[[Category:People educated at Aylesbury Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in England]]\n[[Category:20th-century British politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Official portrait of Baroness Billingham crop 2, 2019.jpg|thumb|right|Angela Billingham]]\n'''Angela Theodora Billingham, Baroness Billingham''' [[Justice of the peace|JP]] (born 31 July 1939) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[politician]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn Angela Theodora Case in [[Liverpool]], she was educated at [[Aylesbury Grammar School]], the [[Institute of Education]] and the Department of Education, [[Oxford University]]. She became a teacher, working in education for thirty five years until 1995.\n\n==Political career==\nBaroness Billingham was a councillor for many years. From 1970 until 1974, she served on [[Banbury]] [[Borough Council]], then from 1974 to 1984 on [[Cherwell (district)|Cherwell District]] Council. She was Mayor of Banbury in 1976. She was an [[Oxfordshire County Council|Oxfordshire]] [[county council]]lor 1993-94. She stood for Parliament in 1992 for [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury]], without success.\n\nBillingham was elected to the [[European Parliament]] for [[Northamptonshire and Blaby (European Parliament constituency)|Northamptonshire and Blaby]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite news | last =Foster | first =Jonathan | title =The European Elections: Working-class voters wooed back | work =The Independent | date =13 June 1994 }}</ref> In 1999 she unsuccessfully stood for the European Parliament in the new [[East Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|East Midlands]] Region. She was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baroness Billingham''', of Banbury in the County of Oxfordshire on 2 May 2000<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55846 |date=12 May 2000 |page=5243}}</ref> and sits on the Labour benches.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hartley-Brewer | first = Julia |author2=Woodward, Will | title =Policy and Politics: Blair `balances' Lords with 33 new peers | work =The Guardian | pages =11 | date =31 March 2000 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title =Life Peers | work =The Times (London) | pages =24 | date =4 May 2000 }}</ref>\n\n==Interests==\nShe has promoted sports for people with disabilities and is a regular on Sky News where she previews the following morning's newspapers. Angela also campaigns for reform of the current [[Daylight Saving]] system, arguing that lighter evenings could end the national scourge of [[childhood obesity]] by allowing children to do an extra hour of [[physical activity]] a day. She also cites economic, environmental and safety concerns as important reasons for reform of the current system. She is also a keen tennis player, and is Chair/Captain of the Commons and Lords Tennis Club and the Chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Tennis Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/register/memi543.htm |title=Register of All-Party Groups |date=24 February 2010 |work=House of Commons |accessdate=2 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327153909/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/register/memi543.htm |archivedate=27 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/8593098.stm |title=All-Party Tennis Group warns LTA over public profile |last=Slater |first=Matt |date=29 March 2010 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2 April 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100401121058/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/8593098.stm| archivedate= 1 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married Peter Billingham in 1962 and they had two daughters, Zo\u00eb and Caroline. Peter died in 1992. Zo\u00eb is married to Dennis Skinner, son of [[Dennis Skinner]], the long-serving Labour [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Bolsover (UK Parliament constituency)|Bolsover]].\n\n==Parliamentary expenses==\nSubsistence Allowances are designed to help peers who live in the country to attend late-night votes and debates in Parliament, Billingham, who has a flat in Hampstead and a country house in Suffolk claimed \u00a326,983 in 2006-07 in overnight allowances, prompting calls for an inquiry.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/feb/10/lords Peers face demand for expenses probe]</ref>\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/baroness_billingham Baroness Billingham page on theyworkforyou.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Billingham, Angela}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the UCL Institute of Education]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for England]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1994\u20131999]]\n[[Category:People educated at Aylesbury Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in England]]\n[[Category:20th-century British politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2006-07 \u2192 2006\u201307, 1993-94 \u2192 1993\u201394", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angela_Billingham,_Baroness_Billingham"}
{"title_page": "Tradicional A Lo Bravo", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tradicional A Lo Bravo\n| cover      = Tradicional a Bravo.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Single Cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tego Calder\u00f3n]]\n| album      = [[El Abayarde Contraataca]]\n| released   = August 7, 2007\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital Download]]\n| recorded   = 2006\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Reggaeton]]\n| length     = 3:45\n| label      = [[Jiggiri Records]]<br>[[Warner Music|Warner Musica Latina]]\n| writer     = [[Tego Calder\u00f3n|Tegui Calder\u00f3n Rossario]]\n| producer   = Almonte\n| prev_title = Cuando Baila Reggaeton\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = [[Quitarte To']] '\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\n\n\"'''Tradicional A Lo Bravo'''\" is a song performed by [[Tego Calder\u00f3n]] for his album ''[[El Abayarde Contraataca]]''. The song was released as the album's first and promotional single in late 2007 and had a lot of airplay during the two weeks after the song got released. This single was released with [[Jiggiri Records]] (Tego Calder\u00f3n's label) and [[Warner Musica Latina]].\n\n==Background==\n\"Tradicional A Lo Bravo\" is based on the Latin culture, and Tego Calder\u00f3n greatly influenced writing this song. The single has both its lyrics and its music video based on the album. It was recorded by Victor \"El Nasi\" and wasn't considered as completely [[reggaeton]], but was Tego's own type of music.\n\n==Music video==\n\"Tradicional A Lo Bravo\" was the first music video on the album, being the first single released. The music video reflects both the album's theme, and the song's lyrics. It is shown in a bar, and shows animated figures throughout the video. It was watched in all channels, including [[Mun2]], [[MTV Tr3s]], and others. Tego Calder\u00f3n performed \"Tradicional A Lo Bravo\" live on [[Mi TRL]], and got interviewed on many programs.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2007)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|US [[Tropical Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web |title=Tego Calder\u00f3n&nbsp;\u2014 Charts & Awards&nbsp;\u2014 Billboard Singles |work=Allmusic |publisher=Rovi Corporation |url=http://allmusic.com/artist/tego-caldern-p561013/charts-awards/billboard-singles}}</ref> \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tegocalderon.com/ Tego Calderon's official website]\n\n[[Category:2007 singles]]\n[[Category:Tego Calder\u00f3n songs]]\n[[Category:2006 songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tradicional A Lo Bravo\n| cover      = Tradicional a Bravo.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Single Cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tego Calder\u00f3n]]\n| album      = [[El Abayarde Contraataca]]\n| released   = August 7, 2007\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital Download]]\n| recorded   = 2006\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Reggaeton]]\n| length     = 3:45\n| label      = [[Jiggiri Records]]<br>[[Warner Music|Warner Musica Latina]]\n| writer     = [[Tego Calder\u00f3n|Tegui Calder\u00f3n Rossario]]\n| producer   = Almonte\n| prev_title = Cuando Baila Reggaeton\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = [[Quitarte To']] '\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\n\n\"'''Tradicional A Lo Bravo'''\" is a song performed by [[Tego Calder\u00f3n]] for his album ''[[El Abayarde Contraataca]]''. The song was released as the album's first and promotional single in late 2007 and had a lot of airplay during the two weeks after the song got released. This single was released with [[Jiggiri Records]] (Tego Calder\u00f3n's label) and [[Warner Musica Latina]]. \n\n==Background==\n\"Tradicional A Lo Bravo\" is based on the Latin culture, and Tego Calder\u00f3n greatly influenced writing this song. The single has both its lyrics and its music video based on the album. It was recorded by Victor \"El Nasi\" and wasn't considered as completely [[reggaeton]], but was Tego's own type of music.\n\n==Music video==\n\"Tradicional A Lo Bravo\" was the first music video on the album, being the first single released. The music video reflects both the album's theme, and the songs lyrics. It is shown in a bar, and shows animated figures throughout the video. It was watched in all channels, including [[Mun2]], [[MTV Tr3s]], and others. Tego Calder\u00f3n performed \"Tradicional A Lo Bravo\" live on [[Mi TRL]], and got interviewed on many programs.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2007)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|US [[Tropical Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web |title=Tego Calder\u00f3n&nbsp;\u2014 Charts & Awards&nbsp;\u2014 Billboard Singles |work=Allmusic |publisher=Rovi Corporation |url=http://allmusic.com/artist/tego-caldern-p561013/charts-awards/billboard-singles}}</ref> \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tegocalderon.com/ Tego Calderon's official website]\n\n[[Category:2007 singles]]\n[[Category:Tego Calder\u00f3n songs]]\n[[Category:2006 songs]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: songs lyrics \u2192 song's lyrics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tradicional_A_Lo_Bravo"}
{"title_page": "Waheed Alli, Baron Alli", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Alli\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image = Waheed Alli 2010.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|smallimage =\n|caption =\n|office          = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]]\n|1blankname      = [[Chancellor (education)#Vice-chancellor|Vice-Chancellor]]\n|1namedata       = Philip Tasker<br/>[[Dominic Shellard]]\n|term_start      = 2006\n|term_end        = 2015\n|predecessor      = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|The Baroness Prashar]]\n|successor        = [[Doreen Lawrence|The Baroness Lawrence]]\n|office2         = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member]] of the [[House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start2       = 18 July 1998<br/><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|term_end2       =\n|birthname = Waheed Alli\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1964|11|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Croydon]], London, UK\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = British\n|restingplace =\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|partner =\n|profession = Media entrepreneur\n\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n'''Waheed Alli, Baron Alli''' (born 16 November 1964) is a media entrepreneur and politician. He is the co-creator of the television series ''[[Survivor (franchise)|Survivor]]'' and has held executive positions at several television production companies including the [[Endemol Shine Group]], Carlton Television Productions (now [[ITV Studios]]), [[Planet 24]], and [[Chorion (company)|Chorion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/markets/stocks|title=Executive Profile: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently the Chief Executive of [[Silvergate Media]], Chairman of Koovs Plc and a director at [[Olga TV|Olga Productions]]. He is a member of the [[House of Lords]] in the United Kingdom, sitting as a [[life peer]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and is described as one of only a few openly [[Islam and sexual orientation|gay Muslim]] politicians in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html|title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row|last=Alderson|first=Andrew|newspaper=Telegraph|quote= one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012|date=6 March 2010}}     \n</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=Edgecliffe-Johnson|first=Andrew|publisher=FT|quote=one of the few gay Muslims in British public life.|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIn British political terms he is considered [[British Asian|Asian]], because both of his parents are [[Indo-Caribbean]]. His mother, a nurse, is an [[Indo-Trinidadian]] from [[Trinidad and Tobago]], and his estranged father, a mechanic, is an [[Indo-Guyanese]] from [[Guyana]]. His mother was [[Hindu]] and his father [[Muslim]]; he has two brothers, who are also Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=26 April 2012|location=London}}</ref> He was named one of the 20 most important Asians in British media in 2005.<ref name=\"AIM\">[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Most Powerful Asians in British Media: Lord Waheed Alli]. ''Asians in Media''</ref> At the same time, he maintains ties with his Caribbean roots, both with other British-Guyanese politicians such as [[Valerie Amos]] and [[Trevor Phillips]], and with President [[Bharrat Jagdeo]].<ref name=\"CV\">John Muir, [http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html \"Caribbean Peers\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html |date=27 September 2007 }}, Caribbean Voice, October 2001.</ref>\n\nHe is one of a group of highly successful Guyanese people in Britain ([[Michael White (journalist)|Michael White]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' refers to them as the \"Guyanese mafia\"), which includes [[Raj Persaud]], [[Herman Ouseley]]<ref>Michael White, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2009/aug/27/balls-gcse-results-michael-white \"Balls gets his retaliation in first as annual GCSE row begins\"], ''The Guardian'', 27 August 2009.</ref> and [[David Dabydeen]], [[Cynthia Pine]], [[Keith Waithe]] and [[Rudolph Dunbar]].<ref>''Guyanese Achievers UK'' (2007) by Dindayal Vidur.</ref>\n\nAlli grew up in humble surroundings, attended [[Harris Academy South Norwood|Stanley Technical College]] in [[South Norwood]] and left school at 16 with nine [[O-levels]].<ref name=\"KC\">[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html Knitting Circle.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307031738/http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html |date=7 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nAlli started work as a junior researcher for a finance magazine, crediting his first success to Salem Ghayar, who hired and mentored him.  After a few years of preparing monthly reports for potential investors, he was headhunted by Save & Prosper, part of [[Robert Fleming & Co.]].<ref name=\"asianoutlook.com\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20030308075823/http://www.asianoutlook.com/lordali.htm Interviewed by Shahid]. ''The Asian Outlook''. No date; approximately 2001.</ref> Eventually he returned to his original employer, and worked his way up in the media business within [[Robert Maxwell]]'s stable of publications.  He then went to [[City of London|the City]] for a second career in [[investment banking]], through which he became wealthy.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm|title=Profile: Lord Waheed Alli|date=29 November 2000|work=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=24 May 2009}}</ref> In the mid-1980s he met [[Charlie Parsons]], who was to become his business partner as well as his life partner.<ref name=\"The Independent (Saturday 06 June 2015)\">{{cite web|title=The Party Boys|publisher=The Independent. Saturday, 6 June 2015|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-party-boys-1196428.html|website=}}</ref>\n\nAlli's third career, and the first in which he achieved public prominence, was in the television industry.  He and Parsons set up [[24 Hour Productions]], which produced ''[[The Word (TV series)|The Word]]'', \"the most talked about television programme in Britain\".<ref name=\"KC\" /> In 1992 they merged with [[Bob Geldof]]'s [[Planet Pictures]] to form [[Planet 24]].  Such was its success that it became one of the largest TV production companies in the country, and the main independent supplier to [[Channel 4]].<ref name=\"KC\" /> It was responsible for genre-breaking programmes such as ''Big Breakfast'' and ''[[Survivor (TV series)|Survivor]]''. [[Carlton Television]] bought Planet 24 in March 1999 for \u00a315 million, with Alli and Parsons prudently retaining the rights to the lucrative ''Survivor'' format. Waheed Alli became a Carlton board director before stepping down a year later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2003 Alli took over as chairman of the [[intellectual property|media rights]] company [[Chorion (company)|Chorion Ltd]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2871751/Hands-off-Noddy.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Hands off Noddy! | date=14 December 2003}}</ref> which owns rights to [[Enid Blyton]] and [[Agatha Christie]], and has offices beyond the UK in New York, Sydney, and Tokyo.<ref name=\"AIM\" /> He was chairman of [[Alternative Investment Market|AIM]]-listed [[ASOS.com]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8124164.stm|title=Overseas sales boost Asos profits|date=29 June 2009|work=[[bbc.co.uk]]|accessdate=29 June 2009}}</ref> and a director of [[Olga Television]], entertainer [[Paul O'Grady]]'s [[production company]]. He owns part of [[Shine Limited]], a media production company he co-founded in March 2001 with [[Elisabeth Murdoch (businesswoman)|Elisabeth Murdoch]], daughter of media-magnate [[Rupert Murdoch]]. In August 2011, he stepped down from the chairmanship of Chorion and sold half his stake in ASOS.com to start a new company called Silvergate Media.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012|reason=please provide source or remove}}\n\nHe was part of a failed \u00a3100m bid backed by [[private equity]] firm [[3i]] to buy [[Virgin Radio]] from [[SMG plc]] in 2005. In March 2007 he was appointed as SMG's non-executive director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/mar/05/smg.citynews|title=SMG makes board appointments|last=Holmwood|first=Leigh|date=5 March 2007|work=[[guardian.co.uk]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAlli is a founder investor in Koovs, an Indian online retailer looking to replicate the success of Asos in the subcontinent. The company was set up in 2012 and intends to raise \u00a322m with a stock market listing on London's Aim.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b8586954-4bb5-11e3-a02f-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2kVSow9B5|author=Duncan Robinson|work=Financial Times|date=12 November 2013|title=Ex-Asos boss to list Indian venture on Aim}}</ref>\nIn December 2019 the company goes into administration after funding isn't found.  The company is bought by SGIK 3 for 250,000. Shareholders lose millions.  SGIK 3 is Lord Ali's company, set up in the weeks prior to the collapse.<ref>https://www.morningstar.co.uk/uk/news/AN_1576002908644184200/update-koovs-sold-to-sgik-3-after-falling-in-administration.aspx</ref>\n==Politics==\nAlli joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at the persuasion of his neighbour [[Emily Thornberry]], to whom he remains close.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Aida |last=Edemariam |title=Right, so just what do you do all day? |date=19 May 2009 }}</ref> He is also close to [[Anji Hunter]], Director of Government Relations in [[Tony Blair]]'s first government.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Kamal |last=Ahmed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2002/jun/02/tonyblair.schools |title=Inside Labour's young boy (and girl) network |work=[[The Observer]] |date=2 June 2002 }}</ref> [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] Blair used him for years as a means to help him reach out to a younger generation (aka \"[[Youth subculture|yoof culture]]\"),<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and as such he is considered{{by whom|date=July 2013}} one of \"[[Tony's Cronies]]\".<ref name=\"CV\" /> He was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Alli''', of [[Norbury]] in the [[London Borough of Croydon]], on 18 July 1998<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55203 |date=22 July 1998 |page=7983}}</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Minutes and Order Paper \u2013 Minutes of Proceedings \u2013 The House of Lords] Parliament (19 July 1998). Retrieved on 15 March 2013.</ref> at the age of 34, becoming the youngest and the first openly gay peer in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. He sits on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]]. The [[BBC]] summarised his appointment as \"the antithesis of the stereotypical '[[The Establishment|establishment]]' peer \u2013 young, Asian and from the world of media and entertainment\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nAlli has used his political position to argue for [[gay rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kooth.com/|title=Kooth {{!}} Home|website=kooth.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-23}}</ref> He spearheaded the campaign to repeal [[Section 28]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |title=What was Clause 28? |first=Liz |last=Highleyman |work=Gmax |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060814052339/http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |date=16 February 2006 |archivedate=14 August 2006 |accessdate=24 June 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He advocated lowering the [[age of consent]] for homosexuals from 18 to 16, equal to heterosexuals; this eventually became law as the [[Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000]]. It was during a heated exchange with conservative opponents, led by [[Janet Young, Baroness Young|Baroness Young]], that he informed his fellow peers that he was gay. In April 1999, he said in a speech, \"I have never been confused about my sexuality. I have been confused about the way I am treated as a result of it. The only confusion lies in the prejudice shown, some of it tonight [i.e. in the House], and much of it enshrined in the law.\"<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Hansard: Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000\">{{cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |title=HL Deb 13 April 1999 vol 599 c737 |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1999/apr/13/sexual-offences-amendment-bill#S5LV0599P0_19990413_HOL_256 |house=[[House of Lords]] |date=13 April 1999 |column=737 |speaker=Waheed Alli, Baron Alli |position=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he participated the [[2006 World Outgames#International Conference on LGBT Human Rights|International Conference on LGBT Human Rights]] adopting [[Declaration of Montreal]] and in 2009, he spearheaded an effort to repeal clauses in the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004]] which prohibited religious institutions from conducting the ceremonies on their premises.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.churchofengland.org/our-views/home-and-community-affairs/home-affairs-policy/equality-bill/lord-alli's-amendment.aspx |title=Lord Alli's amendment |publisher=[[Church of England]] }}{{dead link |date=June 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html |title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row |last=Alderson |first=Andrew |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |quote=one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012 |date=6 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8546827.stm |title=Church gay ceremonies ban lifted |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref> This campaign culminated in a bipartisan amendment, which became part of the [[Equality Act 2010]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Jerome |last=Taylor |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/gay-weddings-to-be-allowed-in-church-1915467.html |title=Gay weddings to be allowed in church |work=[[The Independent]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-16203951 |title=Peer drops fight over same-sex ceremonies in churches |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=15 December 2011 }}</ref> He influenced the draft Communications Bill in 2003.<ref name=\"AIM\" />\n\n==Other activities==\nAlli's work has been focused around gay rights, youth and education.  He is the former [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]] in [[Leicester]]. He is also the President of the [[Croydon]] Youth Development Trust.<ref>[http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html Croydon Youth Development Trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060620100247/http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html |date=20 June 2006 }}</ref> He is a patron of Skillset,<ref>[http://www.skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp Skillset Board of Patrons] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129220527/http://skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp |date=29 November 2010 }}</ref> the [[Sector Skills Council]] supporting skills and training within the creative media industries.\n\nIn Autumn 2008 he won a [[Stonewall Awards|Stonewall Award]] for the category of political figure. In 2002 he became a patron of [[The Albert Kennedy Trust]], stating: \"Being a teenager isn't easy and it's particularly difficult for vulnerable and [[social exclusion|socially excluded]] members of our community. The Albert Kennedy Trust offers young [[LGBT|gay men, lesbians and bisexuals]] a unique and targeted service. My first task as Patron will be to support plans to extend these services across the UK, to help the increasing number of young people contacting the Trust.\" He was a [[keynote speaker]] at the International Conference on [[LGBT social movements|LGBT Human Rights]], part of the [[2006 World Outgames]], which led to the [[Declaration of Montreal]]. Alli is a patron of Oxford Pride, the annual [[Pride parade|Pride event]] in Oxfordshire, and of [[Pride London]]. He is a patron of the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]].<ref>[http://ejaf.com/about/our-patrons/ Elton John AIDS Foundation patrons]</ref>\n\nA portrait of Alli is in the [[National Portrait Gallery (United Kingdom)|National Portrait Gallery]] collection,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040926215213/http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp66357 \"Waheed Alli, Baron Alli (1964-), Television producer and politician\"], National Portrait Gallery.</ref> which contains \"portraits of the Nation's great men and women\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/about/primary-collection/learn-more-primary.php | title = National Portrait Gallery \u2013 Introduction to the Primary Collection | accessdate = 18 June 2013 | quote = \" The collections fulfil two enduring functions: to display portraits of the Nation's great men and women [and] to act as a national focus for the study and understanding of portraits and portraiture.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Alli Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure on a Cross Argent between four Suns issuing from the dexter and sinister chief and from the dexter and sinister base a Cross flory Gules each limb banded Or\n|crest = A Scarlet Ibis proper grasping in the sinister claws a Rose Gules barbed seeded slipped and leaved Or\n|supporters = On either side a Jaguar Or spotted Azure grasping in the interior forefoot a Sugar Cain Or\n|motto = Pro multis non pro paucis <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20a.htm</ref>\n|badge = Out of a Rim Or fimbriated Argent the Jaguar Heads conjoined Or spotted Azure }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Biography|Politics|LGBT}}\n*{{UK Peer links |parliament = waheed-alli/26958 |hansard = mr-waheed-alli |hansardcurr= 3639 |guardian= |publicwhip = Lord_Alli |theywork= lord_alli | record = Waheed-Alli/1834 | bbc = 26958.stm | journalisted = waheed-alli }}\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Announcement of his introduction at the House of Lords], House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 21 July 1998\n*[http://oxfordpride.org.uk Oxford Pride]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm  BBC profile], 29 November 2000.\n*[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Asians in Media profile], 2005.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html Caribbean Voice profile], October 2001.\n*[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli Knitting Circle profile]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, with press cuttings\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070403225421/http://www.akt.org.uk/patrons.htm The Albert Kennedy Trust]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[De Montfort University|Chancellor of De Montfort University]]\n  | years  = 2006\u20132015\n  | before = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|Baroness Usha Prashar]]\n  | after = [[Doreen Lawrence|Baroness Doreen Lawrence]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alli, Waheed Alli, Baron}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Guyanese descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Trinidadian descent]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:People associated with De Montfort University]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Alli\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image = Waheed Alli 2010.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|smallimage =\n|caption =\n|office          = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]]\n|1blankname      = [[Chancellor (education)#Vice-chancellor|Vice-Chancellor]]\n|1namedata       = Philip Tasker<br/>[[Dominic Shellard]]\n|term_start      = 2006\n|term_end        = 2015\n|predecessor      = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|The Baroness Prashar]]\n|successor        = [[Doreen Lawrence|The Baroness Lawrence]]\n|office2         = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member]] of the [[House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start2       = 18 July 1998<br/><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|term_end2       =\n|birthname = Waheed Alli\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1964|11|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Croydon]], London, UK\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = British\n|restingplace =\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|partner =\n|profession = Media entrepreneur\n\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n'''Waheed Alli, Baron Alli''' (born 16 November 1964) is a media entrepreneur and politician. He is the co-creator of the television series ''[[Survivor (franchise)|Survivor]]'' and has held executive positions at several television production companies including the [[Endemol Shine Group]], Carlton Television Productions (now [[ITV Studios]]), [[Planet 24]], and [[Chorion (company)|Chorion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/markets/stocks|title=Executive Profile: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently the Chief Executive of [[Silvergate Media]], Chairman of Koovs Plc and a director at [[Olga TV|Olga Productions]]. He is a member of the [[House of Lords]] in the United Kingdom, sitting as a [[life peer]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], and is described as one of only a few openly [[Islam and sexual orientation|gay Muslim]] politicians in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html|title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row|last=Alderson|first=Andrew|newspaper=Telegraph|quote= one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012|date=6 March 2010}}     \n</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/f43ebf70-ef34-11e0-918b-00144feab49a.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Waheed Alli|last=Edgecliffe-Johnson|first=Andrew|publisher=FT|quote=one of the few gay Muslims in British public life.|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIn British political terms he is considered [[British Asian|Asian]], because both of his parents are [[Indo-Caribbean]]. His mother, a nurse, is an [[Indo-Trinidadian]] from [[Trinidad and Tobago]], and his estranged father, a mechanic, is an [[Indo-Guyanese]] from [[Guyana]]. His mother was [[Hindu]] and his father [[Muslim]]; he has two brothers, who are also Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=26 April 2012|location=London}}</ref> He was named one of the 20 most important Asians in British media in 2005.<ref name=\"AIM\">[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Most Powerful Asians in British Media: Lord Waheed Alli]. ''Asians in Media''</ref> At the same time, he maintains ties with his Caribbean roots, both with other British-Guyanese politicians such as [[Valerie Amos]] and [[Trevor Phillips]], and with President [[Bharrat Jagdeo]].<ref name=\"CV\">John Muir, [http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html \"Caribbean Peers\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html |date=27 September 2007 }}, Caribbean Voice, October 2001.</ref>\n\nHe is one of a group of highly successful Guyanese people in Britain ([[Michael White (journalist)|Michael White]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' refers to them as the \"Guyanese mafia\"), which includes [[Raj Persaud]], [[Herman Ouseley]]<ref>Michael White, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2009/aug/27/balls-gcse-results-michael-white \"Balls gets his retaliation in first as annual GCSE row begins\"], ''The Guardian'', 27 August 2009.</ref> and [[David Dabydeen]], [[Cynthia Pine]], [[Keith Waithe]] and [[Rudolph Dunbar]].<ref>''Guyanese Achievers UK'' (2007) by Dindayal Vidur.</ref>\n\nAlli grew up in humble surroundings, attended [[Harris Academy South Norwood|Stanley Technical College]] in [[South Norwood]] and left school at 16 with nine [[O-levels]].<ref name=\"KC\">[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html Knitting Circle.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307031738/http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli.html |date=7 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nAlli started work as a junior researcher for a finance magazine, crediting his first success to Salem Ghayar, who hired and mentored him.  After a few years of preparing monthly reports for potential investors, he was headhunted by Save & Prosper, part of [[Robert Fleming & Co.]].<ref name=\"asianoutlook.com\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20030308075823/http://www.asianoutlook.com/lordali.htm Interviewed by Shahid]. ''The Asian Outlook''. No date; approximately 2001.</ref> Eventually he returned to his original employer, and worked his way up in the media business within [[Robert Maxwell]]'s stable of publications.  He then went to [[City of London|the City]] for a second career in [[investment banking]], through which he became wealthy.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm|title=Profile: Lord Waheed Alli|date=29 November 2000|work=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=24 May 2009}}</ref> In the mid-1980s he met [[Charlie Parsons]], who was to become his business partner as well as his life partner.<ref name=\"The Independent (Saturday 06 June 2015)\">{{cite web|title=The Party Boys|publisher=The Independent. Saturday, 6 June 2015|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-party-boys-1196428.html|website=}}</ref>\n\nAlli's third career, and the first in which he achieved public prominence, was in the television industry.  He and Parsons set up [[24 Hour Productions]], which produced ''[[The Word (TV series)|The Word]]'', \"the most talked about television programme in Britain\".<ref name=\"KC\" /> In 1992 they merged with [[Bob Geldof]]'s [[Planet Pictures]] to form [[Planet 24]].  Such was its success that it became one of the largest TV production companies in the country, and the main independent supplier to [[Channel 4]].<ref name=\"KC\" /> It was responsible for genre-breaking programmes such as ''Big Breakfast'' and ''[[Survivor (TV series)|Survivor]]''. [[Carlton Television]] bought Planet 24 in March 1999 for \u00a315 million, with Alli and Parsons prudently retaining the rights to the lucrative ''Survivor'' format. Waheed Alli became a Carlton board director before stepping down a year later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/17/religion.immigrationpolicy|title=Profiles of 10 leading British Muslims|author1=Vasagar, Jeevan |author2=Kelso, Paul |author3=James-Gregory, Sally |author4=Dodd, Vikram |date=17 June 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2003 Alli took over as chairman of the [[intellectual property|media rights]] company [[Chorion (company)|Chorion Ltd]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2871751/Hands-off-Noddy.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Hands off Noddy! | date=14 December 2003}}</ref> which owns rights to [[Enid Blyton]] and [[Agatha Christie]], and has offices beyond the UK in New York, Sydney, and Tokyo.<ref name=\"AIM\" /> He was chairman of [[Alternative Investment Market|AIM]]-listed [[ASOS.com]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8124164.stm|title=Overseas sales boost Asos profits|date=29 June 2009|work=[[bbc.co.uk]]|accessdate=29 June 2009}}</ref> and a director of [[Olga Television]], entertainer [[Paul O'Grady]]'s [[production company]]. He owns part of [[Shine Limited]], a media production company he co-founded in March 2001 with [[Elisabeth Murdoch (businesswoman)|Elisabeth Murdoch]], daughter of media-magnate [[Rupert Murdoch]]. In August 2011, he stepped down from the chairmanship of Chorion and sold half his stake in ASOS.com to start a new company called Silvergate Media.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012|reason=please provide source or remove}}\n\nHe was part of a failed \u00a3100m bid backed by [[private equity]] firm [[3i]] to buy [[Virgin Radio]] from [[SMG plc]] in 2005. In March 2007 he was appointed as SMG's non-executive director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/mar/05/smg.citynews|title=SMG makes board appointments|last=Holmwood|first=Leigh|date=5 March 2007|work=[[guardian.co.uk]]|accessdate=24 May 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAlli is a founder investor in Koovs, an Indian online retailer looking to replicate the success of Asos in the subcontinent. The company was set up in 2012 and intends to raise \u00a322m with a stock market listing on London's Aim.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b8586954-4bb5-11e3-a02f-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2kVSow9B5|author=Duncan Robinson|work=Financial Times|date=12 November 2013|title=Ex-Asos boss to list Indian venture on Aim}}</ref>\nIn december 2019 the company goes into administration after funding isn't found.  The company is bought by SGIK 3 for 250,000. Shareholders lose millions.  SGIK 3 is Lord Ali's company, set up in the weeks prior to the collapse.<ref>https://www.morningstar.co.uk/uk/news/AN_1576002908644184200/update-koovs-sold-to-sgik-3-after-falling-in-administration.aspx</ref>\n==Politics==\nAlli joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] at the persuasion of his neighbour [[Emily Thornberry]], to whom he remains close.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/19/emily-thornberry-islington-mps-expenses |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Aida |last=Edemariam |title=Right, so just what do you do all day? |date=19 May 2009 }}</ref> He is also close to [[Anji Hunter]], Director of Government Relations in [[Tony Blair]]'s first government.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Kamal |last=Ahmed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2002/jun/02/tonyblair.schools |title=Inside Labour's young boy (and girl) network |work=[[The Observer]] |date=2 June 2002 }}</ref> [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] Blair used him for years as a means to help him reach out to a younger generation (aka \"[[Youth subculture|yoof culture]]\"),<ref name=\"BBC\" /> and as such he is considered{{by whom|date=July 2013}} one of \"[[Tony's Cronies]]\".<ref name=\"CV\" /> He was made a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Alli''', of [[Norbury]] in the [[London Borough of Croydon]], on 18 July 1998<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55203 |date=22 July 1998 |page=7983}}</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Minutes and Order Paper \u2013 Minutes of Proceedings \u2013 The House of Lords] Parliament (19 July 1998). Retrieved on 15 March 2013.</ref> at the age of 34, becoming the youngest and the first openly gay peer in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. He sits on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]]. The [[BBC]] summarised his appointment as \"the antithesis of the stereotypical '[[The Establishment|establishment]]' peer \u2013 young, Asian and from the world of media and entertainment\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nAlli has used his political position to argue for [[gay rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kooth.com/|title=Kooth {{!}} Home|website=kooth.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-23}}</ref> He spearheaded the campaign to repeal [[Section 28]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |title=What was Clause 28? |first=Liz |last=Highleyman |work=Gmax |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060814052339/http://www.gmax.co.za/think/history/2006/060316-clause28.html |date=16 February 2006 |archivedate=14 August 2006 |accessdate=24 June 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He advocated lowering the [[age of consent]] for homosexuals from 18 to 16, equal to heterosexuals; this eventually became law as the [[Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000]]. It was during a heated exchange with conservative opponents, led by [[Janet Young, Baroness Young|Baroness Young]], that he informed his fellow peers that he was gay. In April 1999, he said in a speech, \"I have never been confused about my sexuality. I have been confused about the way I am treated as a result of it. The only confusion lies in the prejudice shown, some of it tonight [i.e. in the House], and much of it enshrined in the law.\"<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Hansard: Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000\">{{cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |title=HL Deb 13 April 1999 vol 599 c737 |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1999/apr/13/sexual-offences-amendment-bill#S5LV0599P0_19990413_HOL_256 |house=[[House of Lords]] |date=13 April 1999 |column=737 |speaker=Waheed Alli, Baron Alli |position=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he participated the [[2006 World Outgames#International Conference on LGBT Human Rights|International Conference on LGBT Human Rights]] adopting [[Declaration of Montreal]] and in 2009, he spearheaded an effort to repeal clauses in the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004]] which prohibited religious institutions from conducting the ceremonies on their premises.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.churchofengland.org/our-views/home-and-community-affairs/home-affairs-policy/equality-bill/lord-alli's-amendment.aspx |title=Lord Alli's amendment |publisher=[[Church of England]] }}{{dead link |date=June 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/7386492/Lord-Alli-attacks-bishops-in-gay-marriage-row.html |title=Lord Alli attacks bishops in 'gay marriage' row |last=Alderson |first=Andrew |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |quote=one of the few openly-gay Muslim politicians |accessdate=25 April 2012 |date=6 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8546827.stm |title=Church gay ceremonies ban lifted |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref> This campaign culminated in a bipartisan amendment, which became part of the [[Equality Act 2010]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Jerome |last=Taylor |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/gay-weddings-to-be-allowed-in-church-1915467.html |title=Gay weddings to be allowed in church |work=[[The Independent]] |date=3 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-16203951 |title=Peer drops fight over same-sex ceremonies in churches |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=15 December 2011 }}</ref> He influenced the draft Communications Bill in 2003.<ref name=\"AIM\" />\n\n==Other activities==\nAlli's work has been focused around gay rights, youth and education.  He is the former [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[De Montfort University]] in [[Leicester]]. He is also the President of the [[Croydon]] Youth Development Trust.<ref>[http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html Croydon Youth Development Trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060620100247/http://www.cydt.org.uk/index.html |date=20 June 2006 }}</ref> He is a patron of Skillset,<ref>[http://www.skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp Skillset Board of Patrons] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129220527/http://skillset.org/skillset/governance/article_1844_1.asp |date=29 November 2010 }}</ref> the [[Sector Skills Council]] supporting skills and training within the creative media industries.\n\nIn Autumn 2008 he won a [[Stonewall Awards|Stonewall Award]] for the category of political figure. In 2002 he became a patron of [[The Albert Kennedy Trust]], stating: \"Being a teenager isn't easy and it's particularly difficult for vulnerable and [[social exclusion|socially excluded]] members of our community. The Albert Kennedy Trust offers young [[LGBT|gay men, lesbians and bisexuals]] a unique and targeted service. My first task as Patron will be to support plans to extend these services across the UK, to help the increasing number of young people contacting the Trust.\" He was a [[keynote speaker]] at the International Conference on [[LGBT social movements|LGBT Human Rights]], part of the [[2006 World Outgames]], which led to the [[Declaration of Montreal]]. Alli is a patron of Oxford Pride, the annual [[Pride parade|Pride event]] in Oxfordshire, and of [[Pride London]]. He is a patron of the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]].<ref>[http://ejaf.com/about/our-patrons/ Elton John AIDS Foundation patrons]</ref>\n\nA portrait of Alli is in the [[National Portrait Gallery (United Kingdom)|National Portrait Gallery]] collection,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040926215213/http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp66357 \"Waheed Alli, Baron Alli (1964-), Television producer and politician\"], National Portrait Gallery.</ref> which contains \"portraits of the Nation's great men and women\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/about/primary-collection/learn-more-primary.php | title = National Portrait Gallery \u2013 Introduction to the Primary Collection | accessdate = 18 June 2013 | quote = \" The collections fulfil two enduring functions: to display portraits of the Nation's great men and women [and] to act as a national focus for the study and understanding of portraits and portraiture.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Alli Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure on a Cross Argent between four Suns issuing from the dexter and sinister chief and from the dexter and sinister base a Cross flory Gules each limb banded Or\n|crest = A Scarlet Ibis proper grasping in the sinister claws a Rose Gules barbed seeded slipped and leaved Or\n|supporters = On either side a Jaguar Or spotted Azure grasping in the interior forefoot a Sugar Cain Or\n|motto = Pro multis non pro paucis <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20a.htm</ref>\n|badge = Out of a Rim Or fimbriated Argent the Jaguar Heads conjoined Or spotted Azure }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Biography|Politics|LGBT}}\n*{{UK Peer links |parliament = waheed-alli/26958 |hansard = mr-waheed-alli |hansardcurr= 3639 |guardian= |publicwhip = Lord_Alli |theywork= lord_alli | record = Waheed-Alli/1834 | bbc = 26958.stm | journalisted = waheed-alli }}\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/980721/ldminute.htm Announcement of his introduction at the House of Lords], House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 21 July 1998\n*[http://oxfordpride.org.uk Oxford Pride]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1047062.stm  BBC profile], 29 November 2000.\n*[http://www.asiansinmedia.org/top20/2005/1.php Asians in Media profile], 2005.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927202004/http://www.caribvoice.org/Profiles/peers.html Caribbean Voice profile], October 2001.\n*[http://www.knittingcircle.org.uk/waheedalli Knitting Circle profile]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, with press cuttings\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070403225421/http://www.akt.org.uk/patrons.htm The Albert Kennedy Trust]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[De Montfort University|Chancellor of De Montfort University]]\n  | years  = 2006\u20132015\n  | before = [[Usha Prashar, Baroness Prashar|Baroness Usha Prashar]]\n  | after = [[Doreen Lawrence|Baroness Doreen Lawrence]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alli, Waheed Alli, Baron}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Guyanese descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Indo-Trinidadian descent]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:People associated with De Montfort University]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBusiness career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: december \u2192 December", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waheed_Alli,_Baron_Alli"}
{"title_page": "Charles Allen, Baron Allen of Kensington", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox politician\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Lord Allen of Kensington\n| honorific_suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|size=100%}}\n| office4          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start4      = 2 October 2013<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n| term_end4        = \n| party  = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth-date and age|4 January 1957}}\n| birth_place      = [[Lanarkshire]], Scotland<ref>{{cite news|title=The Charles Allen years |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/aug/08/citynews.television1 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=8 August 2006 |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n| nationality      = British\n| residence        = Kensington, London\n| years_active     = 1991\u2013present\n| occupation       = [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[Granada plc|Granada Group]] (1996\u20132000)<br/>[[Non-executive director|Non-exec. director]] of [[Tesco|Tesco plc]] (1999\u20132010)<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors|work=[[Tesco]]|url=http://ar2010.tescoplc.com/a-business-for-a-new-decade/board-of-directors.aspx|accessdate=1 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910051502/http://ar2010.tescoplc.com/a-business-for-a-new-decade/board-of-directors.aspx|archivedate=10 September 2011}}</ref><br/>[[Chairman|Exec. chairman]] of Granada Media plc (2000\u201304)<br/>CEO of [[ITV plc]] (2004\u201307)<br/>Chairman of [[Global Radio]] (2007\u2013present)<br/>Exec. chairman of [[EMI]] (2008\u201310)<br/>Chairman of Executive Board of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (March 2012-2015)<br/>Chairman of [[British Red Cross]] (2013\u20132014)<br/>Chairman of [[ISS A/S]] (2013\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''Charles Lamb Allen, Baron Allen of Kensington''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|size=100%|sep=,}} (born 4 January 1957) is a British businessman and broadcaster, and the chairman of [[Global Radio]],  [[2 Sisters Food Group]], ISS and Advisory chairman at [[Moelis & Company]]. Lord Allen was chief executive of [[Granada plc|Granada Group]] from 1996 to 2000, executive chairman of Granada Media plc from 2000 to 2004, chief executive of [[ITV plc]] from its formation in 2004 until 2007, and chairman of the music company [[EMI]]. He was chairman of Endemol, a non-executive director of Tesco plc and Virgin Media. In March 2012, he was appointed by [[Ed Miliband]], the leader of the Labour Party, to the position of chairman of the executive board of the party. He has been chairman of the [[British Red Cross]].\n\n==Education==\nAllen was educated at Bellshill Academy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/dec/09/citynews.television|title=Charles Allen: a survivor in the minefield of the media|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Jane Martinson|date=9 December 2005|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref> a state school in the town of [[Bellshill]] in [[North Lanarkshire]] in central Scotland. He did not attend university, and says of his life, \"It's been an amazing journey considering I left school at 17 with no job to go to\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.director.co.uk/2-2958-lord-allen-global-radio-chairman-mentor-tormentor|title=Global Radio chairman Lord Allen on Brexit, boardrooms and the BBC|work=Director.co.uk|author=Richard Dunnett|date=5 January 2016|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nAllen joined [[Granada plc]] in 1991, originally as CEO of [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]], before becoming Group Chief Executive in 1996. During his time at Granada, he was instrumental in the takeover of [[Forte Group]] for \u00a33.9 billion in 1996, and the takeovers of [[London Weekend Television|LWT]] and [[Yorkshire-Tyne Tees Television]] in 1994 and 1999 respectively. In 2001 Granada Group merged with Compass to form Granada Compass, then demerged into Granada Media plc and Compass Group. He remained with Granada when the two companies demerged, and became Executive Chairman of Granada plc in 2001. When Granada merged with [[Carlton Communications]] in 2004 to form ITV plc, Allen became the new company's [[Chief executive officer|Chief Executive]].<ref>[http://www.itvplc.com/itv/about/board/#allen ITV plc] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128182216/http://www.itvplc.com/itv/about/board/#allen |date=28 November 2006 }}, accessed 6 July 2006.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Allen stepped down after fifteen years with the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jan/16/itv-emi-charles-allen|title=Charles Allen: a survivor in the minefield of the media|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Other interests==\nFrom 2006 to 2008, Allen was previously Chief Advisor to the British Home Office. He has also been a senior advisor to Goldman Sachs Private Equity, non-executive director of [[Endemol]] and [[Virgin Media]] and executive Chairman of [[EMI]].<ref name=PARLIAMENT>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-allen-of-kensington/4304|website=UK Parliament|title=Lord Allen of Kensington}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, he is Chairman of ISS Group, [[2 Sisters Food Group]] and [[Global Group]] \u2014 which owns Capital, Heart, Classic FM, LBC, Radio X and Gold \u2014 as well as advisory Chairman of [[Moelis & Company]].\n\nAllen chaired the [[2002 Commonwealth Games]]. He was a member of the [[2012_Summer_Olympics|London 2012]] Olympic bid team and a Director of the London Organising Committee of the Olympic Games and Paralympic Games. He was also Mayor of the [[Olympic Park, London|Olympic Village]].\n\n==Honours==\nAllen was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2003 New Year Honours]] \"for services to the [[2002 Commonwealth Games|XVII Commonwealth Games]]\".<ref name=\"LG 31 December 2002\">{{London Gazette |issue=56797 |date=31 December 2002 |page=7 |supp=y }}</ref> He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2012 New Year Honours]] \"for services to the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]] and [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]]\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60009 |date=31 December 2011 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60245 |date=21 August 2012 |page=16079}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 2013, it was announced that Allen was to become a Labour peer in a list of new appointments to the House of Lords.<ref>{{cite news|last=Craig |first=Jon |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1123153/jcb-boss-sir-anthony-bamford-made-tory-peer |title=JCB Boss Sir Anthony Bamford Made Tory Peer |publisher=Sky News |date=2013-08-01 |accessdate=2013-11-01}}</ref> He was created a [[Life Peer]] on 2 October 2013 taking the title '''Baron Allen of Kensington''', of [[Kensington]] in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60648 |date=4 October 2013 |page=19575}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Allen was appointed as a member of the Lords Communications Committee.<ref name=PARLIAMENT />\n\nIn 2005 he was awarded the Freedom of the City of Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news|title=Business Diary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/citydiary/2923753/Business-diary.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=13 October 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAllen lives in Kensington with his partner of more than 20 years, Michael, an architect.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/lord-allen-putting-an-obsessive-attitude-to-work-and-making-it-pay-9195868.html|title=Lord Allen: Putting an obsessive attitude to work \u2013 and making it pay|work=[[The Independent]]|date=16 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=Chief Executive of [[ITV plc]]|before=None|after=[[Michael Grade]]<br><small>(Executive chairman)</small>|years=2004\u201306}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{International Emmy Directorate Award}}\n{{Global Radio}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Charles}}\n[[Category:ITV people]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Scotland]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Ed Miliband]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:International Emmy Directorate Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox politician\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Lord Allen of Kensington\n| honorific_suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|size=100%}}\n| office4          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start4      = 2 October 2013<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n| term_end4        = \n| party  = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth-date and age|4 January 1957}}\n| birth_place      = [[Lanarkshire]], Scotland<ref>{{cite news|title=The Charles Allen years |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/aug/08/citynews.television1 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=8 August 2006 |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n| nationality      = British\n| residence        = Kensington, London\n| years_active     = 1991\u2013present\n| occupation       = [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[Granada plc|Granada Group]] (1996\u20132000)<br/>[[Non-executive director|Non-exec. director]] of [[Tesco|Tesco plc]] (1999\u20132010)<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors|work=[[Tesco]]|url=http://ar2010.tescoplc.com/a-business-for-a-new-decade/board-of-directors.aspx|accessdate=1 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910051502/http://ar2010.tescoplc.com/a-business-for-a-new-decade/board-of-directors.aspx|archivedate=10 September 2011}}</ref><br/>[[Chairman|Exec. chairman]] of Granada Media plc (2000\u201304)<br/>CEO of [[ITV plc]] (2004\u201307)<br/>Chairman of [[Global Radio]] (2007\u2013present)<br/>Exec. chairman of [[EMI]] (2008\u201310)<br/>Chairman of Executive Board of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (March 2012-2015)<br/>Chairman of [[British Red Cross]] (2013\u20132014)<br/>Chairman of [[ISS A/S]] (2013\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''Charles Lamb Allen, Baron Allen of Kensington''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|size=100%|sep=,}} (born 4 January 1957) is a British businessman and broadcaster, and the chairman of [[Global Radio]],  [[2 Sisters Food Group]], ISS and Advisory chairman at [[Moelis & Company]]. Lord Allen was chief executive of [[Granada plc|Granada Group]] from 1996 to 2000, executive chairman of Granada Media plc from 2000 to 2004, chief executive of [[ITV plc]] from its formation in 2004 until 2007, and chairman of the music company [[EMI]]. He was chairman of Endemol, a non-executive director of Tesco plc and Virgin Media. In March 2012, he was appointed by [[Ed Miliband]], the leader of the Labour Party, to the position of chairman of the executive board of the party. He has been chairman of the [[British Red Cross]].\n\n==Education==\nAllen was educated at Bellshill Academy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/dec/09/citynews.television|title=Charles Allen: a survivor in the minefield of the media|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Jane Martinson|date=9 December 2005|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref> a state school in the town of [[Bellshill]] in [[North Lanarkshire]] in central Scotland. He did not attend university, and says of his life, \"It's been an amazing journey considering I left school at 17 with no job to go to\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.director.co.uk/2-2958-lord-allen-global-radio-chairman-mentor-tormentor|title=Global Radio chairman Lord Allen on Brexit, boardrooms and the BBC|work=Director.co.uk|author=Richard Dunnett|date=5 January 2016|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nAllen joined [[Granada plc]] in 1991, originally as CEO of [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]], before becoming Group Chief Executive in 1996. During his time at Granada, he was instrumental in the takeover of [[Forte Group]] for \u00a33.9 billion in 1996, and the takeovers of [[London Weekend Television|LWT]] and [[Yorkshire-Tyne Tees Television]] in 1994 and 1999 respectively. In 2001 Granada Group merged with Compass to form Granada Compass, then demerged into Granada Media plc and Compass Group. He remained with Granada when the two companies demerged, and became Executive Chairman of Granada plc in 2001. When Granada merged with [[Carlton Communications]] in 2004 to form ITV plc, Allen became the new company's [[Chief executive officer|Chief Executive]].<ref>[http://www.itvplc.com/itv/about/board/#allen ITV plc] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128182216/http://www.itvplc.com/itv/about/board/#allen |date=28 November 2006 }}, accessed 6 July 2006.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Allen stepped down after fifteen years with the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jan/16/itv-emi-charles-allen|title=Charles Allen: a survivor in the minefield of the media|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Other interests==\nFrom 2006 to 2008, Allen was previously Chief Advisor to the British Home Office. He has also been a Senior Advisor to Goldman Sachs Private Equity, non-executive director of [[Endemol]] and [[Virgin Media]] and executive Chairman of [[EMI]].<ref name=PARLIAMENT>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-allen-of-kensington/4304|website=UK Parliament|title=Lord Allen of Kensington}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, he is Chairman of ISS Group, [[2 Sisters Food Group]] and [[Global Group]] \u2014 which owns Capital, Heart, Classic FM, LBC, Radio X and Gold \u2014 as well as advisory Chairman of [[Moelis & Company]].\n\nAllen chaired the [[2002 Commonwealth Games]]. He was a member of the [[2012_Summer_Olympics|London 2012]] Olympic bid team and a Director of the London Organising Committee of the Olympic Games and Paralympic Games. He was also Mayor of the [[Olympic Park, London|Olympic Village]].\n\n==Honours==\nAllen was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2003 New Year Honours]] \"for services to the [[2002 Commonwealth Games|XVII Commonwealth Games]]\".<ref name=\"LG 31 December 2002\">{{London Gazette |issue=56797 |date=31 December 2002 |page=7 |supp=y }}</ref> He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2012 New Year Honours]] \"for services to the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]] and [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]]\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60009 |date=31 December 2011 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60245 |date=21 August 2012 |page=16079}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 2013, it was announced that Allen was to become a Labour peer in a list of new appointments to the House of Lords.<ref>{{cite news|last=Craig |first=Jon |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1123153/jcb-boss-sir-anthony-bamford-made-tory-peer |title=JCB Boss Sir Anthony Bamford Made Tory Peer |publisher=Sky News |date=2013-08-01 |accessdate=2013-11-01}}</ref> He was created a [[Life Peer]] on 2 October 2013 taking the title '''Baron Allen of Kensington''', of [[Kensington]] in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60648 |date=4 October 2013 |page=19575}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Allen was appointed as a member of the Lords Communications Committee.<ref name=PARLIAMENT />\n\nIn 2005 he was awarded the Freedom of the City of Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news|title=Business Diary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/citydiary/2923753/Business-diary.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=13 October 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAllen lives in Kensington with his partner of more than 20 years, Michael, an architect.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/lord-allen-putting-an-obsessive-attitude-to-work-and-making-it-pay-9195868.html|title=Lord Allen: Putting an obsessive attitude to work \u2013 and making it pay|work=[[The Independent]]|date=16 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=Chief Executive of [[ITV plc]]|before=None|after=[[Michael Grade]]<br><small>(Executive chairman)</small>|years=2004\u201306}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{International Emmy Directorate Award}}\n{{Global Radio}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Charles}}\n[[Category:ITV people]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Scotland]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Ed Miliband]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:International Emmy Directorate Award]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther interests:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: a Senior Advisor \u2192 a senior advisor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Allen,_Baron_Allen_of_Kensington"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Adonis\n|caption          = Lord Adonis in 2019\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}}\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Adonis crop 2.jpg\n|office2          = [[Secretary of State for Transport]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start2      = 5 June 2009\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor2     = [[Geoff Hoon]]\n|successor2       = [[Philip Hammond]]\n|office3          = [[Minister of State for Transport]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start3      = 3 October 2008\n|term_end3        = 5 June 2009\n|predecessor3     = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n|successor3       = [[Sadiq Khan]]\n|office5          = [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Schools]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Tony Blair]]<br/>[[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start5      = 10 May 2005\u00a0\n|term_end5        = 3 October 2008\n|predecessor5     = [[Geoffrey Filkin, Baron Filkin|The Lord Filkin]]\n|successor5       = [[Sarah McCarthy-Fry]]\n|office7          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start7      = 16 May 2005<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|office           = [[European Movement UK|Vice Chairman of the European Movement]]\n|term_start       = 15 January 2019\n|term_end         = \n|vicepresident    = [[Kenneth Clarke]]<br />[[Joyce Quin, Baroness Quin|Joyce Quin]]\n|president        = [[Michael Heseltine]]\n| 1blankname      = Chairman\n| 1namedata       = [[Stephen Dorrell]]\n|predecessor      = [[Richard Corbett]]\n|successor        = \n|birth_name       = Andreas Adonis\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|2|22}}\n|birth_place      = [[Hampstead]], [[London]], England<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=2CHB8L6ej8SGOfVlyuF%2BLQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=18 April 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] {{small|(1995\u20132015, 2017\u2013present)}}\n|otherparty       = [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic]] {{small|(1985\u20131988)}}<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] {{small|(1988\u20131995)}}\n|nationality      = {{flagicon|UK}} [[British people|British]]\n|profession       = [[Journalist]]\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Kathryn Davies<br />|1994|2015|end=div}}\n|children         = 2 \n|alma_mater       = [[Keble College, Oxford]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Christ Church, Oxford]] ([[DPhil]])\n|website          = {{url|andrewadonis.org/|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (born '''Andreas Adonis'''; 22 February 1963)<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\">{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/publicservices/story/0,11032,1602671,00.html |title=The Guardian profile: Andrew Adonis |date=28 October 2005 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |author=Will Woodward |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and journalist who served in [[HM Government]] for five years in the [[Blair ministry]] and the [[Brown ministry]]. He served as [[Secretary of State for Transport]] from 2009 to 2010, and as [[National Infrastructure Commission|Chairman of the National Infrastructure Commission]] from 2015 to 2017.\n\nAdonis began his career as an [[academic]] at [[Oxford University]], before becoming a journalist at the ''[[Financial Times]]'' and later ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /><ref name=\"DfESprofile\" /><ref name=\"BBCstory\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4530433.stm |title=Adviser Adonis made a minister |date=10 May 2005 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Adonis was appointed by Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] to be an advisor at the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]], specialising in constitutional and educational policy, in 1998. He was later promoted to become the Head of the Policy Unit from 2001 until being created a [[life peer]] in 2005, when he was appointed [[Department for Education|Minister of State for Education]] in [[HM Government]].<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /><ref name=\"DfESprofile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/aboutus/whoswho/ministersinfo.shtml|title=Department for Education and Skills Ministerial Team |accessdate=30 March 2007 |publisher=Department for Education and Skills |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401112255/http://www.dfes.gov.uk/aboutus/whoswho/ministersinfo.shtml#hughes |archivedate=1 April 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> He remained in that role when [[Gordon Brown]] became Prime Minister in 2007, before becoming [[Department for Transport|Minister of State for Transport]] in 2008. In 2009, he was promoted to [[Cabinet (UK)|the Cabinet]] as [[Secretary of State for Transport|Transport Secretary]], a position he held until 2010.<ref name=\"nationalarchives1\">[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100513070028/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/commandpaper/ High Speed Rail \u2013 Command Paper]. Department for Transport, 11 March 2010, {{ISBN|9780101782722}}</ref>\n\nAdonis has worked for a number of [[think tank]]s, is a board member of [[Policy Network]] and is the author or co-author of several books, including several studies of the [[Social structure of the United Kingdom|British class system]], the rise and fall of the [[Poll tax (Great Britain)|Community Charge]], and the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] [[House of Lords]]. He has also co-edited a collection of essays on [[Roy Jenkins]]. Like Jenkins, Adonis speaks with [[Rhotacism (speech impediment)|rhotacism]].\n\nAdonis is a strong supporter and advocate of the [[European Union]] and a vocal opponent of [[Brexit]]. Following the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on UK membership]] of the [[European Union]], he then became a key campaigner for a [[People's Vote|second referendum]] on British departure from the EU.\n\n==Family and education==\nAdonis's father, Nikos, emigrated from [[Greek Cypriot|Cyprus]] as a teenager, becoming a waiter in [[London]], where he met Adonis's English mother.<ref name=\"Timesonline\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article532497.ece |title=Mother: why I left minister as a toddler |date=12 June 2005 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |work=The Times |location=London |first=Robert |last=Winnett}}</ref> His mother left the family when he was three, and she has had no communication with him since.<ref name=\"Timesonline\" /> Shortly thereafter Adonis and his sister were placed in care, because their father was working long hours and was not able to cope with sole parental responsibilities. Adonis lived in a council children's home until the age of 11, when he was awarded a [[local education authority]] grant to attend [[Kingham Hill School]], a boarding school in [[Oxfordshire]].<ref name=\"Financialtimes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b9ffc3b8-a1a5-11db-8bc1-0000779e2340.html |title=This is not a wacky utopia |date=17 January 2007 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |author=Ben Hall |work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nAdonis went up to [[Keble College, Oxford]], where he graduated with a first-class Bachelor of Arts degree in Modern History in 1984.<ref>''The Record'', page 21. Keble College, 1984</ref> He pursued further studies at [[Oxford University|Oxford]] receiving a <!-- Not a PhD at Oxford. -->[[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate]] with a thesis entitled, ''The political role of the British peerage in the Third Reform Act system, c. 1885\u20131914'' at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], before being elected a [[fellow]] in History and Politics at [[Nuffield College, Oxford|Nuffield College]].<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /><ref name=\"Financialtimes\" />\n\nFrom 1991 to 1996, he was an education and industry correspondent at the ''[[Financial Times]]'', eventually becoming their public policy editor.<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /> In 1996, he moved to ''[[The Observer]]'' to work as a political columnist, leader writer and editor.<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" />\n\n==Early political career==\nFrom 1987 until 1991, Adonis served as an [[Oxford City Council]]lor for the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] and later the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], representing the [[Ward (country subdivision)|North Ward]].<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /> In 1994, he was selected by the Liberal Democrats as their [[prospective parliamentary candidate]] for the [[Westbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Westbury constituency]], but he resigned after 18 months. In the following year he joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref name=\"Lab1995\">{{cite news |title=Profile: Andrew Adonis |work=BBC News |date=9 May 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/frontpage/4530847.stm |accessdate=22 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-to-late 1990s he was politically active for Labour in [[Islington North]], the constituency represented by [[Jeremy Corbyn]], and was selected as Labour candidate to contest St George's Ward for [[Islington London Borough Council]] in 1998. He withdrew from the process before the election, however, upon being offered a position in the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]] as a constitutional and educational policy advisor in 1997. He remained in this role until 2001, when he was promoted to become Head of the Policy Unit.\n\nOn 16 May 2005, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Adonis''', ''of [[Camden Town]] in the [[London Borough of Camden]]'',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57644 |page=6547 |date=19 May 2005}}</ref> making it possible for him to serve as a [[Minister (government)|government minister]], representing it in the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://education.independent.co.uk/schools/article221029.ece |title=Adonis will now be accountable |date=12 May 2005 |accessdate=3 April 2007 |work=[[The Independent]] |location=London}}{{dead link |date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n==HM Government==\n[[File:Andrew Adonis at Council House, Bristol on 5 January 2011.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Adonis at [[Council House, Bristol]] in 2011]]\nLord Adonis became the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State |Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Education]] in the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]], which was later renamed the [[Department for Children, Schools and Families]]. He was closely involved in the [[London Challenge]].<ref name=JRFLondonChallenge>{{cite web |title=Implementing the London Challenge |url=http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/Implementing%20the%20London%20Challenge%20-%20final_0.pdf |website=Institute for Government |publisher=Joseph Rowntree Foundation |accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nHaving been the architect of the [[Academy (English school)|academies policy]] in the Policy Unit, Adonis was also able to be the driving force in Government behind the programme, which replaced failing and under-performing comprehensive schools with all-ability, independently managed academies, run on a not-for-profit basis. By the time he left the Department in October 2008, 133 academies were open and 300 more were in the pipeline. These early academies were very successful.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} Government policy later sought to force academisation of all schools, moving them from outside Local Authority control. This policy has now ceased. Within this later wave of academies, evidence on performance compared to local authority schools is mixed, but on the whole suggests there is no substantial difference in performance.<ref>[https://fullfact.org/education/academies-and-maintained-schools-what-do-we-know/ Academies and maintained schools: what do we know?] Fullfact.org</ref>\n\nAdonis also encouraged [[state school]]s to adopt practices of the [[private sector]] and generally believed in giving individual schools more independence and autonomy from central government and the [[local education authority|local education authorities]]. Although he voted against schools having more independent authority in the houses of parliament in 2006. His criticism of under-performing [[comprehensive schools|comprehensives]] made him unpopular with some trade union members and some on the Labour Party's left-wing. In 2006 Adonis supported the conversion of some independent schools under financial duress into state academies, portrayed at the time as a new style of [[direct grant grammar school]]s although not selective.<ref name=independent-20061019>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/ministers-in-secret-talks-to-bring-back-direct-grant-schools-420674.html |title=Ministers in secret talks to bring back direct grant schools |last=Garner |first=Richard |newspaper=The Independent |date=19 October 2006 |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref> Adonis was also popular with some [[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition]] politicians, in particular the then [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] education spokesman [[Michael Gove]], who once declared, \"We are on the same page as Andrew Adonis.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Academy fears on Adonis reshuffle |work=BBC News | date = 6 October 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7654337.stm | accessdate = 15 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs Tony Blair's head of policy, Adonis was regarded as the architect of [[Tuition fees in the United Kingdom|tuition fees]] in 2004 \u2013 a policy he criticised and disowned 13 years later.<ref>{{cite news | title = I put up tuition fees. It's now clear they have to be scrapped | publisher = Guardian News | date = 7 July 2017 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/jul/07/tuition-fees-scrapped-debts-graduates-andrew-adonis | accessdate = 29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHaving initially kept his position when [[Gordon Brown]] became [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], Adonis was reshuffled to the [[Department for Transport]] on 3 October 2008, to become [[Minister of State]]. In May 2009, while reviewing potential cycle \"super highways\" with [[Kulveer Ranger]] and then-London Mayor [[Boris Johnson]], the group had a narrow escape when a passing lorry's back door \"suddenly flew open, dragged a parked car into the street and smashed into another \u2013 just feet from the group\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/23/boris-cycling|title=Boris Johnson's 'near-death experience' with lorry caught on camera|work=The Guardian|accessdate=26 February 2010 | location=London | first=Toby | last=Helm | date=23 May 2009}}</ref> On 5 June 2009, Adonis was promoted to the [[Cabinet (UK)|Cabinet]] as [[Secretary of State for Transport]] and was sworn a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. In this role, he pioneered the plan for [[High Speed 2]], the proposed high-speed railway line from [[Euston railway station|London]] to [[Birmingham Curzon Street railway station|Birmingham]] and the north of England. The plan was published shortly before the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 election]], and has since been adopted and taken forward, largely unchanged, by subsequent governments. In July 2015, Adonis was appointed a non-executive director to HS2 Board Ltd.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jul/16/lord-adonis-joins-board-of-hs2-project Lord Adonis joins board of HS2 project] ''The Guardian'', 16 July 2015</ref>\n\nAdonis planned and announced the electrification of the [[Great Western Main Line]] from [[Paddington railway station|London Paddington]] to [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station|Bristol]], [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff]] and [[Swansea railway station|Swansea]], and the electrification of lines in [[North West England]] from [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester]] to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool]] and Manchester to [[Preston railway station|Preston]]. This electrification programme, except for the Cardiff to Swansea section of the Great Western, was taken forward by the coalition government.\n\nAdonis was a key figure in the aftermath of the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], which produced a [[hung parliament]]. He was reputed to favour a [[Lib\u2013Lab pact|Lib\u2013Lab deal]] and, given his SDP background, was a member of Labour's negotiating team that [[2010 United Kingdom government formation|attempted to form an administration]] with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. After the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Liberal Democrats formed a coalition government with the Conservative Party]], Adonis stepped down from frontline politics.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7127791.ece |title=Adonis devised original coalition plan |work=The Times |date=16 May 2010 | location=London | first=Robert | last=Watts}}</ref>\n\nAdonis later returned to active politics in 2012, as part of [[Ed Miliband]]'s [[Shadow Cabinet]] reshuffle. He worked with former Shadow Business Secretary [[Chuka Umunna]] on crafting Labour's industrial strategy, and previously took up the role of Shadow Minister for Infrastructure in the House of Lords,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/29/lord-adonis-quits-as-theresa-may-infrastructure-tsar-over-brexit www.theguardian.com]</ref> and overseeing the Armitt Review looking at future infrastructure plans for the Labour Party.<ref>[https://www.policyforum.labour.org.uk/uploads/editor/files/The_Armitt_Review_Final_Report.pdf ''Armitt Review'']</ref>\n\n==Subsequent career==\nIn July 2010, Adonis became the director of the [[Institute for Government]], an independent charity with cross-party support and [[Whitehall]] governance working to improve government effectiveness.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/news/article/144/andrew-adonis-announced-as-new-director-of-the-institute-for-government |title=Andrew Adonis announced as new Director of the Institute for Government.' |date=15 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318010831/http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/news/article/144/andrew-adonis-announced-as-new-director-of-the-institute-for-government |archivedate=18 March 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Adonis left the Institute for Government in January 2012, to become Chair of [[Progress (organisation)|Progress]], an internal Labour Party organisation.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120111075549/http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/news/article/270/institute-for-government-appoints-rt-hon-peter-riddell-as-director Institute For Government Appoints Rt Hon Peter Riddell As Director]. instituteforgovernment.org.uk. 17 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/01/11/andrew-adonis-becomes-new-progress-chair/ Andrew Adonis becomes new Progress chair | Progress | News and debate from the progressive community] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318154809/http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/01/11/andrew-adonis-becomes-new-progress-chair/ |date=18 March 2012 }}. Progressonline.org.uk (11 January 2012). Retrieved 19 October 2013.</ref> Having been appointed President of the Independent Academies Association, in 2012, Adonis was also admitted as a [[Liveryman]] ''[[Honoris Causa]]'' of the [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers]], one of the major charitable promoters of [[Academy (English school)|academies]].<ref>[http://www.iaa.uk.net/ www.iaa.uk.net]. http://www.iaa.uk.net (5 July 2013). Retrieved 19 October 2013.</ref>\n\nLord Adonis is a [[Trustee]] of [[Teach First]], the charity which recruits graduates to teach in state schools, as well as a Trustee of the vocational education charity [[Edge (educational foundation)|Edge]], and a [[Governor]] of the Baker-Dearing Trust, which supports the establishment of University Technical Colleges, technical schools for 14- to 18-year-olds.<ref>[http://www.edge.co.uk/about-edge/our-people Our people] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501083155/http://www.edge.co.uk/about-edge/our-people |date=1 May 2012 }}. Edge.co.uk. Retrieved 19 October 2013.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130315182102/http://www.teachfirst.org.uk/AboutUs/ourpeople.aspx Our People]. teachfirst.org.uk</ref> He has been a Director of RM Plc since October 2011. His book on education reform \u2013 ''Education, Education, Education'' \u2013 was published by [[Biteback]] in September 2012.<ref>[https://www.bitebackpublishing.com/books/education-education-education-paperback Education, Education, Education Reforming] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017122625/https://www.bitebackpublishing.com/books/education-education-education-paperback |date=17 October 2013 }}. bitebackpublishing.com</ref> In November 2014, he was appointed visiting professor at [[King's College London]].<ref>[http://www.kcl.ac.uk/newsevents/news/newsrecords/2014/November/Lord-Adonis-appointed-Visiting-Professor.aspx www.kcl.ac.uk]. King's College London. Retrieved 23 November 2014.</ref>\n\nAdonis considered standing<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/04/andrew-adonis-tale-two-cities-reality-london|title=Andrew Adonis: \"The tale of two cities is the reality of London\"|work=New Statesman|accessdate=6 May 2016 | location=London | first=Tim | last=Wigmore | date=30 April 2015}}</ref> to be Labour's candidate for [[Mayor of London]] in [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]], but ended his putative campaign in February 2015, endorsing [[Tessa Jowell]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/i-wont-run-for-mayor-dame-tessa-jowell-is-the-best-candidate-says-lord-adonis-10056054.html|title=I won't run for mayor \u2013 Dame Tessa Jowell is the best candidate, says Lord Adonis|work=London Evening Standard|accessdate=6 May 2016 | location=London | first=Joe | last=Murphy | date=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, he resigned the Labour Party whip in the House of Lords to sit as a [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|non-affiliated Peer]] and lead a newly created [[National Infrastructure Commission]] (NIC). However, he resigned from the NIC in December 2017 because of the HM Government's approach to [[Brexit]], saying the UK was \"hurtling towards the EU's emergency exit with no credible plan for the future of British trade and European co-operation\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42514117|title=Adonis quits role with Brexit attack|date=29 December 2017|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\nAdonis said he planned to oppose \"relentlessly\" the government's [[European Union (Withdrawal) Bill]] in the House of Lords.  In his resignation letter, he wrote that, as well as Brexit, the recent decision to end the [[InterCity East Coast]] [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|rail franchise]] three years early, at a cost of hundreds of millions of pounds, would also have forced him to quit. He also claimed that  \"taking us back into Europe will become the mission of our children's generation\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Lord Adonis quits government role in stinging letter|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42515637|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=BBC News|date=29 December 2017}}</ref> On 15 April 2018 Adonis attended the launch event of the [[People's Vote]], a campaign group calling for a public vote on the final [[Brexit]] deal between the UK and the European Union.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Brexit: 'People's Vote' campaign group launched | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43774200 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 15 April 2018 | access-date = 17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 European Parliament election]], Adonis was second on Labour's [[party list]] for [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foster |first1=Matt |title=Anti-Brexit peer Lord Adonis among candidates as Labour unveils MEP hopefuls |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/foreign-affairs/brexit/news/103344/anti-brexit-peer-lord-adonis-among-candidates-labour |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Politicshome.com |date=19 April 2019}}</ref> but was not elected. Labour's share of the vote was 6.5% (a fall of 7.3% relative to the 2014 result) and the party lost its only MEP in the region.\n\nAdonis was a participant at the 30 May - 2 June 2019 [[Bilderberg Meeting]] at [[Montreux]], Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bilderbergmeetings.org/press/press-release/participants|title=Participants|author=|date=|website=bilderbergmeetings.org|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAdonis was formerly married to Kathryn Davies,<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /> who was once a student of his;<ref name=\"Timesonline\"/> the couple had two children.<ref name=\"Financialtimes\" /> Adonis and Davies divorced in 2015. In a profile<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrew-adonis-we-must-spell-it-out-now-labour-is-a-remain-party-a4137381.html|title=Andrew Adonis: We must spell it out now, Labour is a Remain party|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=8 May 2019 | location=London | first=Julian| last=Glover| date=8 May 2019}}</ref> in the ''Evening Standard'' in 2019, the journalist [[Julian Glover (journalist)|Julian Glover]] reported that Adonis was gay.<ref>{{cite news |title=Andrew Adonis: We must spell it out now, Labour is a Remain party |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrew-adonis-we-must-spell-it-out-now-labour-is-a-remain-party-a4137381.html |work=Evening Standard |date=8 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book | title=Roy Jenkins: A Retrospective | author=Andrew Adonis (Editor), Keith Thomas (Editor) | id=| year = 2004}}\n*{{cite book | title=A Class Act: Myth of Britain's Classless Society| author=Andrew Adonis, [[Stephen Pollard]] | id=| year = 1997}}\n*{{cite book | title= Failure in British government : the politics of the poll tax | author=David Butler, Andrew Adonis & [[Tony Travers]] | id=| year = 1994}}\n*{{cite book | title=Making Aristocracy Work: The Peerage and the Political System in Britain, | author=Andrew Adonis | id=| year = 1993}}\n*{{cite book | title=Subsidiarity: no panacea | author=Andrew Adonis (Editor), [[Andrew Tyrie]] (Editor) | id=| year = 1989}}\n*{{cite book | title=The Thatcher-Reagan Decade in Perspective | author=Andrew Adonis (Editor), [[Tim Hames]] (Editor) | id=| year = 1994}}\n*{{cite book | title=Education Education Education: Reforming England's Schools | author=Andrew Adonis| id=| year=2012}}\n*{{Cite book | title=5 Days in May: The Coalition and Beyond | last=Adonis | first=Andrew | year=2013 | publisher=Biteback Publishing | isbn=978-1849545662 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/5daysinmaycoalit0000adon }}\n*{{Cite book | title=Saving Britain: How We Must Change To Prosper In Europe  | author=[[Will Hutton]], Andrew Adonis | year=2018 | publisher=Abacus: Little, Brown Book Group, London | isbn = 978-1408711224}}\n*{{Cite book | title=Half In Half Out: Prime Ministers on Europe | author=Andrew Adonis (editor) | year=2018 | publisher=Biteback Publishing | isbn = 978-1785904349}}\n\n===Articles===\n* [[Ben Pimlott]] ''The Queen: A Biography of Elizabeth II'' \u2013 book review, 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* ''Our progressives only look dead'' (prospects for a revival of progressivism in the United Kingdom), 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Christopher Booker]] and [[Richard North (blogger)|Richard North]] ''The Castle of Lies: Why Britain Must Get Out of Europe'' \u2013 book review, 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Anthony Barnett (writer)|Anthony Barnett]] ''This Time: Our Constitutional Revolution'' \u2013 book review, 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Shirley Williams]] ''Climbing the Bookshelves: the Autobiography'' \u2013 book review, 2009, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Roy Hattersley]] ''David Lloyd George: the Great Outsider'' \u2013 book review, 2010, Andrew Adonis\n* [[David Laws]] ''22 Days in May: The Birth of the Lib Dem-Conservative Coalition'' \u2013 book review, 2010, Andrew Adonis\n* Chris Bowers ''Nick Clegg: the Biography'' \u2013 book review, 2011, Andrew Adonis\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK Peer links | parliament = lords/lord-adonis/3743 | hansard = mr-andrew-adonis | hansardcurr = 4852 | guardian = | publicwhip = Lord_Adonis | theywork = lord_adonis | record = Andrew-Adonis/1457 | bbc = 19424.stm | journalisted = }}\n*[http://thepeerage.com/p14950.htm#i149491 \"Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis\"] at ''The Peerage''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120324153353/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/19424 www.parliament.uk]\n*[https://www.andrewadonistour.org/ Official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Timms]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Education|Minister of State for Education]]|years=2005\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Knight]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rosie Winterton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Transport]]|years=2008\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sadiq Khan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Geoff Hoon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Transport]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Philip Hammond]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People's Vote}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Minister of State for Transport}}\n{{British special advisers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adonis, Andrew Adonis, Baron}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kingham Hill School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keble College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of Oxford City Council]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:English political writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Keble College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Nuffield College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Advocates of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Transport (UK)]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Tony Blair]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Gay academics]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Rhotacism (speech impediment)|Rhotacism.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Adonis\n|caption          = Lord Adonis in 2019\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}}\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Adonis crop 2.jpg\n|office2          = [[Secretary of State for Transport]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start2      = 5 June 2009\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor2     = [[Geoff Hoon]]\n|successor2       = [[Philip Hammond]]\n|office3          = [[Minister of State for Transport]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start3      = 3 October 2008\n|term_end3        = 5 June 2009\n|predecessor3     = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n|successor3       = [[Sadiq Khan]]\n|office5          = [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Schools]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Tony Blair]]<br/>[[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start5      = 10 May 2005\u00a0\n|term_end5        = 3 October 2008\n|predecessor5     = [[Geoffrey Filkin, Baron Filkin|The Lord Filkin]]\n|successor5       = [[Sarah McCarthy-Fry]]\n|office7          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start7      = 16 May 2005<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|office           = [[European Movement UK|Vice Chairman of the European Movement]]\n|term_start       = 15 January 2019\n|term_end         = \n|vicepresident    = [[Kenneth Clarke]]<br />[[Joyce Quin, Baroness Quin|Joyce Quin]]\n|president        = [[Michael Heseltine]]\n| 1blankname      = Chairman\n| 1namedata       = [[Stephen Dorrell]]\n|predecessor      = [[Richard Corbett]]\n|successor        = \n|birth_name       = Andreas Adonis\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|2|22}}\n|birth_place      = [[Hampstead]], [[London]], England<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=2CHB8L6ej8SGOfVlyuF%2BLQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=18 April 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] {{small|(1995\u20132015, 2017\u2013present)}}\n|otherparty       = [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic]] {{small|(1985\u20131988)}}<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] {{small|(1988\u20131995)}}\n|nationality      = {{flagicon|UK}} [[British people|British]]\n|profession       = [[Journalist]]\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Kathryn Davies<br />|1994|2015|end=div}}\n|children         = 2 \n|alma_mater       = [[Keble College, Oxford]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Christ Church, Oxford]] ([[DPhil]])\n|website          = {{url|andrewadonis.org/|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (born '''Andreas Adonis'''; 22 February 1963)<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\">{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/publicservices/story/0,11032,1602671,00.html |title=The Guardian profile: Andrew Adonis |date=28 October 2005 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |author=Will Woodward |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and journalist who served in [[HM Government]] for five years in the [[Blair ministry]] and the [[Brown ministry]]. He served as [[Secretary of State for Transport]] from 2009 to 2010, and as [[National Infrastructure Commission|Chairman of the National Infrastructure Commission]] from 2015 to 2017.\n\nAdonis began his career as an [[academic]] at [[Oxford University]], before becoming a journalist at the ''[[Financial Times]]'' and later ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /><ref name=\"DfESprofile\" /><ref name=\"BBCstory\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4530433.stm |title=Adviser Adonis made a minister |date=10 May 2005 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Adonis was appointed by Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] to be an advisor at the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]], specialising in constitutional and educational policy, in 1998. He was later promoted to become the Head of the Policy Unit from 2001 until being created a [[life peer]] in 2005, when he was appointed [[Department for Education|Minister of State for Education]] in [[HM Government]].<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /><ref name=\"DfESprofile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/aboutus/whoswho/ministersinfo.shtml|title=Department for Education and Skills Ministerial Team |accessdate=30 March 2007 |publisher=Department for Education and Skills |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401112255/http://www.dfes.gov.uk/aboutus/whoswho/ministersinfo.shtml#hughes |archivedate=1 April 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> He remained in that role when [[Gordon Brown]] became Prime Minister in 2007, before becoming [[Department for Transport|Minister of State for Transport]] in 2008. In 2009, he was promoted to [[Cabinet (UK)|the Cabinet]] as [[Secretary of State for Transport|Transport Secretary]], a position he held until 2010.<ref name=\"nationalarchives1\">[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100513070028/http:/www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/rail/pi/highspeedrail/commandpaper/ High Speed Rail \u2013 Command Paper]. Department for Transport, 11 March 2010, {{ISBN|9780101782722}}</ref>\n\nAdonis has worked for a number of [[think tank]]s, is a board member of [[Policy Network]] and is the author or co-author of several books, including several studies of the [[Social structure of the United Kingdom|British class system]], the rise and fall of the [[Poll tax (Great Britain)|Community Charge]], and the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] [[House of Lords]]. He has also co-edited a collection of essays on [[Roy Jenkins]]. Like Jenkins, Adonis speaks with [[Rhotacism (speech impediment)|rhotacism]].\n\nAdonis is a strong supporter and advocate of the [[European Union]] and a vocal opponent of [[Brexit]]. Following the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on UK membership]] of the [[European Union]], he then became a key campaigner for a [[People's Vote|second referendum]] on British departure from the EU.\n\n==Family and education==\nAdonis's father, Nikos, emigrated from [[Greek Cypriot|Cyprus]] as a teenager, becoming a waiter in [[London]], where he met Adonis's English mother.<ref name=\"Timesonline\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article532497.ece |title=Mother: why I left minister as a toddler |date=12 June 2005 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |work=The Times |location=London |first=Robert |last=Winnett}}</ref> His mother left the family when he was three, and she has had no communication with him since.<ref name=\"Timesonline\" /> Shortly thereafter Adonis and his sister were placed in care, because their father was working long hours and was not able to cope with sole parental responsibilities. Adonis lived in a council children's home until the age of 11, when he was awarded a [[local education authority]] grant to attend [[Kingham Hill School]], a boarding school in [[Oxfordshire]].<ref name=\"Financialtimes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b9ffc3b8-a1a5-11db-8bc1-0000779e2340.html |title=This is not a wacky utopia |date=17 January 2007 |accessdate=30 March 2007 |author=Ben Hall |work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nAdonis went up to [[Keble College, Oxford]], where he graduated with a first-class Bachelor of Arts degree in Modern History in 1984.<ref>''The Record'', page 21. Keble College, 1984</ref> He pursued further studies at [[Oxford University|Oxford]] receiving a <!-- Not a PhD at Oxford. -->[[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate]] with a thesis entitled, ''The political role of the British peerage in the Third Reform Act system, c. 1885\u20131914'' at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], before being elected a [[fellow]] in History and Politics at [[Nuffield College, Oxford|Nuffield College]].<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /><ref name=\"Financialtimes\" />\n\nFrom 1991 to 1996, he was an education and industry correspondent at the ''[[Financial Times]]'', eventually becoming their public policy editor.<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /> In 1996, he moved to ''[[The Observer]]'' to work as a political columnist, leader writer and editor.<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" />\n\n==Early political career==\nFrom 1987 until 1991, Adonis served as an [[Oxford City Council]]lor for the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] and later the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], representing the [[Ward (country subdivision)|North Ward]].<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /> In 1994, he was selected by the Liberal Democrats as their [[prospective parliamentary candidate]] for the [[Westbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Westbury constituency]], but he resigned after 18 months. In the following year he joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref name=\"Lab1995\">{{cite news |title=Profile: Andrew Adonis |work=BBC News |date=9 May 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/frontpage/4530847.stm |accessdate=22 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-to-late 1990s he was politically active for Labour in [[Islington North]], the constituency represented by [[Jeremy Corbyn]], and was selected as Labour candidate to contest St George's Ward for [[Islington London Borough Council]] in 1998. He withdrew from the process before the election, however, upon being offered a position in the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]] as a constitutional and educational policy advisor in 1997. He remained in this role until 2001, when he was promoted to become Head of the Policy Unit.\n\nOn 16 May 2005, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Adonis''', ''of [[Camden Town]] in the [[London Borough of Camden]]'',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57644 |page=6547 |date=19 May 2005}}</ref> making it possible for him to serve as a [[Minister (government)|government minister]], representing it in the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://education.independent.co.uk/schools/article221029.ece |title=Adonis will now be accountable |date=12 May 2005 |accessdate=3 April 2007 |work=[[The Independent]] |location=London}}{{dead link |date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n==HM Government==\n[[File:Andrew Adonis at Council House, Bristol on 5 January 2011.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Adonis at [[Council House, Bristol]] in 2011]]\nLord Adonis became the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State |Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Education]] in the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]], which was later renamed the [[Department for Children, Schools and Families]]. He was closely involved in the [[London Challenge]].<ref name=JRFLondonChallenge>{{cite web |title=Implementing the London Challenge |url=http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/Implementing%20the%20London%20Challenge%20-%20final_0.pdf |website=Institute for Government |publisher=Joseph Rowntree Foundation |accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nHaving been the architect of the [[Academy (English school)|academies policy]] in the Policy Unit, Adonis was also able to be the driving force in Government behind the programme, which replaced failing and under-performing comprehensive schools with all-ability, independently managed academies, run on a not-for-profit basis. By the time he left the Department in October 2008, 133 academies were open and 300 more were in the pipeline. These early academies were very successful.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} Government policy later sought to force academisation of all schools, moving them from outside Local Authority control. This policy has now ceased. Within this later wave of academies, evidence on performance compared to local authority schools is mixed, but on the whole suggests there is no substantial difference in performance.<ref>[https://fullfact.org/education/academies-and-maintained-schools-what-do-we-know/ Academies and maintained schools: what do we know?] Fullfact.org</ref>\n\nAdonis also encouraged [[state school]]s to adopt practices of the [[private sector]] and generally believed in giving individual schools more independence and autonomy from central government and the [[local education authority|local education authorities]]. Although he voted against schools having more independent authority in the houses of parliament in 2006. His criticism of under-performing [[comprehensive schools|comprehensives]] made him unpopular with some trade union members and some on the Labour Party's left-wing. In 2006 Adonis supported the conversion of some independent schools under financial duress into state academies, portrayed at the time as a new style of [[direct grant grammar school]]s although not selective.<ref name=independent-20061019>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/ministers-in-secret-talks-to-bring-back-direct-grant-schools-420674.html |title=Ministers in secret talks to bring back direct grant schools |last=Garner |first=Richard |newspaper=The Independent |date=19 October 2006 |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref> Adonis was also popular with some [[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition]] politicians, in particular the then [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] education spokesman [[Michael Gove]], who once declared, \"We are on the same page as Andrew Adonis.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Academy fears on Adonis reshuffle |work=BBC News | date = 6 October 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7654337.stm | accessdate = 15 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs Tony Blair's head of policy, Adonis was regarded as the architect of [[Tuition fees in the United Kingdom|tuition fees]] in 2004 \u2013 a policy he criticised and disowned 13 years later.<ref>{{cite news | title = I put up tuition fees. It's now clear they have to be scrapped | publisher = Guardian News | date = 7 July 2017 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/jul/07/tuition-fees-scrapped-debts-graduates-andrew-adonis | accessdate = 29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHaving initially kept his position when [[Gordon Brown]] became [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], Adonis was reshuffled to the [[Department for Transport]] on 3 October 2008, to become [[Minister of State]]. In May 2009, while reviewing potential cycle \"super highways\" with [[Kulveer Ranger]] and then-London Mayor [[Boris Johnson]], the group had a narrow escape when a passing lorry's back door \"suddenly flew open, dragged a parked car into the street and smashed into another \u2013 just feet from the group\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/23/boris-cycling|title=Boris Johnson's 'near-death experience' with lorry caught on camera|work=The Guardian|accessdate=26 February 2010 | location=London | first=Toby | last=Helm | date=23 May 2009}}</ref> On 5 June 2009, Adonis was promoted to the [[Cabinet (UK)|Cabinet]] as [[Secretary of State for Transport]] and was sworn a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. In this role, he pioneered the plan for [[High Speed 2]], the proposed high-speed railway line from [[Euston railway station|London]] to [[Birmingham Curzon Street railway station|Birmingham]] and the north of England. The plan was published shortly before the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 election]], and has since been adopted and taken forward, largely unchanged, by subsequent governments. In July 2015, Adonis was appointed a non-executive director to HS2 Board Ltd.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jul/16/lord-adonis-joins-board-of-hs2-project Lord Adonis joins board of HS2 project] ''The Guardian'', 16 July 2015</ref>\n\nAdonis planned and announced the electrification of the [[Great Western Main Line]] from [[Paddington railway station|London Paddington]] to [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station|Bristol]], [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff]] and [[Swansea railway station|Swansea]], and the electrification of lines in [[North West England]] from [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester]] to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool]] and Manchester to [[Preston railway station|Preston]]. This electrification programme, except for the Cardiff to Swansea section of the Great Western, was taken forward by the coalition government.\n\nAdonis was a key figure in the aftermath of the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], which produced a [[hung parliament]]. He was reputed to favour a [[Lib\u2013Lab pact|Lib\u2013Lab deal]] and, given his SDP background, was a member of Labour's negotiating team that [[2010 United Kingdom government formation|attempted to form an administration]] with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. After the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Liberal Democrats formed a coalition government with the Conservative Party]], Adonis stepped down from frontline politics.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7127791.ece |title=Adonis devised original coalition plan |work=The Times |date=16 May 2010 | location=London | first=Robert | last=Watts}}</ref>\n\nAdonis later returned to active politics in 2012, as part of [[Ed Miliband]]'s [[Shadow Cabinet]] reshuffle. He worked with former Shadow Business Secretary [[Chuka Umunna]] on crafting Labour's industrial strategy, and previously took up the role of Shadow Minister for Infrastructure in the House of Lords,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/29/lord-adonis-quits-as-theresa-may-infrastructure-tsar-over-brexit www.theguardian.com]</ref> and overseeing the Armitt Review looking at future infrastructure plans for the Labour Party.<ref>[https://www.policyforum.labour.org.uk/uploads/editor/files/The_Armitt_Review_Final_Report.pdf ''Armitt Review'']</ref>\n\n==Subsequent career==\nIn July 2010, Adonis became the director of the [[Institute for Government]], an independent charity with cross-party support and [[Whitehall]] governance working to improve government effectiveness.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/news/article/144/andrew-adonis-announced-as-new-director-of-the-institute-for-government |title=Andrew Adonis announced as new Director of the Institute for Government.' |date=15 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318010831/http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/news/article/144/andrew-adonis-announced-as-new-director-of-the-institute-for-government |archivedate=18 March 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Adonis left the Institute for Government in January 2012, to become Chair of [[Progress (organisation)|Progress]], an internal Labour Party organisation.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120111075549/http://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/news/article/270/institute-for-government-appoints-rt-hon-peter-riddell-as-director Institute For Government Appoints Rt Hon Peter Riddell As Director]. instituteforgovernment.org.uk. 17 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/01/11/andrew-adonis-becomes-new-progress-chair/ Andrew Adonis becomes new Progress chair | Progress | News and debate from the progressive community] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318154809/http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/01/11/andrew-adonis-becomes-new-progress-chair/ |date=18 March 2012 }}. Progressonline.org.uk (11 January 2012). Retrieved 19 October 2013.</ref> Having been appointed President of the Independent Academies Association, in 2012, Adonis was also admitted as a [[Liveryman]] ''[[Honoris Causa]]'' of the [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers]], one of the major charitable promoters of [[Academy (English school)|academies]].<ref>[http://www.iaa.uk.net/ www.iaa.uk.net]. http://www.iaa.uk.net (5 July 2013). Retrieved 19 October 2013.</ref>\n\nLord Adonis is a [[Trustee]] of [[Teach First]], the charity which recruits graduates to teach in state schools, as well as a Trustee of the vocational education charity [[Edge (educational foundation)|Edge]], and a [[Governor]] of the Baker-Dearing Trust, which supports the establishment of University Technical Colleges, technical schools for 14- to 18-year-olds.<ref>[http://www.edge.co.uk/about-edge/our-people Our people] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501083155/http://www.edge.co.uk/about-edge/our-people |date=1 May 2012 }}. Edge.co.uk. Retrieved 19 October 2013.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130315182102/http://www.teachfirst.org.uk/AboutUs/ourpeople.aspx Our People]. teachfirst.org.uk</ref> He has been a Director of RM Plc since October 2011. His book on education reform \u2013 ''Education, Education, Education'' \u2013 was published by [[Biteback]] in September 2012.<ref>[https://www.bitebackpublishing.com/books/education-education-education-paperback Education, Education, Education Reforming] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017122625/https://www.bitebackpublishing.com/books/education-education-education-paperback |date=17 October 2013 }}. bitebackpublishing.com</ref> In November 2014, he was appointed visiting professor at [[King's College London]].<ref>[http://www.kcl.ac.uk/newsevents/news/newsrecords/2014/November/Lord-Adonis-appointed-Visiting-Professor.aspx www.kcl.ac.uk]. King's College London. Retrieved 23 November 2014.</ref>\n\nAdonis considered standing<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/04/andrew-adonis-tale-two-cities-reality-london|title=Andrew Adonis: \"The tale of two cities is the reality of London\"|work=New Statesman|accessdate=6 May 2016 | location=London | first=Tim | last=Wigmore | date=30 April 2015}}</ref> to be Labour's candidate for [[Mayor of London]] in [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]], but ended his putative campaign in February 2015, endorsing [[Tessa Jowell]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/i-wont-run-for-mayor-dame-tessa-jowell-is-the-best-candidate-says-lord-adonis-10056054.html|title=I won't run for mayor \u2013 Dame Tessa Jowell is the best candidate, says Lord Adonis|work=London Evening Standard|accessdate=6 May 2016 | location=London | first=Joe | last=Murphy | date=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, he resigned the Labour Party whip in the House of Lords to sit as a [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|non-affiliated Peer]] and lead a newly created [[National Infrastructure Commission]] (NIC). However, he resigned from the NIC in December 2017 because of the HM Government's approach to [[Brexit]], saying the UK was \"hurtling towards the EU's emergency exit with no credible plan for the future of British trade and European co-operation\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42514117|title=Adonis quits role with Brexit attack|date=29 December 2017|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\nAdonis said he planned to oppose \"relentlessly\" the government's [[European Union (Withdrawal) Bill]] in the House of Lords.  In his resignation letter, he wrote that, as well as Brexit, the recent decision to end the [[InterCity East Coast]] [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|rail franchise]] three years early, at a cost of hundreds of millions of pounds, would also have forced him to quit. He also claimed that  \"taking us back into Europe will become the mission of our children's generation\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Lord Adonis quits government role in stinging letter|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42515637|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=BBC News|date=29 December 2017}}</ref> On 15 April 2018 Adonis attended the launch event of the [[People's Vote]], a campaign group calling for a public vote on the final [[Brexit]] deal between the UK and the European Union.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Brexit: 'People's Vote' campaign group launched | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43774200 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 15 April 2018 | access-date = 17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 European Parliament election]], Adonis was second on Labour's [[party list]] for [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foster |first1=Matt |title=Anti-Brexit peer Lord Adonis among candidates as Labour unveils MEP hopefuls |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/foreign-affairs/brexit/news/103344/anti-brexit-peer-lord-adonis-among-candidates-labour |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Politicshome.com |date=19 April 2019}}</ref> but was not elected. Labour\u2019s share of the vote was 6.5% (a fall of 7.3% relative to the 2014 result) and the party lost its only MEP in the region.\n\nAdonis was a participant at the 30 May - 2 June 2019 [[Bilderberg Meeting]] at [[Montreux]], Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bilderbergmeetings.org/press/press-release/participants|title=Participants|author=|date=|website=bilderbergmeetings.org|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAdonis was formerly married to Kathryn Davies,<ref name=\"Guardianprofile\" /> who was once a student of his;<ref name=\"Timesonline\"/> the couple had two children.<ref name=\"Financialtimes\" /> Adonis and Davies divorced in 2015. In a profile<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrew-adonis-we-must-spell-it-out-now-labour-is-a-remain-party-a4137381.html|title=Andrew Adonis: We must spell it out now, Labour is a Remain party|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=8 May 2019 | location=London | first=Julian| last=Glover| date=8 May 2019}}</ref> in the ''Evening Standard'' in 2019, the journalist [[Julian Glover (journalist)|Julian Glover]] reported that Adonis was gay.<ref>{{cite news |title=Andrew Adonis: We must spell it out now, Labour is a Remain party |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrew-adonis-we-must-spell-it-out-now-labour-is-a-remain-party-a4137381.html |work=Evening Standard |date=8 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book | title=Roy Jenkins: A Retrospective | author=Andrew Adonis (Editor), Keith Thomas (Editor) | id=| year = 2004}}\n*{{cite book | title=A Class Act: Myth of Britain's Classless Society| author=Andrew Adonis, [[Stephen Pollard]] | id=| year = 1997}}\n*{{cite book | title= Failure in British government : the politics of the poll tax | author=David Butler, Andrew Adonis & [[Tony Travers]] | id=| year = 1994}}\n*{{cite book | title=Making Aristocracy Work: The Peerage and the Political System in Britain, | author=Andrew Adonis | id=| year = 1993}}\n*{{cite book | title=Subsidiarity: no panacea | author=Andrew Adonis (Editor), [[Andrew Tyrie]] (Editor) | id=| year = 1989}}\n*{{cite book | title=The Thatcher-Reagan Decade in Perspective | author=Andrew Adonis (Editor), [[Tim Hames]] (Editor) | id=| year = 1994}}\n*{{cite book | title=Education Education Education: Reforming England's Schools | author=Andrew Adonis| id=| year=2012}}\n*{{Cite book | title=5 Days in May: The Coalition and Beyond | last=Adonis | first=Andrew | year=2013 | publisher=Biteback Publishing | isbn=978-1849545662 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/5daysinmaycoalit0000adon }}\n*{{Cite book | title=Saving Britain: How We Must Change To Prosper In Europe  | author=[[Will Hutton]], Andrew Adonis | year=2018 | publisher=Abacus: Little, Brown Book Group, London | isbn = 978-1408711224}}\n*{{Cite book | title=Half In Half Out: Prime Ministers on Europe | author=Andrew Adonis (editor) | year=2018 | publisher=Biteback Publishing | isbn = 978-1785904349}}\n\n===Articles===\n* [[Ben Pimlott]] ''The Queen: A Biography of Elizabeth II'' \u2013 book review, 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* ''Our progressives only look dead'' (prospects for a revival of progressivism in the United Kingdom), 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Christopher Booker]] and [[Richard North (blogger)|Richard North]] ''The Castle of Lies: Why Britain Must Get Out of Europe'' \u2013 book review, 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Anthony Barnett (writer)|Anthony Barnett]] ''This Time: Our Constitutional Revolution'' \u2013 book review, 1996, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Shirley Williams]] ''Climbing the Bookshelves: the Autobiography'' \u2013 book review, 2009, Andrew Adonis\n* [[Roy Hattersley]] ''David Lloyd George: the Great Outsider'' \u2013 book review, 2010, Andrew Adonis\n* [[David Laws]] ''22 Days in May: The Birth of the Lib Dem-Conservative Coalition'' \u2013 book review, 2010, Andrew Adonis\n* Chris Bowers ''Nick Clegg: the Biography'' \u2013 book review, 2011, Andrew Adonis\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK Peer links | parliament = lords/lord-adonis/3743 | hansard = mr-andrew-adonis | hansardcurr = 4852 | guardian = | publicwhip = Lord_Adonis | theywork = lord_adonis | record = Andrew-Adonis/1457 | bbc = 19424.stm | journalisted = }}\n*[http://thepeerage.com/p14950.htm#i149491 \"Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis\"] at ''The Peerage''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120324153353/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/19424 www.parliament.uk]\n*[https://www.andrewadonistour.org/ Official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Timms]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Education|Minister of State for Education]]|years=2005\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Knight]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rosie Winterton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Transport]]|years=2008\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sadiq Khan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Geoff Hoon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Transport]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Philip Hammond]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People's Vote}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Minister of State for Transport}}\n{{British special advisers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adonis, Andrew Adonis, Baron}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kingham Hill School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keble College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of Oxford City Council]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:English political writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Keble College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Nuffield College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Advocates of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Transport (UK)]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Tony Blair]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Gay academics]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]