{"title_page": "Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb", "text_new": "{{other people|Jenny Jones}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Baroness Jones <br />of Moulsecoomb\n| honorific-suffix = [[Fellow of The Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]]\n| image            = Official portrait of Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb crop 2.jpg\n| caption          = \n| office1           = [[Deputy Mayor of London]]\n| term_start1       = 16 May 2003\n| term_end1         = 14 June 2004\n| 1blankname1       = [[Mayor of London|Mayor]]\n| 1namedata1        = [[Ken Livingstone]]\n| predecessor1      = [[Nicky Gavron]]\n| successor1        = [[Nicky Gavron]]\n|office         = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start = 5 November 2013<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| office3        = [[London Assembly|Member of the London Assembly]]<br/>as the [[List of London Assembly constituencies|11th Additional Member]]\n| term_start3      = 4 May 2000\n| term_end3        = 6 May 2016\n| successor3       = [[Caroline Russell]]\n|office4 = [[Councillor#United Kingdom|Councillor]] for [[Southwark London Borough Council]]\n|term_start4 = 4 May 2006\n|term_end4   = 6 May 2010\n|1blankname4      = [[Wards of the United Kingdom|Ward]]\n|1namedata4       = South Camberwell\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1949|12|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brighton]], [[Sussex]], England\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = British\n| spouse           = \n| party            = {{Nowrap|[[Green Party of England and Wales]]}}\n| relations        = \n| children         = \n| residence        = [[Southwark]], London, UK\n| alma_mater       = [[University College London]]\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = Archaeologist\n| signature        = \n| website          = {{url|http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-jones-of-moulsecoomb/4297|www.parliament.uk}}\n| footnotes        = \n| module           = <center>{{Listen|embed=yes|filename=Jenny Jones voice.ogg|title=Jones' voice|type=speech|description=<center>recorded February 2013</center>}} }}</center>\n\n'''Jennifer Helen Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb''', [[Fellow of The Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (born 23 December 1949) is a British politician and member of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]. She was until September 2019 the sole Green Party member in the House of Lords.\n\nJones represented the Green Party in the [[London Assembly]] from its creation in 2000 until standing down in 2016. She was the Green candidate for [[Mayor of London]] in the [[2012 London mayoral election|2012 election]], coming third with 4.48% of first preferences. She served as [[Deputy Mayor of London]] from May 2003 to June 2004. She was also the sole Green councillor on [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark Council]] from 2006 to 2010.<ref name=GPBio>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/individual/86 |title=Cllr. Jenny Jones AM's Green Party Website Biography |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref><ref name=southwarkgreen>[http://southwark.greenparty.org.uk/localsites/southwark/news/livingwage.html] ''Southwark Greens'' Stop paying council cleaners poverty wages.</ref>\n\nOn the London Assembly, Jones's prime areas of interest were transport, housing and planning, and policing, \"with a strong emphasis on sustainability and localism\".<ref name=GPBio/> In addition to her period as deputy mayor, Jones served as Chair of London Food, Green Transport Advisor, and Road Safety Ambassador<ref name=\"JonesTransport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/transport/|title=Jenny For London, March 12th 2011, A transport system that works|publisher=Jennyforlondon.org|date=|access-date=2012-03-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307045625/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/transport/|archive-date=7 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was announced at the beginning of August 2013 that she was to become the first Green [[life peer]] in the [[House of Lords]] since [[Tim Beaumont]] <ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/news/working-peerages-announced Working Peerages announced] Gov.uk</ref> She was introduced to the House of Lords on 5 November 2013.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/house-of-lords-24554846 \"Introductions\"] ''Democracy Live'' ([[House of Lords]]; published by the BBC), 5 November 2013; [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2013-11-05a.97.2 \"Introduction: Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb \u2013 in the House of Lords at 2:38 pm on 5th November 2013.\"] ''They Work For You'' 5 November 2013</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nJones mainly grew up on the [[Moulsecoomb]] estate in [[Brighton]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Vowles|first=Neil|title=Baroness of Moulsecoomb gives first speech in House of Lords|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/10847903.Baroness_of_Moulsecoomb_gives_first_speech_in_House_of_Lords|work=The Argus|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> with brief periods of time abroad in [[Lesotho]] and [[Seychelles]].<ref name=4talent>{{cite web |url=http://4talent.channel4.com/extra/evening-discussion-young-people-equality-diversity-and-mayor |title=An Evening Discussion: Young People, Equality, Diversity and the Mayor |publisher=Channel 4 |date=2012-02-22 |accessdate=2012-03-21 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She attended the co-educational Westlain Grammar School (now [[Falmer High School]]). Before entering politics, Jones worked as [[financial controller]] in London. She attended the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology|Institute of Archaeology]] at [[University College London]] as a [[mature student]], studying for an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in [[archaeology]].<ref name=GPBio/> She spent approximately ten years as an archaeologist in the Middle East, [[paleobotany|studying carbonised plant remains]], before embarking on a career in politics.<ref name=4talent/>\n\n==Political career==\nJones joined the [[Green Party of England and Wales]] in 1988. She has held several posts within the party, including the position of chair on the executive from 1995 to 1997.<ref name=GPBio/>\n\n=== London Assembly member ===\nIn [[2000 London Assembly election|the 2000 election]], Jones won a place in the inaugural [[London Assembly]] as part of a three-strong Green Group, including Councillor [[Darren Johnson]] AM and [[Victor Anderson (Green politician)|Victor Anderson]], who resigned in March 2003 and was replaced by [[Noel Lynch]] for the remainder of the term. The [[2004 London Assembly election|2004 GLA elections]] saw the Greens lose the seat held by Lynch, leaving Jones and Johnson as the two remaining members of the Green Group.\n\nIn May 2003, the Green Party, after some internal dissent, accepted an offer from the [[Mayor of London]], [[Ken Livingstone]], to nominate a [[Deputy Mayor of London|deputy mayor]]; they chose Jones, who held the post until June 2004. The offer was part of Livingstone's pledge to rotate the position of deputy mayor, although he later declined to offer the post to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] and had an offer to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] turned down.<ref name=\"deputyarticle\">{{cite news|author=Andrew Clark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/feb/19/uk.london |title='&#39;The Guardian'&#39;, February 19th 2003, '&#39;\"Greens select Livingstone's deputy\"'&#39; |newspaper=Guardian |date= 2003-02-19|accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nAs a London Assembly Member, Jenny Jones promoted the issues of [[road safety]], food, [[sustainable transport]], social justice and the police and civil liberties.<ref name=\"GLABio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/profile/jenny-jones |title=London Assembly Biography |publisher=London.gov.uk |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425034849/http://www.london.gov.uk/profile/jenny-jones |archive-date=25 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nShe was a member of the [[Metropolitan Police Authority]],<ref name=GLABio/> and has issued a report on traffic policing.<ref name=\"LawlessRoads\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/lawlessroad_report.pdf |title='&#39;Jenny Jones'&#39;, 2007, '&#39;\"London\u2019s Lawless Roads: Why traffic policing must improve to prevent road death and injury\"'&#39; |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303164439/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/lawlessroad_report.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> She sat on both the MPA's Strategic and Operational Policing Committee and Civil Liberties Panel.<ref name=\"SOPC\">[http://www.mpa.gov.uk/committees/sop/ Strategic Operational Policing Committee] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803122217/http://www.mpa.gov.uk/committees/sop/ |date=3 August 2009 }}, part of the Metropolitan Police Authority</ref><ref name=\"CLP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mpa.gov.uk/clp/ |title=Civil Liberties Panel |publisher=Mpa.gov.uk |date=2009-07-09 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220062041/http://www.mpa.gov.uk/clp/ |archive-date=20 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Elsewhere she put forward a motion and has put questions to the Mayor calling for progress on women's issues, specifically in relation to [[violence against women]] and support provision.<ref name=\"RapeCrisisCentres\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/21/boris-johnson-rape-crisis-centres|title=Boris Johnson urged to honour rape crisis centres pledge|author=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Mulholland|date=21 October 2009|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nJones chaired the Planning and Housing Committee, which issued a report on food growing and planning in London, Cultivating the Capital.<ref name=GLABio/> It concluded that \"London has only three or four days stocks of food should there be any disruption to supply\".<ref name=\"CultivatingCapital\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/the-london-assembly/publications/housing-planning/cultivating-capital-food-growing-and-planning-system-london |title='&#39;Planning and Housing Committee'&#39;, 1 January 2010, '&#39;\" Cultivating the Capital \u2013 Food growing and the planning system in London\"'&#39; |publisher=London.gov.uk |date=2010-01-06 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427081423/http://www.london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/the-london-assembly/publications/housing-planning/cultivating-capital-food-growing-and-planning-system-london |archive-date=27 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Jones issued an individual report in January 2010 on [[affordable housing]] in London, which determined that \"the cost of buying a home [in London] has risen twice as fast as incomes\".<ref name=\"ComingHome\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/cominghometoroost.pdf |title='&#39;Jenny Jones'&#39;, January 2010, '&#39;\"Coming Home to Roost: How two Mayors have failed to make housing affordable\"'&#39; |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303164452/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/cominghometoroost.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nShe was also a member of the Confirmation Hearings and Transport Committees.<ref name=GLABio/>\n\nShe previously held roles as the Mayor's Road Safety Ambassador and Green Transport advisor,<ref name= GPBio/> focusing on road safety and [[cycling in London]]<ref name=\"BikeRentalScheme\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/motoring/features/stop-your-engines-with-the-bike-rental-scheme-463855.html ''The Independent'', 4 September 2007 ''Stop Your Engines With the Bike Rental Scheme'']{{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref> respectively, as well as being the former Chair of London Food, a mayoral commission which \"aims to give Londoners fresher, healthier and more affordable food while reducing the environmental impact of our current food supply\".<ref name=\"LondonFood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lda.gov.uk/server.php?show=ConWebDoc.1499 |title='&#39;London Development Agency'&#39;, May 22, 2006, '&#39;\"Mayor of London unveils first strategy to improve London's food\" '&#39; |publisher=Lda.gov.uk |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224021144/http://www.lda.gov.uk/server.php?show=ConWebDoc.1499 |archive-date=24 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> As Chair, Jones was responsible for drawing up the Sustainable Food Strategy for London<ref name=\"LDAFoodStrategy\">{{cite web|url=http://moderngov.southwarksites.com/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=4231 |title='&#39;London Development Agency'&#39;, May 2006, '&#39;\"The Mayor\u2019s Food Strategy: Healthy and Sustainable Food for London\"'&#39; |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201180113/http://moderngov.southwarksites.com/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=4231 |archive-date= 1 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>  and chaired the Food Implementation Group overseeing the strategy<ref name=LondonFood/> More recently she also issued a report on the subject of food security in the capital.<ref name=\"SecureFood\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/secure_food.pdf |title='&#39;Jenny Jones'&#39;, 2008, '&#39;\"Why London Needs to Grow More Food\"'&#39; |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303164505/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/secure_food.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Southwark Councillor ===\nIn the [[2006 United Kingdom local elections|2006 local elections]], Jones was elected as a councillor for the South [[Camberwell]] ward in the [[London Borough of Southwark]], the Greens' first councillor in Southwark.<ref name=GPBio/> She came third in the ward, polling 1014 votes.<ref name=Southwark2006Election>[http://www.southwark.gov.uk/Uploads/File_27062.pdf Southwark Council | Your Council | Your Vote | Results of Borough Council Elections 4 May 2006 | Local Election Results 2006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927234853/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/Uploads/File_27062.pdf |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> In the [[2010 Southwark Council election|2010 elections]] she lost her seat, coming fifth with 1282 votes.<ref name=Southwark2010election>{{cite web |url=http://www.southwark.gov.uk/site/custom_scripts/viewelection.php?pollid=18 |title=Election results for South Camberwell &#124; Southwark Council |publisher=Southwark.gov.uk |date=2010-05-06 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511074109/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/site/custom_scripts/viewelection.php?pollid=18 |archive-date=11 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Parliamentary candidate ===\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]], she stood in the [[Dulwich and West Norwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Dulwich and West Norwood]] parliamentary constituency, coming fourth with 2,741 votes (6.5%).<ref name=2005Election>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwark.gov.uk/YourCouncil/YourVote/GeneralElection/resultsdawn.html |title=Council and democracy \u2013 Southwark Council |publisher=Southwark.gov.uk |date=2005-04-01 |access-date=2013-12-27 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201132135/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/YourCouncil/yourvote/GeneralElection/resultsdawn.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]], she stood in the [[Camberwell and Peckham (UK Parliament constituency)|Camberwell and Peckham]] parliamentary constituency, coming fourth with 1,361 votes (2.9%).<ref name=2010Election>{{cite web |url=http://www.southwark.gov.uk/info/1000/election_results/1617/general_election_2010 |title=General election 2010 \u2013 Southwark Council |publisher=Southwark.gov.uk |date=2010-05-06 |access-date=2012-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510030206/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/info/1000/election_results/1617/general_election_2010 |archive-date=10 May 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Mayoral candidate ===\nIn March 2011, Jones was selected as the Green Party's candidate for the 2012 London Mayoral election winning 67% of the votes against prominent Green Party members [[Shahrar Ali|Dr Shahrar Ali]] and Farid Bakht, stating \"At this time of savage cuts to essential services, London needs a Mayor who will create a fairer city and reduce the gap between rich and poor. These are hard times for people who care about quality services, local businesses, and protecting the most vulnerable members of our communities. I promise to make fighting cuts to housing benefit, the NHS and youth services a key part of my campaign to be Mayor.\"<ref name=jennyjonescandidate>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/20-03-2011-jenny-jones-london-mayor.html |title='&#39;Green Party'&#39;, 2012, '&#39;\"Jenny Jones Mayoral Candidate\"'&#39; |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date=2011-03-20 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nAt the election, she came third with 98,913 first preference votes, the highest position of a Green candidate to date, but lost her deposit, scoring less than 5% of the vote.\n\n=== House of Lords ===\nOn 20 September 2013, she was created a [[Life Peer]] taking the title '''Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb''', of [[Moulsecoomb]] in the County of [[East Sussex]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60638 |date=25 September 2013 |page=18895}}</ref> She was nominated for this appointment by her party after a ballot of members. She was introduced to the [[House of Lords]] on 5 November 2013.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> She became the first Green Party [[peer of the realm|peer]] since the death of [[Tim Beaumont]], in 2008. The only other Green parliamentarian is [[Caroline Lucas]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Brighton Pavilion]].\n\n==Political views==\n\n===Police===\n\nJones was a member of the [[Metropolitan Police Authority]] from its creation in 2000 \"and has worked on a wide range of policing issues, with a particular focus on road safety, violence against women, civil liberties and neighbourhood policing\" until it was disbanded in 2012.<ref name=\"Jones-mpa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mpa.gov.uk/about/people/members/02jones/ |title=Metropolitan Polica Authority, Jenny Jones MPA Member |publisher=Mpa.gov.uk |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205105526/http://www.mpa.gov.uk/about/people/members/02jones/ |archive-date=5 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"bbcmpaend\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-16525629 |title='&#39;, 12th January 2012, '&#39;\" MPA Holds Last Meeting\"'&#39; |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2012-01-12 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> She was outspoken about numerous issues including what she called mayor [[Boris Johnson]]'s demonisation of youth through the use of \"baseless\" rhetoric on \"soaring gang-membership and rising knife-crime\", suggesting the mayor created an unhelpful climate of fear.<ref name=\"evilyouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/2008-10-06-youth.html |title=Green Party, 2008, Myth-busting report criticises London Mayor's demonisation of youth |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date=2008-10-05 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> Jones then served as a member of the MPA's replacement body, the London Assembly Police and Crime Committee.<ref name=\"crimecom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/moderngov/mgCommitteeDetails.aspx?ID=240 |title=GLA, Police and Crime Committee details |publisher=London.gov.uk |date= 2012|accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2011 England Riots|riots in August 2011]], Jones and [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] leader, [[Caroline Lucas]] MP co-authored an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'', arguing that all cuts to policing should be postponed until December 2012 when a sufficient review of the events has occurred and the lessons from the [[London Olympics]] are learned, \"In the meantime, the police should focus on spending money wisely, and ensuring that police officers are not burdened with administrative tasks which take them away from frontline policing.\"<ref name=\"guadrianriots\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/aug/22/recover-riot-rebalance-inequality-society |title=The Guardian, August 22nd 2011, To recover from the riots we must rebalance the inequalities of society |newspaper=Guardian |date=2010-07-16 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |first=Caroline |last=Lucas}}</ref>\n\nAfter herself being [[kettled]] at a students demonstration, Jones was vociferously critical of this police tactic, telling the BBC the police used kettling to \"imprison peaceful campaigners and have shown they can't be trusted with such a powerful tactic\", suggesting \"The Met's reputation sinks even further every time they abuse their powers and it's time to stop this particular mistreatment\".<ref name=\"bbckettle\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12293394 |title=  Petition against Metropolitan Police 'kettling' tactic |publisher=BBC |date=2011-01-27 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Jones penned an editorial in ''[[The Guardian]]'' wherein she criticised the surveillance tactics of police on activists. After going through the process now available through the Data Protection Act to get the police report on herself, she found that she was labelled a potential \"domestic extremist\". She found that the report contained only publicly available information, such as tweets, and that nothing in it would suggest potentially dangerous activity. Jones has been under surveillance by the police's \"domestic extremism\" unit from 2001 until 2012, including the time during her attempt to become London's mayor.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jun/15/green-party-peer-put-on-database-of-extremists-by-police | title=Green party peer put on database of 'extremists' after police surveillance | accessdate=2016-01-11 | last1=Evans | first1=Rob | last2=Bowcott | first2=Owen | date=2014-06-15 | newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref> She viewed the revelation as both a violation of her privacy and a waste of police resources. She is now calling for a re-evaluation of police policies, especially in regards to political activists.<ref>Jenny Jones, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jun/16/domestic-extremist-metropolitan-police-spying-elected-politician The Met turned me into a domestic extremist \u2013 with tweets and trivia], The Guardian, 13 June 2014.</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, [[whistleblower]] [[Sergeant#United Kingdom|Sgt]] David Williams claimed that the police's \"domestic extremism\" unit [[Paper shredder|shredded]] records \"related to\" Jones in June 2014, the month Jones met with the unit pressing for answers.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jan/08/officer-claims-met-police-improperly-destroyed-files-on-green-party-peer | title=Officer claims Met police improperly destroyed files on Green party peer | accessdate=2016-01-11 | last=Evans | first=Rob | date=2016-01-08 | newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref>\n\n===Healthy eating===\nJones has argued for big changes to London's current food culture as Chair of London Food during Ken Livingstone's second Mayoral term. During her time as chair, London Food released its \u2018Food Strategy\u2019 aiming to \"help improve food in London\u2019s schools, hospitals and other public institutions\" and \"offer people on low income better access to healthy and affordable food\".<ref name=LondonFood/> Some of the reports key points were:\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Brian May, Jenny Jones at Animal mini-manifesto Launch.jpg|thumb|right|Jones with [[Queen (Band)|Queen]] guitarist [[Brian May]] and Assembly candidate Caroline Allen at the launch of the Animal mini-manifesto]] -->\n\n* \"Consideration will be given to the role that the public sector can play in helping to facilitate more producer collaborations and logistics and distribution partnerships, to help smaller producers to compete in the market, and to encourage new entrants\"\n* \"Directing better the existing resources available for business support for specialist food manufacturers and processors, particularly on consumer market trends and collaborative working, and particularly for [[small and medium sized enterprises]] (SMEs) that reflect London\u2019s diverse communities\"\n* \"Promote and expand opportunities for small-scale food production for individuals and communities through gardens, orchards, schools, allotments and parks and open spaces\"\n* \"Continue to increase the amount of organic and local food provided through public sector services in London in response to growing consumer demand\"\n* \"Research and promote the positive benefits of nutritious food for children.\"<ref name=LondonFood/>\n\nIn 2008, Jones released a report \u2018Why London Needs to Grow More Food\u2019 stressing \"The Mayor of London has planning and development powers, which could be used to support widespread urban agriculture in London through the commercial and voluntary sectors, community-led social enterprises, and by engaging the unemployed, elderly, and lower skilled groups\".<ref name=SecureFood/>\n\n===Transport===\nJones commissioned the initial [[Transport for London]] report into promoting cycling that paved the way for the London Cycle-hire scheme.<ref name=JonesTransport/> Ashok Sinha, Chief executive of the [[London Cycling Campaign]], said of Jones \"In 2008 the London Cycling Campaign gave Jenny Jones a Special Award for her Lifetime Services to cycling. This was in recognition of her success in helping to push cycling into mainstream politics, her efforts to deliver many cycling projects on the ground, and her energies as cycling champion in general.\".<ref name=JonesTransport/>\nIn a confrontation with the Mayor over cycle safety, Johnson said:<ref name=\"mqtcycling\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mBup5U_9Ycw |title=Mayor\u2019s Question Time, November 2011, Jenny Jones AM questions Boris Johnson on cycle safety |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|(it is) your duty as an honest politician to tell people the truth that cycling is actually getting safer, when you consider the number of people on the roads.}}\n\nJohnson's advisor wrote to Jones claiming there had been:\n\n{{quote|... a reduced number of cycling collisions in the last ten years}}\n\nWhich turned out not to be true.<ref name=\"cycledanger\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-am-new-tfl-figures-show-cycling-not-getting-safer |title=GLA, February 2012, Cycling not getting safer |publisher=London.gov.uk |date=2012-02-02 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425205633/http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-am-new-tfl-figures-show-cycling-not-getting-safer |archive-date=25 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>  In a written statement Jones said, \"we know that cycle safety is the big problem which puts Londoners off jumping on their bikes. There are a growing number of deaths and injuries of cyclists and trying to cover that up by issuing factually inaccurate statements won\u2019t change the reality,\" continuing, \"We urgently need to fix the most dangerous junctions and reverse the Mayor\u2019s policy of giving priority to motorised traffic. The Mayor needs to stand his policy on its head and give legal priority on many local roads to pedestrians and cyclists.\"<ref name=cycledanger/> Jones has also been critical of Johnson's neglect of cycling in outer London, stating \"given that 70% of the potential new cyclists identified by TfL are outside of inner and central London, it is shocking that the Transport Strategy has no clear plan for cycling in the suburbs and outer London.\"<ref name=\"Transportresponse\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/response-statement-intent-070809.pdf |title=GLA Consultation Response to Mayor\u2019s Transport Strategy Statement of Intent|format=PDF |date=July 2009 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516170549/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/response-statement-intent-070809.pdf |archive-date=16 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nJones has spoken against Boris Johnson's transport policy of \"making motoring cheaper in London, whilst public transport fares are raised above inflation\".<ref name=\"Transportresponse\" /> At Mayor's question time, Jones highlighted a \"promise\" Johnson had made in 2008 to make all new buses  [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]] by 2012 when in reality less than 10% had met this criterion.<ref name=\"mqthybrid\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H3gg98QWM0A&noredirect=1 |title=Mayor's Question time, February 2012, Jones grills Boris on Busses |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> Jones wishes for a reduction in the burden for Londoners felt by Johnson's price increases and proposes a reduction in fares of about 4%.<ref name=\"artslondonnews\">{{cite web|last=Starkey |first=Gerard |url=http://www.artslondonnews.co.uk/20120131-green-party-jenny-jones |title=Arts London News, 3 February 2012, London Mayor elections: Jenny Jones|publisher=Artslondonnews.co.uk |date=2012-02-03 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512214413/http://www.artslondonnews.co.uk/20120131-green-party-jenny-jones |archive-date=12 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Jones supported the [[congestion charge]] as a way to lower pollution and road casualties and spoke against the mayor's cancellation of the Western extension, arguing that it made London dirtier, more crowded and less safe.<ref name=\"guardiancc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/28/london-boris |title=The Guardian, 28 November 2008, Boris's C-charge blunder|newspaper=Guardian |date=2010-07-16 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |first=Jenny |last=Jones}}</ref> Jones favours replacing the congestion charge with a \"smart, pay-as-you drive scheme\".<ref name=\"manifestotransport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/region/london/manifesto/transport.html |title=London Green Party, March 2012, Our Manifesto: Let's transform public transport |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===The City===\nIn her statement of policy for the 2012 election, Jones proposes several ideas to bring \"a renaissance of micro, small and medium businesses\" in order to spread \"wealth to all Londoners\", seeking \"a financial services sector that works for them\".<ref name=\"GreenCity\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Fresh-ideas-for-banking.pdf |title=Jenny for London, February 2012, Making the City work for London |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308165900/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Fresh-ideas-for-banking.pdf |archive-date=8 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She argues for a system that rewards good long-term investment \"instead of trying to make a fast buck\" and proposes a good financial example to be Sweden's [[Handelsbanken]] which gives \"good basic pay and no bonuses.\"<ref name=GreenCity/> One of her candidacy's most distinct positions is with respect to [[The City of London|The City]] with ambitions to \"Abolish the City of London Corporation and replace it with a democratic London borough\", \"support new institutions like local community banks focused on lending to small businesses and social enterprises\" and \"Promote building societies and credit unions and lobby the Government to put its remaining nationalised banking assets into one of these models rather than a bank\".<ref name=GreenCity/> Elsewhere Jones has been critical of excessive top-level remuneration, stating, \"It's difficult not to feel enraged\" by statistics showing the average FTSE CEO earns 565 times the national average.<ref name=\"CityPayGap\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/oct/14/london-pay-gap-public-sector |title=The Guardian, 14 October 2011, London\u2019s City Hall must lead on closing Britain\u2019s pay gap|newspaper=Guardian |date=2011-10-14 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |first=Jenny |last=Jones}}</ref>\n\n===Fair Pay ratio===\nJones and the Green Party, alongside others,<ref name=\"neftheratio\">{{cite web |url=http://neweconomics.org/publications/the-ratio |title=The New Economics Foundation, 4 July 2011, Common sense controls for executive pay and revitalising UK business |publisher=Neweconomics.org |date=2011-07-04 |access-date=2012-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120185039/http://www.neweconomics.org/publications/the-ratio |archive-date=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> are deeply critical of the inequalities in pay between rich and poor.<ref name=CityPayGap/>  Jones supports calls by the [[New Economics Foundation]] to introduce a 10:1 pay ratio, whereby the highest earner in a company or institution should earn no more than 10 times the lowest paid employee.<ref name=CityPayGap/><ref name=neftheratio/>  Jones's policy indicates that, if elected, this would be instigated in \"[[London City Hall|City Hall]], [[Transport for London]], the [[London Fire Brigade|fire brigade]] and [[Metropolitan Police Force|the police]]\",<ref name=\"jennyfreshideas\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/ |title=Jenny for London, Fresh Ideas for London |publisher=Jennyforlondon.org |date=1999-02-22 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307121140/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/ |archive-date=7 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and she claims \"more equal societies tend to be happier and healthier as well as experiencing lower levels of violent crime.\"<ref name=CityPayGap/>  This is a high priority for her candidacy and she states that \"this would mean that no City Hall cleaner could earn less than a tenth the Mayor\u2019s salary, and the Commissioner of the Met Police couldn\u2019t earn more than ten times a young recruit.\"<ref name=\"JennyfairPay\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fair-pay-city/ |title=Jenny for London, 25 November 2011, Make London a Fair Pay city |publisher=Jennyforlondon.org |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307070049/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fair-pay-city/ |archive-date=7 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Housing ===\n\nJones sees tackling homelessness as a key and achievable target and criticised Johnson's poor record: \"This rise in homelessness is unsurprising and depressing, but completely avoidable. One fifth of people became homeless just because their insecure tenancy ended, another fifth because they have had to move out of their parents\u2019 home into the incredibly expensive rental market. With housing benefit cuts now biting deep into people's incomes, this is only going to get worse.\"<ref name=\"GLAhomeless\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-lower-rents-and-more-security-needed-stop-rise-homelessness |title= Greater London Authority, Lower rents and more security needed to stop rise in homelessness|publisher=London.gov.uk |date=2012-03-08 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425041953/http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-lower-rents-and-more-security-needed-stop-rise-homelessness |archive-date=25 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Jones proposes to \"bring all grants for pan-London homelessness services into the GLA to protect frontline services, and work closely with homelessness organisations to ensure nobody needs to spend a second night out sleeping rough on the street.\"<ref name=\"wembleymatters\">{{cite web|last=Francis |first=Martin |url=http://wembleymatters.blogspot.co.uk/2012/03/housing-brent-crisis-and-jenny-jones.html |title=Housing: The Brent Crisis and Jenny Jones's Solutions|publisher=Wembleymatters.blogspot.co.uk |date=2012-03-17 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn her campaign for mayor, Jones has spoken against the inflationary effects of certain businesses, stating, \"we want to change the housing market from a playground for speculative investment to a source of secure, affordable homes\".<ref name=\"jennyhousing\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/housing/ |title=Jenny For London: Housing |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date=April 2012 |access-date=2012-04-02 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409120022/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/housing/ |archive-date=9 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  Jones has spoken in favour of community engagement in planning, specifically with regards to housing co-operatives.<ref name=jennyhousing/>  To help co-operatives develop, she proposes to \"establish the London Mutual Housing Company to help communities set-up Community Land Trusts, which will give them control over the design, development and management of permanently affordable homes.\"<ref name=jennyhousing/> In addition to this, she proposes a scheme to build affordable homes and to give communities the means to bring unused buildings back into use.<ref name=jennyhousing/> For the Greens fuel poverty is a big issue and \"Green London Assembly Members worked to secure the city's largest home insulation programme and demonstrated how it could be funded to reach over a million homes.\"<ref name=\"manifestohousing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/region/london/manifesto/housing.html |title=Let\u2019s make housing affordable |publisher=London Green Party |date= March 2012|accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== The European Union and Brexit ===\n\nJones is a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] and advocates the withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the [[European Union]]. Jones cites lack of democracy, waste and cost as her reasons for supporting [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ba_KHPl4OOg|title=Brexit med Jenny Jones fra Green Party|first=|last=Folkebev\u00e6gelsen mod EU|date=9 May 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> In October 2015 Jones gave her support to [[Vote Leave]], an organisation campaigning to leave the European Union in the [[proposed referendum on United Kingdom membership of the European Union|referendum in the UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/09/millionaire-donors-back-cross-party-campaign-to-leave-eu|title=Millionaire donors and business leaders back Vote Leave campaign to exit EU|author=|date=|work=[[The Guardian]]|via=[[Press Association]]}}</ref> Jones cited the [[Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership]] and EU policies of [[austerity]] as part of [[Greek government-debt crisis countermeasures|a measure to deal with Greece's national debt]] imposed by the [[European troika]] as reasons to support Brexit.<ref name=\"RottenEurope\">{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Jenny|title=Something rotten in the state of Europe|url=http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2946192/something_rotten_in_the_state_of_europe.html|accessdate=25 March 2016|work=The Ecologist|date=13 July 2015}}</ref> She has also argued that 'the EU exists on too large a scale for genuine democratic oversight and accountability. The Green party believes that small is beautiful \u2013 and the EU is gigantist in its very nature.'<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jun/08/eu-reform-green-brexit. Retrieved 7 November 2018.</ref>\n\n=== Climate and ecological crisis ===\n\nOn 17 November 2018, she joined the demonstration organised in London by [[Extinction Rebellion]].<ref name=Taylor-Gayle>{{Cite news |author=Matthew Taylor and Damien Gayle |title=Thousands gather to block London bridges in climate rebellion |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/nov/17/thousands-gather-to-block-london-bridges-in-climate-rebellion |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 November 2018 |access-date=17 November 2018 }}</ref> She told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that \"We are at the point where if we don\u2019t start acting and acting fast we are just going to wipe out our life support system\" and that \"Basically, conventional politics has failed us \u2013 it\u2019s even failed me and I\u2019m part of the system \u2013 so people have no other choice\".<ref name=Taylor-Gayle/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb}}\n* [https://jennyjones.org Jenny Jones' official website]\n* [http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2013/11/05/green-party%E2%80%99s-baroness-jones-of-moulsecoomb-to-be-introduced-into-second-chamber-today-at-14.30/ \"Green Party\u2019s Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb to be introduced into Second Chamber\"], 2013-11-05\n* {{Twitter}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ba_KHPl4OOg Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb [[YouTube]]]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/greenleaves2016/ Jenny Jones' \"Green Leaves\" campaign against membership of the European Union]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Chair of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]|years=1996 \u2013 1998|before=John Morrissey|after=?}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Nicky Gavron]] | title=[[Deputy Mayor of London]] | years=2003\u20132004 | after=[[Nicky Gavron]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DeputyLondonMayors}}\n{{GPEW|Elected}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Jenny}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sussex]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Southwark]]\n[[Category:English environmentalists]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the UCL Institute of Archaeology]]\n[[Category:People associated with the UCL Institute of Archaeology]]\n[[Category:Green Party Members of the London Assembly]]\n[[Category:Green Party of England and Wales life peers]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Jenny Jones}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Baroness Jones <br />of Moulsecoomb\n| honorific-suffix = [[Fellow of The Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]]\n| image            = Official portrait of Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb crop 2.jpg\n| caption          = \n| office1           = [[Deputy Mayor of London]]\n| term_start1       = 16 May 2003\n| term_end1         = 14 June 2004\n| 1blankname1       = [[Mayor of London|Mayor]]\n| 1namedata1        = [[Ken Livingstone]]\n| predecessor1      = [[Nicky Gavron]]\n| successor1        = [[Nicky Gavron]]\n|office         = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start = 5 November 2013<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| office3        = [[London Assembly|Member of the London Assembly]]<br/>as the [[List of London Assembly constituencies|11th Additional Member]]\n| term_start3      = 4 May 2000\n| term_end3        = 6 May 2016\n| successor3       = [[Caroline Russell]]\n|office4 = [[Councillor#United Kingdom|Councillor]] for [[Southwark London Borough Council]]\n|term_start4 = 4 May 2006\n|term_end4   = 6 May 2010\n|1blankname4      = [[Wards of the United Kingdom|Ward]]\n|1namedata4       = South Camberwell\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1949|12|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brighton]], [[Sussex]], England\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = British\n| spouse           = \n| party            = {{Nowrap|[[Green Party of England and Wales]]}}\n| relations        = \n| children         = \n| residence        = [[Southwark]], London, UK\n| alma_mater       = [[University College London]]\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = Archaeologist\n| signature        = \n| website          = {{url|http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-jones-of-moulsecoomb/4297|www.parliament.uk}}\n| footnotes        = \n| module           = <center>{{Listen|embed=yes|filename=Jenny Jones voice.ogg|title=Jones' voice|type=speech|description=<center>recorded February 2013</center>}} }}</center>\n\n'''Jennifer Helen Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb''', [[Fellow of The Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (born 23 December 1949) is a British politician and member of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]. She was until September 2019 the sole Green Party member in the House of Lords.\n\nJones represented the Green Party in the [[London Assembly]] from its creation in 2000 until standing down in 2016. She was the Green candidate for [[Mayor of London]] in the [[2012 London mayoral election|2012 election]], coming third with 4.48% of first preferences. She served as [[Deputy Mayor of London]] from May 2003 to June 2004. She was also the sole Green councillor on [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark Council]] from 2006 to 2010.<ref name=GPBio>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/individual/86 |title=Cllr. Jenny Jones AM's Green Party Website Biography |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref><ref name=southwarkgreen>[http://southwark.greenparty.org.uk/localsites/southwark/news/livingwage.html] ''Southwark Greens'' Stop paying council cleaners poverty wages.</ref>\n\nOn the London Assembly, Jones's prime areas of interest were transport, housing and planning, and policing, \"with a strong emphasis on sustainability and localism\".<ref name=GPBio/> In addition to her period as deputy mayor, Jones served as Chair of London Food, Green Transport Advisor, and Road Safety Ambassador<ref name=\"JonesTransport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/transport/|title=Jenny For London, March 12th 2011, A transport system that works|publisher=Jennyforlondon.org|date=|access-date=2012-03-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307045625/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/transport/|archive-date=7 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was announced at the beginning of August 2013 that she was to become the first Green [[life peer]] in the [[House of Lords]] since [[Tim Beaumont]] <ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/news/working-peerages-announced Working Peerages announced] Gov.uk</ref> She was introduced to the House of Lords on 5 November 2013.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/house-of-lords-24554846 \"Introductions\"] ''Democracy Live'' ([[House of Lords]]; published by the BBC), 5 November 2013; [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2013-11-05a.97.2 \"Introduction: Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb \u2013 in the House of Lords at 2:38 pm on 5th November 2013.\"] ''They Work For You'' 5 November 2013</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nJones mainly grew up on the [[Moulsecoomb]] estate in [[Brighton]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Vowles|first=Neil|title=Baroness of Moulsecoomb gives first speech in House of Lords|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/10847903.Baroness_of_Moulsecoomb_gives_first_speech_in_House_of_Lords|work=The Argus|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> with brief periods of time abroad in [[Lesotho]] and [[Seychelles]].<ref name=4talent>{{cite web |url=http://4talent.channel4.com/extra/evening-discussion-young-people-equality-diversity-and-mayor |title=An Evening Discussion: Young People, Equality, Diversity and the Mayor |publisher=Channel 4 |date=2012-02-22 |accessdate=2012-03-21 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She attended the co-educational Westlain Grammar School (now [[Falmer High School]]). Before entering politics, Jones worked as [[financial controller]] in London. She attended the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology|Institute of Archaeology]] at [[University College London]] as a [[mature student]], studying for an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in [[archaeology]].<ref name=GPBio/> She spent approximately ten years as an archaeologist in the Middle East, [[paleobotany|studying carbonised plant remains]], before embarking on a career in politics.<ref name=4talent/>\n\n==Political career==\nJones joined the [[Green Party of England and Wales]] in 1988. She has held several posts within the party, including the position of chair on the executive from 1995 to 1997.<ref name=GPBio/>\n\n=== London Assembly member ===\nIn [[2000 London Assembly election|the 2000 election]], Jones won a place in the inaugural [[London Assembly]] as part of a three-strong Green Group, including Councillor [[Darren Johnson]] AM and [[Victor Anderson (Green politician)|Victor Anderson]], who resigned in March 2003 and was replaced by [[Noel Lynch]] for the remainder of the term. The [[2004 London Assembly election|2004 GLA elections]] saw the Greens lose the seat held by Lynch, leaving Jones and Johnson as the two remaining members of the Green Group.\n\nIn May 2003, the Green Party, after some internal dissent, accepted an offer from the [[Mayor of London]], [[Ken Livingstone]], to nominate a [[Deputy Mayor of London|deputy mayor]]; they chose Jones, who held the post until June 2004. The offer was part of Livingstone's pledge to rotate the position of deputy mayor, although he later declined to offer the post to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] and had an offer to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] turned down.<ref name=\"deputyarticle\">{{cite news|author=Andrew Clark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/feb/19/uk.london |title='&#39;The Guardian'&#39;, February 19th 2003, '&#39;\"Greens select Livingstone's deputy\"'&#39; |newspaper=Guardian |date= 2003-02-19|accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nAs a London Assembly Member, Jenny Jones promoted the issues of [[road safety]], food, [[sustainable transport]], social justice and the police and civil liberties.<ref name=\"GLABio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/profile/jenny-jones |title=London Assembly Biography |publisher=London.gov.uk |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425034849/http://www.london.gov.uk/profile/jenny-jones |archive-date=25 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nShe was a member of the [[Metropolitan Police Authority]],<ref name=GLABio/> and has issued a report on traffic policing.<ref name=\"LawlessRoads\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/lawlessroad_report.pdf |title='&#39;Jenny Jones'&#39;, 2007, '&#39;\"London\u2019s Lawless Roads: Why traffic policing must improve to prevent road death and injury\"'&#39; |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303164439/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/lawlessroad_report.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> She sat on both the MPA's Strategic and Operational Policing Committee and Civil Liberties Panel.<ref name=\"SOPC\">[http://www.mpa.gov.uk/committees/sop/ Strategic Operational Policing Committee] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803122217/http://www.mpa.gov.uk/committees/sop/ |date=3 August 2009 }}, part of the Metropolitan Police Authority</ref><ref name=\"CLP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mpa.gov.uk/clp/ |title=Civil Liberties Panel |publisher=Mpa.gov.uk |date=2009-07-09 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220062041/http://www.mpa.gov.uk/clp/ |archive-date=20 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Elsewhere she put forward a motion and has put questions to the Mayor calling for progress on women's issues, specifically in relation to [[violence against women]] and support provision.<ref name=\"RapeCrisisCentres\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/21/boris-johnson-rape-crisis-centres|title=Boris Johnson urged to honour rape crisis centres pledge|author=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Mulholland|date=21 October 2009|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nJones chaired the Planning and Housing Committee, which issued a report on food growing and planning in London, Cultivating the Capital.<ref name=GLABio/> It concluded that \"London has only three or four days stocks of food should there be any disruption to supply\".<ref name=\"CultivatingCapital\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/the-london-assembly/publications/housing-planning/cultivating-capital-food-growing-and-planning-system-london |title='&#39;Planning and Housing Committee'&#39;, 1 January 2010, '&#39;\" Cultivating the Capital \u2013 Food growing and the planning system in London\"'&#39; |publisher=London.gov.uk |date=2010-01-06 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427081423/http://www.london.gov.uk/who-runs-london/the-london-assembly/publications/housing-planning/cultivating-capital-food-growing-and-planning-system-london |archive-date=27 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Jones issued an individual report in January 2010 on [[affordable housing]] in London, which determined that \"the cost of buying a home [in London] has risen twice as fast as incomes\".<ref name=\"ComingHome\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/cominghometoroost.pdf |title='&#39;Jenny Jones'&#39;, January 2010, '&#39;\"Coming Home to Roost: How two Mayors have failed to make housing affordable\"'&#39; |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303164452/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/cominghometoroost.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nShe was also a member of the Confirmation Hearings and Transport Committees.<ref name=GLABio/>\n\nShe previously held roles as the Mayor's Road Safety Ambassador and Green Transport advisor,<ref name= GPBio/> focusing on road safety and [[cycling in London]]<ref name=\"BikeRentalScheme\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/motoring/features/stop-your-engines-with-the-bike-rental-scheme-463855.html ''The Independent'', 4 September 2007 ''Stop Your Engines With the Bike Rental Scheme'']{{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref> respectively, as well as being the former Chair of London Food, a mayoral commission which \"aims to give Londoners fresher, healthier and more affordable food while reducing the environmental impact of our current food supply\".<ref name=\"LondonFood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lda.gov.uk/server.php?show=ConWebDoc.1499 |title='&#39;London Development Agency'&#39;, May 22, 2006, '&#39;\"Mayor of London unveils first strategy to improve London's food\" '&#39; |publisher=Lda.gov.uk |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224021144/http://www.lda.gov.uk/server.php?show=ConWebDoc.1499 |archive-date=24 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> As Chair, Jones was responsible for drawing up the Sustainable Food Strategy for London<ref name=\"LDAFoodStrategy\">{{cite web|url=http://moderngov.southwarksites.com/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=4231 |title='&#39;London Development Agency'&#39;, May 2006, '&#39;\"The Mayor\u2019s Food Strategy: Healthy and Sustainable Food for London\"'&#39; |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201180113/http://moderngov.southwarksites.com/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=4231 |archive-date= 1 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>  and chaired the Food Implementation Group overseeing the strategy<ref name=LondonFood/> More recently she also issued a report on the subject of food security in the capital.<ref name=\"SecureFood\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/secure_food.pdf |title='&#39;Jenny Jones'&#39;, 2008, '&#39;\"Why London Needs to Grow More Food\"'&#39; |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303164505/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/secure_food.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Southwark Councillor ===\nIn the [[2006 United Kingdom local elections|2006 local elections]], Jones was elected as a councillor for the South [[Camberwell]] ward in the [[London Borough of Southwark]], the Greens' first councillor in Southwark.<ref name=GPBio/> She came third in the ward, polling 1014 votes.<ref name=Southwark2006Election>[http://www.southwark.gov.uk/Uploads/File_27062.pdf Southwark Council | Your Council | Your Vote | Results of Borough Council Elections 4 May 2006 | Local Election Results 2006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927234853/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/Uploads/File_27062.pdf |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> In the [[2010 Southwark Council election|2010 elections]] she lost her seat, coming fifth with 1282 votes.<ref name=Southwark2010election>{{cite web |url=http://www.southwark.gov.uk/site/custom_scripts/viewelection.php?pollid=18 |title=Election results for South Camberwell &#124; Southwark Council |publisher=Southwark.gov.uk |date=2010-05-06 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511074109/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/site/custom_scripts/viewelection.php?pollid=18 |archive-date=11 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Parliamentary candidate ===\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]], she stood in the [[Dulwich and West Norwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Dulwich and West Norwood]] parliamentary constituency, coming fourth with 2,741 votes (6.5%).<ref name=2005Election>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwark.gov.uk/YourCouncil/YourVote/GeneralElection/resultsdawn.html |title=Council and democracy \u2013 Southwark Council |publisher=Southwark.gov.uk |date=2005-04-01 |access-date=2013-12-27 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201132135/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/YourCouncil/yourvote/GeneralElection/resultsdawn.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]], she stood in the [[Camberwell and Peckham (UK Parliament constituency)|Camberwell and Peckham]] parliamentary constituency, coming fourth with 1,361 votes (2.9%).<ref name=2010Election>{{cite web |url=http://www.southwark.gov.uk/info/1000/election_results/1617/general_election_2010 |title=General election 2010 \u2013 Southwark Council |publisher=Southwark.gov.uk |date=2010-05-06 |access-date=2012-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510030206/http://www.southwark.gov.uk/info/1000/election_results/1617/general_election_2010 |archive-date=10 May 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Mayoral candidate ===\nIn March 2011, Jones was selected as the Green Party's candidate for the 2012 London Mayoral election winning 67% of the votes against prominent Green Party members [[Shahrar Ali|Dr Shahrar Ali]] and Farid Bakht, stating \"At this time of savage cuts to essential services, London needs a Mayor who will create a fairer city and reduce the gap between rich and poor. These are hard times for people who care about quality services, local businesses, and protecting the most vulnerable members of our communities. I promise to make fighting cuts to housing benefit, the NHS and youth services a key part of my campaign to be Mayor.\"<ref name=jennyjonescandidate>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/20-03-2011-jenny-jones-london-mayor.html |title='&#39;Green Party'&#39;, 2012, '&#39;\"Jenny Jones Mayoral Candidate\"'&#39; |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date=2011-03-20 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nAt the election, she came third with 98,913 first preference votes, the highest position of a Green candidate to date, but lost her deposit, scoring less than 5% of the vote.\n\n=== House of Lords ===\nOn 20 September 2013, she was created a [[Life Peer]] taking the title '''Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb''', of [[Moulsecoomb]] in the County of [[East Sussex]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60638 |date=25 September 2013 |page=18895}}</ref> She was nominated for this appointment by her party after a ballot of members. She was introduced to the [[House of Lords]] on 5 November 2013.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> She became the first Green Party [[peer of the realm|peer]] since the death of [[Tim Beaumont]], in 2008. The only other Green parliamentarian is [[Caroline Lucas]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Brighton Pavilion]].\n\n==Political views==\n\n===Police===\n\nJones was a member of the [[Metropolitan Police Authority]] from its creation in 2000 \"and has worked on a wide range of policing issues, with a particular focus on road safety, violence against women, civil liberties and neighbourhood policing\" until it was disbanded in 2012.<ref name=\"Jones-mpa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mpa.gov.uk/about/people/members/02jones/ |title=Metropolitan Polica Authority, Jenny Jones MPA Member |publisher=Mpa.gov.uk |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205105526/http://www.mpa.gov.uk/about/people/members/02jones/ |archive-date=5 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"bbcmpaend\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-16525629 |title='&#39;, 12th January 2012, '&#39;\" MPA Holds Last Meeting\"'&#39; |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2012-01-12 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> She was outspoken about numerous issues including what she called mayor [[Boris Johnson]]'s demonisation of youth through the use of \"baseless\" rhetoric on \"soaring gang-membership and rising knife-crime\", suggesting the mayor created an unhelpful climate of fear.<ref name=\"evilyouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/2008-10-06-youth.html |title=Green Party, 2008, Myth-busting report criticises London Mayor's demonisation of youth |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date=2008-10-05 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> Jones then served as a member of the MPA's replacement body, the London Assembly Police and Crime Committee.<ref name=\"crimecom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/moderngov/mgCommitteeDetails.aspx?ID=240 |title=GLA, Police and Crime Committee details |publisher=London.gov.uk |date= 2012|accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2011 England Riots|riots in August 2011]], Jones and [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] leader, [[Caroline Lucas]] MP co-authored an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'', arguing that all cuts to policing should be postponed until December 2012 when a sufficient review of the events has occurred and the lessons from the [[London Olympics]] are learned, \"In the meantime, the police should focus on spending money wisely, and ensuring that police officers are not burdened with administrative tasks which take them away from frontline policing.\"<ref name=\"guadrianriots\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/aug/22/recover-riot-rebalance-inequality-society |title=The Guardian, August 22nd 2011, To recover from the riots we must rebalance the inequalities of society |newspaper=Guardian |date=2010-07-16 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |first=Caroline |last=Lucas}}</ref>\n\nAfter herself being [[kettled]] at a students demonstration, Jones was vociferously critical of this police tactic, telling the BBC the police used kettling to \"imprison peaceful campaigners and have shown they can't be trusted with such a powerful tactic\", suggesting \"The Met's reputation sinks even further every time they abuse their powers and it's time to stop this particular mistreatment\".<ref name=\"bbckettle\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12293394 |title=  Petition against Metropolitan Police 'kettling' tactic |publisher=BBC |date=2011-01-27 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Jones penned an editorial in ''[[The Guardian]]'' wherein she criticised the surveillance tactics of police on activists. After going through the process now available through the Data Protection Act to get the police report on herself, she found that she was labelled a potential \"domestic extremist\". She found that the report contained only publicly available information, such as tweets, and that nothing in it would suggest potentially dangerous activity. Jones has been under surveillance by the police's \"domestic extremism\" unit from 2001 until 2012, including the time during her attempt to become London's mayor.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jun/15/green-party-peer-put-on-database-of-extremists-by-police | title=Green party peer put on database of 'extremists' after police surveillance | accessdate=2016-01-11 | last1=Evans | first1=Rob | last2=Bowcott | first2=Owen | date=2014-06-15 | newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref> She viewed the revelation as both a violation of her privacy and a waste of police resources. She is now calling for a re-evaluation of police policies, especially in regards to political activists.<ref>Jenny Jones, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jun/16/domestic-extremist-metropolitan-police-spying-elected-politician The Met turned me into a domestic extremist \u2013 with tweets and trivia], The Guardian, 13 June 2014.</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, [[whistleblower]] [[Sergeant#United Kingdom|Sgt]] David Williams claimed that the police's \"domestic extremism\" unit [[Paper shredder|shredded]] records \"related to\" Jones in June 2014, the month Jones met with the unit pressing for answers.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jan/08/officer-claims-met-police-improperly-destroyed-files-on-green-party-peer | title=Officer claims Met police improperly destroyed files on Green party peer | accessdate=2016-01-11 | last=Evans | first=Rob | date=2016-01-08 | newspaper=The Guardian }}</ref>\n\n===Healthy eating===\nJones has argued for big changes to London's current food culture as Chair of London Food during Ken Livingstone's second Mayoral term. During her time as chair, London Food released its \u2018Food Strategy\u2019 aiming to \"help improve food in London\u2019s schools, hospitals and other public institutions\" and \"offer people on low income better access to healthy and affordable food\".<ref name=LondonFood/> Some of the reports key points were:\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Brian May, Jenny Jones at Animal mini-manifesto Launch.jpg|thumb|right|Jones with [[Queen (Band)|Queen]] guitarist [[Brian May]] and Assembly candidate Caroline Allen at the launch of the Animal mini-manifesto]] -->\n\n* \"Consideration will be given to the role that the public sector can play in helping to facilitate more producer collaborations and logistics and distribution partnerships, to help smaller producers to compete in the market, and to encourage new entrants\"\n* \"Directing better the existing resources available for business support for specialist food manufacturers and processors, particularly on consumer market trends and collaborative working, and particularly for [[small and medium sized enterprises]] (SMEs) that reflect London\u2019s diverse communities\"\n* \"Promote and expand opportunities for small-scale food production for individuals and communities through gardens, orchards, schools, allotments and parks and open spaces\"\n* \"Continue to increase the amount of organic and local food provided through public sector services in London in response to growing consumer demand\"\n* \"Research and promote the positive benefits of nutritious food for children.\"<ref name=LondonFood/>\n\nIn 2008, Jones released a report \u2018Why London Needs to Grow More Food\u2019 stressing \"The Mayor of London has planning and development powers, which could be used to support widespread urban agriculture in London through the commercial and voluntary sectors, community-led social enterprises, and by engaging the unemployed, elderly, and lower skilled groups\".<ref name=SecureFood/>\n\n===Transport===\nJones commissioned the initial [[Transport for London]] report into promoting cycling that paved the way for the London Cycle-hire scheme.<ref name=JonesTransport/> Ashok Sinha, Chief executive of the [[London Cycling Campaign]], said of Jones \"In 2008 the London Cycling Campaign gave Jenny Jones a Special Award for her Lifetime Services to cycling. This was in recognition of her success in helping to push cycling into mainstream politics, her efforts to deliver many cycling projects on the ground, and her energies as cycling champion in general.\".<ref name=JonesTransport/>\nIn a confrontation with the Mayor over cycle safety, Johnson said:<ref name=\"mqtcycling\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mBup5U_9Ycw |title=Mayor\u2019s Question Time, November 2011, Jenny Jones AM questions Boris Johnson on cycle safety |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|(it is) your duty as an honest politician to tell people the truth that cycling is actually getting safer, when you consider the number of people on the roads.}}\n\nJohnson's advisor wrote to Jones claiming there had been:\n\n{{quote|... a reduced number of cycling collisions in the last ten years}}\n\nWhich turned out not to be true.<ref name=\"cycledanger\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-am-new-tfl-figures-show-cycling-not-getting-safer |title=GLA, February 2012, Cycling not getting safer |publisher=London.gov.uk |date=2012-02-02 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425205633/http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-am-new-tfl-figures-show-cycling-not-getting-safer |archive-date=25 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>  In a written statement Jones said, \"we know that cycle safety is the big problem which puts Londoners off jumping on their bikes. There are a growing number of deaths and injuries of cyclists and trying to cover that up by issuing factually inaccurate statements won\u2019t change the reality,\" continuing, \"We urgently need to fix the most dangerous junctions and reverse the Mayor\u2019s policy of giving priority to motorised traffic. The Mayor needs to stand his policy on its head and give legal priority on many local roads to pedestrians and cyclists.\"<ref name=cycledanger/> Jones has also been critical of Johnson's neglect of cycling in outer London, stating \"given that 70% of the potential new cyclists identified by TfL are outside of inner and central London, it is shocking that the Transport Strategy has no clear plan for cycling in the suburbs and outer London.\"<ref name=\"Transportresponse\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/response-statement-intent-070809.pdf |title=GLA Consultation Response to Mayor\u2019s Transport Strategy Statement of Intent|format=PDF |date=July 2009 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516170549/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/members/jonesj/docs/response-statement-intent-070809.pdf |archive-date=16 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nJones has spoken against Boris Johnson's transport policy of \"making motoring cheaper in London, whilst public transport fares are raised above inflation\".<ref name=\"Transportresponse\" /> At Mayor's question time, Jones highlighted a \"promise\" Johnson had made in 2008 to make all new buses  [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]] by 2012 when in reality less than 10% had met this criterion.<ref name=\"mqthybrid\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H3gg98QWM0A&noredirect=1 |title=Mayor's Question time, February 2012, Jones grills Boris on Busses |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref> Jones wishes for a reduction in the burden for Londoners felt by Johnson's price increases and proposes a reduction in fares of about 4%.<ref name=\"artslondonnews\">{{cite web|last=Starkey |first=Gerard |url=http://www.artslondonnews.co.uk/20120131-green-party-jenny-jones |title=Arts London News, 3 February 2012, London Mayor elections: Jenny Jones|publisher=Artslondonnews.co.uk |date=2012-02-03 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512214413/http://www.artslondonnews.co.uk/20120131-green-party-jenny-jones |archive-date=12 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Jones supported the [[congestion charge]] as a way to lower pollution and road casualties and spoke against the mayor's cancellation of the Western extension, arguing that it made London dirtier, more crowded and less safe.<ref name=\"guardiancc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/28/london-boris |title=The Guardian, 28 November 2008, Boris's C-charge blunder|newspaper=Guardian |date=2010-07-16 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |first=Jenny |last=Jones}}</ref> Jones favours replacing the congestion charge with a \"smart, pay-as-you drive scheme\".<ref name=\"manifestotransport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/region/london/manifesto/transport.html |title=London Green Party, March 2012, Our Manifesto: Let's transform public transport |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===The City===\nIn her statement of policy for the 2012 election, Jones proposes several ideas to bring \"a renaissance of micro, small and medium businesses\" in order to spread \"wealth to all Londoners\", seeking \"a financial services sector that works for them\".<ref name=\"GreenCity\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Fresh-ideas-for-banking.pdf |title=Jenny for London, February 2012, Making the City work for London |format=PDF |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308165900/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Fresh-ideas-for-banking.pdf |archive-date=8 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She argues for a system that rewards good long term investment \"instead of trying to make a fast buck\" and proposes a good financial example to be Sweden's [[Handelsbanken]] which gives \"good basic pay and no bonuses.\"<ref name=GreenCity/> One of her candidacy's most distinct positions is with respect to [[The City of London|The City]] with ambitions to \"Abolish the City of London Corporation and replace it with a democratic London borough\", \"support new institutions like local community banks focused on lending to small businesses and social enterprises\" and \"Promote building societies and credit unions and lobby the Government to put its remaining nationalised banking assets into one of these models rather than a bank\".<ref name=GreenCity/> Elsewhere Jones has been critical of excessive top-level remuneration, stating, \"It's difficult not to feel enraged\" by statistics showing the average FTSE CEO earns 565 times the national average.<ref name=\"CityPayGap\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/oct/14/london-pay-gap-public-sector |title=The Guardian, 14 October 2011, London\u2019s City Hall must lead on closing Britain\u2019s pay gap|newspaper=Guardian |date=2011-10-14 |accessdate=2012-03-21 |first=Jenny |last=Jones}}</ref>\n\n===Fair Pay ratio===\nJones and the Green Party, alongside others,<ref name=\"neftheratio\">{{cite web |url=http://neweconomics.org/publications/the-ratio |title=The New Economics Foundation, 4 July 2011, Common sense controls for executive pay and revitalising UK business |publisher=Neweconomics.org |date=2011-07-04 |access-date=2012-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120185039/http://www.neweconomics.org/publications/the-ratio |archive-date=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> are deeply critical of the inequalities in pay between rich and poor.<ref name=CityPayGap/>  Jones supports calls by the [[New Economics Foundation]] to introduce a 10:1 pay ratio, whereby the highest earner in a company or institution should earn no more than 10 times the lowest paid employee.<ref name=CityPayGap/><ref name=neftheratio/>  Jones's policy indicates that, if elected, this would be instigated in \"[[London City Hall|City Hall]], [[Transport for London]], the [[London Fire Brigade|fire brigade]] and [[Metropolitan Police Force|the police]]\",<ref name=\"jennyfreshideas\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/ |title=Jenny for London, Fresh Ideas for London |publisher=Jennyforlondon.org |date=1999-02-22 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307121140/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/ |archive-date=7 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and she claims \"more equal societies tend to be happier and healthier as well as experiencing lower levels of violent crime.\"<ref name=CityPayGap/>  This is a high priority for her candidacy and she states that \"this would mean that no City Hall cleaner could earn less than a tenth the Mayor\u2019s salary, and the Commissioner of the Met Police couldn\u2019t earn more than ten times a young recruit.\"<ref name=\"JennyfairPay\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fair-pay-city/ |title=Jenny for London, 25 November 2011, Make London a Fair Pay city |publisher=Jennyforlondon.org |date= |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307070049/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fair-pay-city/ |archive-date=7 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Housing ===\n\nJones sees tackling homelessness as a key and achievable target and criticised Johnson's poor record: \"This rise in homelessness is unsurprising and depressing, but completely avoidable. One fifth of people became homeless just because their insecure tenancy ended, another fifth because they have had to move out of their parents\u2019 home into the incredibly expensive rental market. With housing benefit cuts now biting deep into people's incomes, this is only going to get worse.\"<ref name=\"GLAhomeless\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-lower-rents-and-more-security-needed-stop-rise-homelessness |title= Greater London Authority, Lower rents and more security needed to stop rise in homelessness|publisher=London.gov.uk |date=2012-03-08 |access-date=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425041953/http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_assembly_member/news-jenny-jones-lower-rents-and-more-security-needed-stop-rise-homelessness |archive-date=25 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Jones proposes to \"bring all grants for pan-London homelessness services into the GLA to protect frontline services, and work closely with homelessness organisations to ensure nobody needs to spend a second night out sleeping rough on the street.\"<ref name=\"wembleymatters\">{{cite web|last=Francis |first=Martin |url=http://wembleymatters.blogspot.co.uk/2012/03/housing-brent-crisis-and-jenny-jones.html |title=Housing: The Brent Crisis and Jenny Jones's Solutions|publisher=Wembleymatters.blogspot.co.uk |date=2012-03-17 |accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\nIn her campaign for mayor, Jones has spoken against the inflationary effects of certain businesses, stating, \"we want to change the housing market from a playground for speculative investment to a source of secure, affordable homes\".<ref name=\"jennyhousing\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/housing/ |title=Jenny For London: Housing |publisher=Greenparty.org.uk |date=April 2012 |access-date=2012-04-02 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409120022/http://www.jennyforlondon.org/fresh-ideas/housing/ |archive-date=9 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  Jones has spoken in favour of community engagement in planning, specifically with regards to housing co-operatives.<ref name=jennyhousing/>  To help co-operatives develop, she proposes to \"establish the London Mutual Housing Company to help communities set-up Community Land Trusts, which will give them control over the design, development and management of permanently affordable homes.\"<ref name=jennyhousing/> In addition to this, she proposes a scheme to build affordable homes and to give communities the means to bring unused buildings back into use.<ref name=jennyhousing/> For the Greens fuel poverty is a big issue and \"Green London Assembly Members worked to secure the city's largest home insulation programme and demonstrated how it could be funded to reach over a million homes.\"<ref name=\"manifestohousing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/region/london/manifesto/housing.html |title=Let\u2019s make housing affordable |publisher=London Green Party |date= March 2012|accessdate=2012-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== The European Union and Brexit ===\n\nJones is a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] and advocates the withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the [[European Union]]. Jones cites lack of democracy, waste and cost as her reasons for supporting [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ba_KHPl4OOg|title=Brexit med Jenny Jones fra Green Party|first=|last=Folkebev\u00e6gelsen mod EU|date=9 May 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> In October 2015 Jones gave her support to [[Vote Leave]], an organisation campaigning to leave the European Union in the [[proposed referendum on United Kingdom membership of the European Union|referendum in the UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/09/millionaire-donors-back-cross-party-campaign-to-leave-eu|title=Millionaire donors and business leaders back Vote Leave campaign to exit EU|author=|date=|work=[[The Guardian]]|via=[[Press Association]]}}</ref> Jones cited the [[Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership]] and EU policies of [[austerity]] as part of [[Greek government-debt crisis countermeasures|a measure to deal with Greece's national debt]] imposed by the [[European troika]] as reasons to support Brexit.<ref name=\"RottenEurope\">{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Jenny|title=Something rotten in the state of Europe|url=http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2946192/something_rotten_in_the_state_of_europe.html|accessdate=25 March 2016|work=The Ecologist|date=13 July 2015}}</ref> She has also argued that 'the EU exists on too large a scale for genuine democratic oversight and accountability. The Green party believes that small is beautiful \u2013 and the EU is gigantist in its very nature.'<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jun/08/eu-reform-green-brexit. Retrieved 7 November 2018.</ref>\n\n=== Climate and ecological crisis ===\n\nOn 17 November 2018, she joined the demonstration organised in London by [[Extinction Rebellion]].<ref name=Taylor-Gayle>{{Cite news |author=Matthew Taylor and Damien Gayle |title=Thousands gather to block London bridges in climate rebellion |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/nov/17/thousands-gather-to-block-london-bridges-in-climate-rebellion |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 November 2018 |access-date=17 November 2018 }}</ref> She told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that \"We are at the point where if we don\u2019t start acting and acting fast we are just going to wipe out our life support system\" and that \"Basically, conventional politics has failed us \u2013 it\u2019s even failed me and I\u2019m part of the system \u2013 so people have no other choice\".<ref name=Taylor-Gayle/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb}}\n* [https://jennyjones.org Jenny Jones' official website]\n* [http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2013/11/05/green-party%E2%80%99s-baroness-jones-of-moulsecoomb-to-be-introduced-into-second-chamber-today-at-14.30/ \"Green Party\u2019s Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb to be introduced into Second Chamber\"], 2013-11-05\n* {{Twitter}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ba_KHPl4OOg Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb [[YouTube]]]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/greenleaves2016/ Jenny Jones' \"Green Leaves\" campaign against membership of the European Union]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Chair of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]|years=1996 \u2013 1998|before=John Morrissey|after=?}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Nicky Gavron]] | title=[[Deputy Mayor of London]] | years=2003\u20132004 | after=[[Nicky Gavron]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DeputyLondonMayors}}\n{{GPEW|Elected}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Jenny}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sussex]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Southwark]]\n[[Category:English environmentalists]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the UCL Institute of Archaeology]]\n[[Category:People associated with the UCL Institute of Archaeology]]\n[[Category:Green Party Members of the London Assembly]]\n[[Category:Green Party of England and Wales life peers]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe City:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: long term \u2192 long-term", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jenny_Jones,_Baroness_Jones_of_Moulsecoomb"}
{"title_page": "WSBN", "text_new": "{{short description|ESPN Radio affiliate in Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n | name             = WSBN\n | image            = WSBN-Sports-Capitol-logo-2019.png\n | city             = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n | area             = [[Washington metropolitan area]]\n | branding         = ''ESPN 630 D.C.''\n | slogan           = The Sports Capitol\n | frequency        = 630 [[kilohertz|kHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n | airdate          = October 12, [[1925 in radio|1925]]\n | translator       = \n | format           = [[Sports radio|Sports]]\n | power            = 10,000 [[watt]]s (day)<br>2,700 watts (night)\n | class            = B\n | facility_id      = 73250\n | coordinates      = {{coord|39|08|2|N|77|18|14|W|type:landmark_region:US-DC_source:FCC|display=inline,title}}\n | callsign_meaning = '''SBN''' is a close sound-alike to '''ESPN'''\n | former_callsigns = WMAL (1925\u20132019)\n | affiliations     = [[ESPN Radio]]<br>[[Washington Redskins]] Radio Network\n | owner            = [[Cumulus Media]]\n | licensee         = Radio License Holdings LLC\n | sister_stations  = [[WMAL-FM]]\n | webcast          = {{listen live|http://www.sportscapitoldc.com}}\n | website          = [http://www.sportscapitoldc.com sportscapitoldc.com]\n}}\n'''WSBN''' (630 [[Hertz|kHz]]) is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[AM broadcasting|AM]] [[sports radio|sports]] [[radio station]] [[City of license|licensed]] to [[Washington, D.C.]] and serving the [[Washington Metropolitan Area|Washington metro area]]. It operates with 10,000 [[watt]]s in the daytime and 2,700 watts at night using a [[directional antenna]] around the clock. WSBN's studios are on Jenifer Street in Northwest Washington.<ref>[http://www.wmal.com/station-information/ WMAL.com/station-information]</ref>  The [[transmitter]] located off Black Rock Road in [[Germantown, Maryland]].<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/info/WMAL-AM Radio-Locator.com/WMAL-AM]</ref>\n\nWSBN is owned and operated by [[Cumulus Media]] and is [[network affiliate|affiliated]] with [[ESPN Radio]]. It is one of the oldest radio stations in the Washington [[media market]], continuously on the air from 1925. For most of its history, the station operated as '''WMAL'''; on July 1, 2019, its [[Talk radio|talk]] programming was moved exclusively to co-owned [[WMAL-FM]] at 105.9 [[Hertz|MHz]], which had simulcast with 630 AM since 2011.\n\n==Programming==\n{{as of|2019|7}}, WSBN's programming consists of the national ESPN Radio schedule, though the station intends to produce some local programming.<ref name=\"wp-wmalamsports\">{{cite news |last1=Allen |first1=Scott |title=D.C. is getting a third sports talk radio station with the launch of ESPN 630 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/14/dc-is-getting-third-sports-talk-radio-station-with-launch-espn/ |accessdate=July 2, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 14, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early years===\nWMAL first went on the air on October 12, 1925, using [[Call sign|call letters]] incorporating the initials of Martin A. Leese, a local [[optician]] who began selling radio sets at 720 11th Street NW in Washington, D.C.<ref>\"A Radio for Every Purse\". (August 15, 1926). ''The Washington Post'', p. F7</ref> He started WMAL as a low-power station. The shutdown of station [[WCAP (defunct)|WCAP]] left Washington with  WRC (now [[WTEM]]) as its only high-power station, so local business leaders affiliated with the City Club of Washington banded together to create a second high-powered station. Their original plan was to buy WCAP and convert it to a municipal station, but instead they worked with Leese to boost WMAL's signal and make it the city's second large station.<ref>\"City Club to Help Develop New Radio Station in Capital\". (September 26, 1926). ''The Washington Post'', p. M13</ref> The new high-power WMAL went on the air from studios at 710-712 11th Street NW on October 2, 1926, with former WCAP announcer William T. Pierson as director and with a policy of encouraging young broadcasting talent in hopes of creating \"a people's forum\".<ref>\"New Radio Station in First Program\".  (October 3, 1926).  ''The Washington Post'', p. M14</ref>\n\nIn 1927, Leese left his optical business to focus full-time on running the station, and the following year the [[Federal Radio Commission]]'s national frequency allocation plan assigned WMAL the AM 630 frequency, which it still uses today. WMAL was a [[CBS Radio]] [[Network affiliate]] from 1928 until October 19, 1932, and then was briefly unaffiliated until joining the [[NBC Blue Network]] in January 1933. The Blue Network later became [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], with which WMAL was affiliated for many years, and which owned WMAL for several decades.\n\nBy mid-1932, M. R. Baker had been appointed manager of the station, and Kenneth H. Berkeley was appointed station director of WMAL in 1933. While still owned by the Leese family, WMAL was eventually leased to the [[NBC|National Broadcasting Company]] in 1934, joining it with [[owned-and-operated station]] WRC.\n\nNBC's Washington vice president Frank M. Russell supervised the operation of both WMAL and WRC by 1935 when studios were moved from the National Press Building to the Trans-Lux Theatre Building, 724 14th Street NW. Transmitting facilities continued to be located at 712 Eleventh Street NW.\n\nIn the late months of 1937, the lease to NBC was terminated, with station operation reverting to the Leese Family interests. NBC, however, continued to operate it under a managerial agreement executed in fall 1937. Norman Leese was president of WMAL's licensee at that time. On May 1, 1938, the M.A. Leese Radio Corporation was acquired by publishers of the now-defunct ''[[Washington Star|Washington Evening Star]]'' [[newspaper]], a family-owned concern headed by board chairman and president Samuel H. Kauffman. Norman Leese remained president and K. H. Berkeley continued as general manager of WMAL.\n\nThe operating arrangement between NBC and the M.A. Leese Radio Corporation ended in February 1942. The station then reverted to the direct control of the Evening Star Broadcasting Company, of which K. H. Berkeley was executive vice president. Berkeley was also WMAL's general manager. In October 1947, WMAL-TV signed on as the first high-band [[VHF]] [[television]] station in the United States. It became an ABC Network affiliate a year later.\n\nBy 1946, S. H. Kauffman, president and part owner of the ''Evening Star'', was given additional duties as president of its broadcasting subsidiary, the Evening Star Broadcasting Company, until his resignation in August 1954. His replacement as general manager was Frederick S. Houwink.\n\nAlso in 1954, John W. Thompson, Jr. replaced S. H. Kauffman as president of Evening Star Broadcasting Co.\n\nAndrew Martin Ockershausen was appointed station manager of WMAL in 1960. One of Ockershausen's first moves was to team [[Frank Harden]] with [[Jackson Weaver]] for WMAL's morning drive show after the duo had a successful tryout hosting an evening comedy show patterned after [[Bob and Ray]]; ''Harden and Weaver'' took off in popularity and quickly became the top-rated morning show in the Washington market, featuring a blend of news, interviews, light music and comedy.<ref>Harden and Weaver, 1983. p. 88 & 112</ref><ref name=\"washington\">''Frank Harden Signs Off At WMAL; After 50 Years, Radio Voice Leaves With Little Fanfare'' by Marc Fisher ''The Washington Post'' January 7, 1998  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160325225807/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-647106.html Highbeam.com]</ref><ref name=\"sillier\">'' '60s Radio Days: A Sillier, Simpler Time''. Marc Fisher, ''The Washington Post'', September 13, 1999; Page A1.</ref>\n\nIn 1962, Fred Houwink became a company vice president while continuing as WMAL's general manager. In 1965 Houwink was named vice president of Evening Star Broadcasting and Ockershausen was elevated to general manager of WMAL.\n\nIn 1970 Houwink retired and Ockershausen was named vice president, operations. Also in 1970 Richard S. Stakes was named general manager and Harold L. Green was named station manager. In 1974 Charles A. Macatee became WMAL's general manager.\n\n===ABC years===\nIn early January 1976, the Evening Star Broadcasting Company's WMAL, [[WLVW|WMAL-FM]] and [[WJLA|WMAL-TV]] and majority control of the ailing newspaper were acquired from the Kauffman, Noyes and Adams families by publisher [[Joe Allbritton|Joseph L. Albritton]]\u2019s Perpetual Corporation and Albritton became board chairman and chief owner of WMAL's license. On January 21, 1976, WMAL's licensee name was changed to ''Washington Star Communications of Delaware, Inc.'' Richard S. Stakes became station president, but resigned in December 1976. Mr. Albritton then assumed the presidency, with Robert Nelson becoming president of the broadcasting division. General Manager Charles Macatee resigned in January 1977.\n\nA requirement of the purchase of the Evening Star properties included the sale of the radio or television properties. In March 1977, WMAL and WMAL-FM were spun off to ABC Radio, while the TV station was retained and became [[WJLA|WJLA-TV]], named after Albritton's initials. ABC paid $16 million for WMAL and WMAL-FM, a record price for radio properties at that time. Andrew Ockershausen was appointed executive vice president.\n\n[[File:WMAL 630 old.png|left|thumb|200px|WMAL logo used until 2009.]]On January 3, 1986, [[Capital Cities Communications|Capital Cities]] and [[ABC, Inc.]] merged in a $3.52 billion deal. Thomas S. Murphy was chairman and CEO of the new firm. Frederick Weinhaus became president and general manager following the resignation of Andrew Ockershausen in March 1986. Weinhaus was transferred to [[Citadel Media|ABC Radio]] New York in January 1988. His replacement in May 1988 was Thomas Bresnahan, who continued in that role until his retirement in 2002.\n\nWMAL morning co-host Jackson Weaver died on October 20, 1992, with ''Harden and Weaver'' still at or near the top of the local ratings; Weaver also garnered fame nationally as the first voice of [[Smokey Bear]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jackson Weaver, 72, Voice of Smokey Bear |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/22/obituaries/jackson-weaver-72-voice-of-smokey-bear.html?pagewanted=1 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 22, 1992 |language=en}}</ref> Frank Harden continued the morning show with co-hosts [[Tim Brant]] and Andy Parks until his retirement in 1998.<ref name=\"washington\" /> Brant and Parks continued until Brant's departure in May 2002,<ref>https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2003/dec/15/20031215-093650-7060r/</ref> his replacement would be former congressman [[Fred Grandy]].\n\nBy the late 1990s, WMAL transitioned its talk lineup into one similar to sister station [[WABC (AM)|WABC]] in New York City, with an emphasis on conservative talk.\n\n[[File:WMAL (AM) former logo (2009-2011).png|thumb|200px|WMAL logo, 2009-2011]] [[Chris Berry (broadcaster)|Chris Berry]] was named president and general manager November 19, 2002. Prior to joining WMAL, Berry was vice president, radio for [[ABC News]], based in New York. In August 2005, host [[Michael Graham (radio personality)|Michael Graham]] was fired after refusing to apologize for calling the Council on American-Islamic Relations (CAIR) a \"terrorist organization.\"\n\n===Citadel and Cumulus years===\nABC sold its non-[[Radio Disney]] and [[ESPN Radio]] stations, including WMAL, to [[Citadel Broadcasting]] in 2007; Citadel merged with Cumulus Media on September 16, 2011.<ref name=abj-citadelcumulus>{{cite news|title=Cumulus now owns Citadel Broadcasting|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2011/09/16/cumulus-now-owns-citadel-broadcasting.html|accessdate=September 16, 2011|newspaper=Atlanta Business Journal|date=September 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLongtime Washington broadcaster [[Chris Core]] was dismissed from WMAL in 2008 as part of a broad cost-cutting move; his replacement, [[Austin Hill (radio personality)|Austin Hill]], was dropped in February 2009 due to Levin's show expanding and Sliwa's show moving up an hour. Plante, a popular talk host who hosted evenings and later middays, was yanked in favor of Joe Scarborough's ''[[Morning Joe]]'' in April 2009, only to return to middays six months later after Scarborough's show was cancelled.\n\nBy late 2009, WMAL's morning-drive through midnight weekday format was uninterrupted conservative talk, with a lineup of [[Fred Grandy]] and Andy Parks, [[Chris Plante]], [[Rush Limbaugh]], [[Sean Hannity]], [[Mark Levin]], [[Joe Scarborough]], and [[Curtis Sliwa]]. Weekends include gardening host Jos Roozen, investing adviser [[Ric Edelman]] and lawyer Michael Collins. [[John Batchelor]] replaced Sliwa in November 2009. In April 2010, Parks was laid off from the station, resulting in Plante's and Grandy's shows being merged. At the same time, Scarborough's show was put on extended hiatus. Austin Hill began filling in the middays for the time being, while [[Mark Simone]] handled Scarborough's shift. Grandy left WMAL in March 2011.\n\n[[File:WMAL-AMandFM 2014.png|200px|thumb|left|Logo during simulcast with 105.9 FM, 2011\u20132019]]\nOn September 19, 2011, WMAL began simulcasting its AM signal on 105.9 FM, now [[WMAL-FM]]. The former WMAL-FM, renamed WRQX in 1977, has since become [[WLVW]]; it remained co-owned with WMAL until 2019.\n\nIn 2017, WMAL started broadcasting [[Washington Redskins]] games as an affiliate station for the first time since the team's [[Super Bowl XXVI]] win in 1992. WMAL previously carried the team's games from 1942 to 1956, and again from 1963 to 1991. [[WTEM]] (570 AM), a new sports station at the time, acquired the radio broadcast rights from WMAL for the [[1992 NFL season]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Scott |title=Redskins games will be back on WMAL for first time since last Super Bowl win |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2017/02/16/redskins-games-will-be-back-on-wmal-for-first-time-since-last-super-bowl-win/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 3, 2017, WMAL's weekday lineup consisted of local talent [[Brian Wilson (news correspondent)|Brian Wilson]] and Mary Walter in the morning, then Chris Plante, followed by the syndicated Rush Limbaugh, then [[Larry O'Connor (radio host)|Larry O'Connor]] hosts a local afternoon drive show, followed by the syndicated shows of [[Mark Levin]], [[John Batchelor]], and overnight the syndicated show [[Red Eye Radio]], hosted by [[Eric Harley]] and [[Gary McNamara]].  Brian Wilson was released in May 2017.\n\n===Flip to sports talk===\nOn June 13, 2019, it was announced that WMAL would break away from the simulcast with WMAL-FM and flip to [[ESPN Radio]] on July 1, 2019 as ''ESPN 630''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/local-networks/espn-cumulus-dc-sports-radio-redskins.html|title=ESPN and Cumulus will launch a new D.C. ESPN Radio station|date=2019-06-14|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/187183/wmal-a-f-washington-d-c-to-split-simulcast-am-to-f|title=WMAL-A-F/Washington, D.C. To Split Simulcast, AM To Flip To Sports As ESPN 630, The Sports Capitol|website=All Access|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> WMAL replaced WTEM as ESPN Radio's Washington, D.C. affiliate, though both stations continue to share Redskins games, with WTEM as flagship.<ref name=\"wp-wmalamsports\"/> Concurrent with the format change, WMAL changed its call letters to WSBN;<ref name=\"fcc-callsigns\">{{cite web |url=https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=73250&Callsign=WSBN |title=Call Sign History (WSBN) |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref> prior to the change, it had been Washington's oldest station to be operating under its original call letters.\n\n==Studios==\n[[File:Wmal 20090125 133755.jpg|thumb|right|The former WMAL radio tower site in [[Bethesda, MD]]]]\nWMAL broadcast from various facilities in Washington, D.C., and suburban [[Maryland]] until July 25, 1973, when it settled in at its current studio facility at 4400 Jenifer Street NW in Washington, two blocks from the city's border with [[Maryland]].\n\nWMAL's former transmitting facility, located in the Bradley Hills section of suburban [[Bethesda, Maryland]], once housed studios for WMAL-AM and WMAL-FM. Cumulus put the 75-acre site for sale in February 2015; in the summer of 2016, it was sold to the Toll Brothers company, who has plans to turn the site into a housing development.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radioworld.com/business-and-law/0009/wmal-tower-site-up-for-sale/333530 |title=WMAL Tower Site Up For Sale |work=Radio World |last=Stimson |first=Leslie |date=February 9, 2015 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radioworld.com/business-and-law/0009/wmal-tower-site-demolition-begins/336515 |title=WMAL Tower Site Demolition Begins |work=Radio World |last=Reigart |first=Emily M. |date=September 20, 2016 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/Web-2016/Developer-of-WMAL-Radio-Towers-Site-Unveils-Latest-Plans-to-Skeptical-Public/ |title=Updated: Developer of WMAL Radio Towers Site Unveils Latest Plans to Skeptical Public |work=[[Bethesda Magazine]] |last=Kraut |first=Aaron |date=April 11, 2016 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Planning-Board-Approves-Proposal-for-309-Homes-at-WMAL-Tower-Site/ |title=Planning Board Approves Proposal for 309 Homes at WMAL Tower Site |work=[[Bethesda Magazine]] |last=Rodgers |first=Bethany |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radiomagonline.com/industry/0003/county-planning-board-approves-plan-for-wmal-site/38985 |title=County Planning Board Approves Plan for WMAL Site |work=[[Radio (magazine)|Radio Magazine]] |last=Reigart |first=Emily M. |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 12, 2016, WMAL was granted a [[Federal Communications Commission]] [[construction permit]] to move from their 91-year-old site in Bethesda to the [[WWRC]] transmitter site in [[Germantown, Maryland|Germantown]] and decrease night power to 2,700 watts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101726202&formid=301&fac_num=73250 |title=Application for Construction Permit for Commercial Broadcast Station |work=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |date=May 12, 2016 |accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref> Transmissions from the Bethesda transmitter site ceased on the afternoon of May 1, 2018.\n\n===Personalities===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2010}}\nAmong the WMAL broadcasters over the years have been [[Frank Harden]] and [[Jackson Weaver]], who co-hosted WMAL's morning show for more than four decades until Weaver's death in the early 1990s; Tom Gauger, who also spent several decades at WMAL; [[Arthur Godfrey]], a national radio and early-TV personality who briefly broadcast on WMAL in 1933 as \"Red\" Godfrey; Bill Mayhugh, a mellow-voiced overnight broadcaster; and [[Ken Beatrice]], a sports talk radio pioneer who hosted a call-in show from 1977 to 1995.\n\nThe station also kept a local following for a time by broadcasting [[sports]] games featuring the [[Washington Redskins]] and [[University of Maryland, College Park]] Terrapins. Legendary jazz authority [[Felix Grant]] broadcast on WMAL for decades.\n\nSupport of the local community has been a tradition for WMAL, which founded such innovative fund-raisers as the Leukemia Radiothon and the Gross National Parade, which supported the D.C. Police Boys & Girls Club.\n\n===News===\nIn addition to providing talk programming, WMAL provided local news coverage. With morning anchor Bill Thompson,<ref>[http://wmal.com/Article.asp?id=450426&spid=18558 Bill Thompson]</ref> afternoon anchor Mark Weaver<ref>[http://wmal.com/Article.asp?id=192504&spid=18558 Mark Weaver - WMAL biography]</ref> and the team covers news stories affecting the Washington DC area.\n\n===Jerry Klein's 2006 radio experiment===\n{{main|Jerry Klein's 2006 radio experiment}}\nThe station aired a [[Talk radio|radio talk show]] on November 26, 2006 to gauge his audience's reaction to saying that \"force should be applied to ensure that all Muslims in America wear identifying markers....\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In U.S., fear and distrust of Muslims runs deep | author=Bernd Debusmann | publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=December 1, 2006 |url=http://www.asiamedia.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=58909 |accessdate=December 16, 2006 }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |first=Bernd |last=Debusmann |authorlink=<!-- Bernd Debusmann --> |coauthors=\n |title=Fear and distrust of Muslims run deep in US\n |url=http://www.dawn.com/2006/12/02/int14.htm\n |publisher=[[Dawn Group of Newspapers]] |work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]\n |date=December 2, 2006 |accessdate=2009-03-12\n |page= |author= |location=[[Pakistan]] |id= |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate=\n |quote=When radio host Jerry Klein suggested that all Muslims in the United States should be identified with a crescent-shape tattoo or a distinctive arm band, the phone lines jammed instantly.\n}}\n</ref> The hoax was revealed at the end of the program.\n\n==References to WMAL in movies and fiction==\nNear the beginning of the 1951 movie ''[[The Day the Earth Stood Still]]'', radio personality [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]] is seen making an announcement into a microphone labeled \"WMAL\".\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|sportscapitoldc.com}}\n{{AM station data|WSBN}}\n*[http://www.reelradio.com/gifts/wmaljings.html Unofficial WMAL history, with recordings of past WMAL station-ID jingles]\n\n{{Washington Radio}}\n{{Cumulus Media}}\n\n[[Category:Sports radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Washington, D.C.|SBN]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Cumulus Media radio stations]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins broadcasters]]\n[[Category:ESPN Radio stations]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|ESPN Radio affiliate in Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n | name             = WSBN\n | image            = WSBN-Sports-Capitol-logo-2019.png\n | city             = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n | area             = [[Washington metropolitan area]]\n | branding         = ''ESPN 630 D.C.''\n | slogan           = The Sports Capitol\n | frequency        = 630 [[kilohertz|kHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n | airdate          = October 12, [[1925 in radio|1925]]\n | translator       = \n | format           = [[Sports radio|Sports]]\n | power            = 10,000 [[watt]]s (day)<br>2,700 watts (night)\n | class            = B\n | facility_id      = 73250\n | coordinates      = {{coord|39|08|2|N|77|18|14|W|type:landmark_region:US-DC_source:FCC|display=inline,title}}\n | callsign_meaning =\n | former_callsigns = WMAL (1925\u20132019)\n | affiliations     = [[ESPN Radio]]<br>[[Washington Redskins]] Radio Network\n | owner            = [[Cumulus Media]]\n | licensee         = Radio License Holdings LLC\n | sister_stations  = [[WMAL-FM]]\n | webcast          = {{listen live|http://www.sportscapitoldc.com}}\n | website          = [http://www.sportscapitoldc.com sportscapitoldc.com]\n}}\n'''WSBN''' (630 [[Hertz|kHz]]) is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[AM broadcasting|AM]] [[sports radio|sports]] [[radio station]] [[City of license|licensed]] to [[Washington, D.C.]] and serving the [[Washington Metropolitan Area|Washington metro area]]. It operates with 10,000 [[watt]]s in the daytime and 2,700 watts at night using a [[directional antenna]] around the clock. WSBN's studios are on Jenifer Street in Northwest Washington.<ref>[http://www.wmal.com/station-information/ WMAL.com/station-information]</ref>  The [[transmitter]] located off Black Rock Road in [[Germantown, Maryland]].<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/info/WMAL-AM Radio-Locator.com/WMAL-AM]</ref>\n\nWSBN is owned and operated by [[Cumulus Media]] and is [[network affiliate|affiliated]] with [[ESPN Radio]]. It is one of the oldest radio stations in the Washington [[media market]], continuously on the air from 1925. For most of its history, the station operated as '''WMAL'''; on July 1, 2019, its [[Talk radio|talk]] programming was moved exclusively to co-owned [[WMAL-FM]] at 105.9 [[Hertz|MHz]], which had simulcast with 630 AM since 2011.\n\n==Programming==\n{{as of|2019|7}}, WSBN's programming consists of the national ESPN Radio schedule, though the station intends to produce some local programming.<ref name=\"wp-wmalamsports\">{{cite news |last1=Allen |first1=Scott |title=D.C. is getting a third sports talk radio station with the launch of ESPN 630 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/14/dc-is-getting-third-sports-talk-radio-station-with-launch-espn/ |accessdate=July 2, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 14, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early years===\nWMAL first went on the air on October 12, 1925, using [[Call sign|call letters]] incorporating the initials of Martin A. Leese, a local [[optician]] who began selling radio sets at 720 11th Street NW in Washington, D.C.<ref>\"A Radio for Every Purse\". (August 15, 1926). ''The Washington Post'', p. F7</ref> He started WMAL as a low-power station. The shutdown of station [[WCAP (defunct)|WCAP]] left Washington with  WRC (now [[WTEM]]) as its only high-power station, so local business leaders affiliated with the City Club of Washington banded together to create a second high-powered station. Their original plan was to buy WCAP and convert it to a municipal station, but instead they worked with Leese to boost WMAL's signal and make it the city's second large station.<ref>\"City Club to Help Develop New Radio Station in Capital\". (September 26, 1926). ''The Washington Post'', p. M13</ref> The new high-power WMAL went on the air from studios at 710-712 11th Street NW on October 2, 1926, with former WCAP announcer William T. Pierson as director and with a policy of encouraging young broadcasting talent in hopes of creating \"a people's forum\".<ref>\"New Radio Station in First Program\".  (October 3, 1926).  ''The Washington Post'', p. M14</ref>\n\nIn 1927, Leese left his optical business to focus full-time on running the station, and the following year the [[Federal Radio Commission]]'s national frequency allocation plan assigned WMAL the AM 630 frequency, which it still uses today. WMAL was a [[CBS Radio]] [[Network affiliate]] from 1928 until October 19, 1932, and then was briefly unaffiliated until joining the [[NBC Blue Network]] in January 1933. The Blue Network later became [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], with which WMAL was affiliated for many years, and which owned WMAL for several decades.\n\nBy mid-1932, M. R. Baker had been appointed manager of the station, and Kenneth H. Berkeley was appointed station director of WMAL in 1933. While still owned by the Leese family, WMAL was eventually leased to the [[NBC|National Broadcasting Company]] in 1934, joining it with [[owned-and-operated station]] WRC.\n\nNBC's Washington vice president Frank M. Russell supervised the operation of both WMAL and WRC by 1935 when studios were moved from the National Press Building to the Trans-Lux Theatre Building, 724 14th Street NW. Transmitting facilities continued to be located at 712 Eleventh Street NW.\n\nIn the late months of 1937, the lease to NBC was terminated, with station operation reverting to the Leese Family interests. NBC, however, continued to operate it under a managerial agreement executed in fall 1937. Norman Leese was president of WMAL's licensee at that time. On May 1, 1938, the M.A. Leese Radio Corporation was acquired by publishers of the now-defunct ''[[Washington Star|Washington Evening Star]]'' [[newspaper]], a family-owned concern headed by board chairman and president Samuel H. Kauffman. Norman Leese remained president and K. H. Berkeley continued as general manager of WMAL.\n\nThe operating arrangement between NBC and the M.A. Leese Radio Corporation ended in February 1942. The station then reverted to the direct control of the Evening Star Broadcasting Company, of which K. H. Berkeley was executive vice president. Berkeley was also WMAL's general manager. In October 1947, WMAL-TV signed on as the first high-band [[VHF]] [[television]] station in the United States. It became an ABC Network affiliate a year later.\n\nBy 1946, S. H. Kauffman, president and part owner of the ''Evening Star'', was given additional duties as president of its broadcasting subsidiary, the Evening Star Broadcasting Company, until his resignation in August 1954. His replacement as general manager was Frederick S. Houwink.\n\nAlso in 1954, John W. Thompson, Jr. replaced S. H. Kauffman as president of Evening Star Broadcasting Co.\n\nAndrew Martin Ockershausen was appointed station manager of WMAL in 1960. One of Ockershausen's first moves was to team [[Frank Harden]] with [[Jackson Weaver]] for WMAL's morning drive show after the duo had a successful tryout hosting an evening comedy show patterned after [[Bob and Ray]]; ''Harden and Weaver'' took off in popularity and quickly became the top-rated morning show in the Washington market, featuring a blend of news, interviews, light music and comedy.<ref>Harden and Weaver, 1983. p. 88 & 112</ref><ref name=\"washington\">''Frank Harden Signs Off At WMAL; After 50 Years, Radio Voice Leaves With Little Fanfare'' by Marc Fisher ''The Washington Post'' January 7, 1998  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160325225807/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-647106.html Highbeam.com]</ref><ref name=\"sillier\">'' '60s Radio Days: A Sillier, Simpler Time''. Marc Fisher, ''The Washington Post'', September 13, 1999; Page A1.</ref>\n\nIn 1962, Fred Houwink became a company vice president while continuing as WMAL's general manager. In 1965 Houwink was named vice president of Evening Star Broadcasting and Ockershausen was elevated to general manager of WMAL.\n\nIn 1970 Houwink retired and Ockershausen was named vice president, operations. Also in 1970 Richard S. Stakes was named general manager and Harold L. Green was named station manager. In 1974 Charles A. Macatee became WMAL's general manager.\n\n===ABC years===\nIn early January 1976, the Evening Star Broadcasting Company's WMAL, [[WLVW|WMAL-FM]] and [[WJLA|WMAL-TV]] and majority control of the ailing newspaper were acquired from the Kauffman, Noyes and Adams families by publisher [[Joe Allbritton|Joseph L. Albritton]]\u2019s Perpetual Corporation and Albritton became board chairman and chief owner of WMAL's license. On January 21, 1976, WMAL's licensee name was changed to ''Washington Star Communications of Delaware, Inc.'' Richard S. Stakes became station president, but resigned in December 1976. Mr. Albritton then assumed the presidency, with Robert Nelson becoming president of the broadcasting division. General Manager Charles Macatee resigned in January 1977.\n\nA requirement of the purchase of the Evening Star properties included the sale of the radio or television properties. In March 1977, WMAL and WMAL-FM were spun off to ABC Radio, while the TV station was retained and became [[WJLA|WJLA-TV]], named after Albritton's initials. ABC paid $16 million for WMAL and WMAL-FM, a record price for radio properties at that time. Andrew Ockershausen was appointed executive vice president.\n\n[[File:WMAL 630 old.png|left|thumb|200px|WMAL logo used until 2009.]]On January 3, 1986, [[Capital Cities Communications|Capital Cities]] and [[ABC, Inc.]] merged in a $3.52 billion deal. Thomas S. Murphy was chairman and CEO of the new firm. Frederick Weinhaus became president and general manager following the resignation of Andrew Ockershausen in March 1986. Weinhaus was transferred to [[Citadel Media|ABC Radio]] New York in January 1988. His replacement in May 1988 was Thomas Bresnahan, who continued in that role until his retirement in 2002.\n\nWMAL morning co-host Jackson Weaver died on October 20, 1992, with ''Harden and Weaver'' still at or near the top of the local ratings; Weaver also garnered fame nationally as the first voice of [[Smokey Bear]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jackson Weaver, 72, Voice of Smokey Bear |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/22/obituaries/jackson-weaver-72-voice-of-smokey-bear.html?pagewanted=1 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 22, 1992 |language=en}}</ref> Frank Harden continued the morning show with co-hosts [[Tim Brant]] and Andy Parks until his retirement in 1998.<ref name=\"washington\" /> Brant and Parks continued until Brant's departure in May 2002,<ref>https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2003/dec/15/20031215-093650-7060r/</ref> his replacement would be former congressman [[Fred Grandy]].\n\nBy the late 1990s, WMAL transitioned its talk lineup into one similar to sister station [[WABC (AM)|WABC]] in New York City, with an emphasis on conservative talk.\n\n[[File:WMAL (AM) former logo (2009-2011).png|thumb|200px|WMAL logo, 2009-2011]] [[Chris Berry (broadcaster)|Chris Berry]] was named president and general manager November 19, 2002. Prior to joining WMAL, Berry was vice president, radio for [[ABC News]], based in New York. In August 2005, host [[Michael Graham (radio personality)|Michael Graham]] was fired after refusing to apologize for calling the Council on American-Islamic Relations (CAIR) a \"terrorist organization.\"\n\n===Citadel and Cumulus years===\nABC sold its non-[[Radio Disney]] and [[ESPN Radio]] stations, including WMAL, to [[Citadel Broadcasting]] in 2007; Citadel merged with Cumulus Media on September 16, 2011.<ref name=abj-citadelcumulus>{{cite news|title=Cumulus now owns Citadel Broadcasting|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2011/09/16/cumulus-now-owns-citadel-broadcasting.html|accessdate=September 16, 2011|newspaper=Atlanta Business Journal|date=September 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLongtime Washington broadcaster [[Chris Core]] was dismissed from WMAL in 2008 as part of a broad cost-cutting move; his replacement, [[Austin Hill (radio personality)|Austin Hill]], was dropped in February 2009 due to Levin's show expanding and Sliwa's show moving up an hour. Plante, a popular talk host who hosted evenings and later middays, was yanked in favor of Joe Scarborough's ''[[Morning Joe]]'' in April 2009, only to return to middays six months later after Scarborough's show was cancelled.\n\nBy late 2009, WMAL's morning-drive through midnight weekday format was uninterrupted conservative talk, with a lineup of [[Fred Grandy]] and Andy Parks, [[Chris Plante]], [[Rush Limbaugh]], [[Sean Hannity]], [[Mark Levin]], [[Joe Scarborough]], and [[Curtis Sliwa]]. Weekends include gardening host Jos Roozen, investing adviser [[Ric Edelman]] and lawyer Michael Collins. [[John Batchelor]] replaced Sliwa in November 2009. In April 2010, Parks was laid off from the station, resulting in Plante's and Grandy's shows being merged. At the same time, Scarborough's show was put on extended hiatus. Austin Hill began filling in the middays for the time being, while [[Mark Simone]] handled Scarborough's shift. Grandy left WMAL in March 2011.\n\n[[File:WMAL-AMandFM 2014.png|200px|thumb|left|Logo during simulcast with 105.9 FM, 2011\u20132019]]\nOn September 19, 2011, WMAL began simulcasting its AM signal on 105.9 FM, now [[WMAL-FM]]. The former WMAL-FM, renamed WRQX in 1977, has since become [[WLVW]]; it remained co-owned with WMAL until 2019.\n\nIn 2017, WMAL started broadcasting [[Washington Redskins]] games as an affiliate station for the first time since the team's [[Super Bowl XXVI]] win in 1992. WMAL previously carried the team's games from 1942 to 1956, and again from 1963 to 1991. [[WTEM]] (570 AM), a new sports station at the time, acquired the radio broadcast rights from WMAL for the [[1992 NFL season]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Scott |title=Redskins games will be back on WMAL for first time since last Super Bowl win |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2017/02/16/redskins-games-will-be-back-on-wmal-for-first-time-since-last-super-bowl-win/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 3, 2017, WMAL's weekday lineup consisted of local talent [[Brian Wilson (news correspondent)|Brian Wilson]] and Mary Walter in the morning, then Chris Plante, followed by the syndicated Rush Limbaugh, then [[Larry O'Connor (radio host)|Larry O'Connor]] hosts a local afternoon drive show, followed by the syndicated shows of [[Mark Levin]], [[John Batchelor]], and overnight the syndicated show [[Red Eye Radio]], hosted by [[Eric Harley]] and [[Gary McNamara]].  Brian Wilson was released in May 2017.\n\n===Flip to sports talk===\nOn June 13, 2019, it was announced that WMAL would break away from the simulcast with WMAL-FM and flip to [[ESPN Radio]] on July 1, 2019 as ''ESPN 630''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/local-networks/espn-cumulus-dc-sports-radio-redskins.html|title=ESPN and Cumulus will launch a new D.C. ESPN Radio station|date=2019-06-14|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/187183/wmal-a-f-washington-d-c-to-split-simulcast-am-to-f|title=WMAL-A-F/Washington, D.C. To Split Simulcast, AM To Flip To Sports As ESPN 630, The Sports Capitol|website=All Access|language=en|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref> WMAL replaced WTEM as ESPN Radio's Washington, D.C. affiliate, though both stations continue to share Redskins games, with WTEM as flagship.<ref name=\"wp-wmalamsports\"/> Concurrent with the format change, WMAL changed its call letters to WSBN;<ref name=\"fcc-callsigns\">{{cite web |url=https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=73250&Callsign=WSBN |title=Call Sign History (WSBN) |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref> prior to the change, it had been Washington's oldest station to be operating under its original call letters.\n\n==Studios==\n[[File:Wmal 20090125 133755.jpg|thumb|right|The former WMAL radio tower site in [[Bethesda, MD]]]]\nWMAL broadcast from various facilities in Washington, D.C., and suburban [[Maryland]] until July 25, 1973, when it settled in at its current studio facility at 4400 Jenifer Street NW in Washington, two blocks from the city's border with [[Maryland]].\n\nWMAL's former transmitting facility, located in the Bradley Hills section of suburban [[Bethesda, Maryland]], once housed studios for WMAL-AM and WMAL-FM. Cumulus put the 75-acre site for sale in February 2015; in the summer of 2016, it was sold to the Toll Brothers company, who has plans to turn the site into a housing development.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radioworld.com/business-and-law/0009/wmal-tower-site-up-for-sale/333530 |title=WMAL Tower Site Up For Sale |work=Radio World |last=Stimson |first=Leslie |date=February 9, 2015 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radioworld.com/business-and-law/0009/wmal-tower-site-demolition-begins/336515 |title=WMAL Tower Site Demolition Begins |work=Radio World |last=Reigart |first=Emily M. |date=September 20, 2016 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/Web-2016/Developer-of-WMAL-Radio-Towers-Site-Unveils-Latest-Plans-to-Skeptical-Public/ |title=Updated: Developer of WMAL Radio Towers Site Unveils Latest Plans to Skeptical Public |work=[[Bethesda Magazine]] |last=Kraut |first=Aaron |date=April 11, 2016 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bethesdamagazine.com/Bethesda-Beat/2017/Planning-Board-Approves-Proposal-for-309-Homes-at-WMAL-Tower-Site/ |title=Planning Board Approves Proposal for 309 Homes at WMAL Tower Site |work=[[Bethesda Magazine]] |last=Rodgers |first=Bethany |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radiomagonline.com/industry/0003/county-planning-board-approves-plan-for-wmal-site/38985 |title=County Planning Board Approves Plan for WMAL Site |work=[[Radio (magazine)|Radio Magazine]] |last=Reigart |first=Emily M. |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 12, 2016, WMAL was granted a [[Federal Communications Commission]] [[construction permit]] to move from their 91-year-old site in Bethesda to the [[WWRC]] transmitter site in [[Germantown, Maryland|Germantown]] and decrease night power to 2,700 watts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101726202&formid=301&fac_num=73250 |title=Application for Construction Permit for Commercial Broadcast Station |work=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |date=May 12, 2016 |accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref> Transmissions from the Bethesda transmitter site ceased on the afternoon of May 1, 2018.\n\n===Personalities===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2010}}\nAmong the WMAL broadcasters over the years have been [[Frank Harden]] and [[Jackson Weaver]], who co-hosted WMAL's morning show for more than four decades until Weaver's death in the early 1990s; Tom Gauger, who also spent several decades at WMAL; [[Arthur Godfrey]], a national radio and early-TV personality who briefly broadcast on WMAL in 1933 as \"Red\" Godfrey; Bill Mayhugh, a mellow-voiced overnight broadcaster; and [[Ken Beatrice]], a sports talk radio pioneer who hosted a call-in show from 1977 to 1995.\n\nThe station also kept a local following for a time by broadcasting [[sports]] games featuring the [[Washington Redskins]] and [[University of Maryland, College Park]] Terrapins. Legendary jazz authority [[Felix Grant]] broadcast on WMAL for decades.\n\nSupport of the local community has been a tradition for WMAL, which founded such innovative fund-raisers as the Leukemia Radiothon and the Gross National Parade, which supported the D.C. Police Boys & Girls Club.\n\n===News===\nIn addition to providing talk programming, WMAL provided local news coverage. With morning anchor Bill Thompson,<ref>[http://wmal.com/Article.asp?id=450426&spid=18558 Bill Thompson]</ref> afternoon anchor Mark Weaver<ref>[http://wmal.com/Article.asp?id=192504&spid=18558 Mark Weaver - WMAL biography]</ref> and the team covers news stories affecting the Washington DC area.\n\n===Jerry Klein's 2006 radio experiment===\n{{main|Jerry Klein's 2006 radio experiment}}\nThe station aired a [[Talk radio|radio talk show]] on November 26, 2006 to gauge his audience's reaction to saying that \"force should be applied to ensure that all Muslims in America wear identifying markers....\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In U.S., fear and distrust of Muslims runs deep | author=Bernd Debusmann | publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=December 1, 2006 |url=http://www.asiamedia.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=58909 |accessdate=December 16, 2006 }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |first=Bernd |last=Debusmann |authorlink=<!-- Bernd Debusmann --> |coauthors=\n |title=Fear and distrust of Muslims run deep in US\n |url=http://www.dawn.com/2006/12/02/int14.htm\n |publisher=[[Dawn Group of Newspapers]] |work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]\n |date=December 2, 2006 |accessdate=2009-03-12\n |page= |author= |location=[[Pakistan]] |id= |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate=\n |quote=When radio host Jerry Klein suggested that all Muslims in the United States should be identified with a crescent-shape tattoo or a distinctive arm band, the phone lines jammed instantly.\n}}\n</ref> The hoax was revealed at the end of the program.\n\n==References to WMAL in movies and fiction==\nNear the beginning of the 1951 movie ''[[The Day the Earth Stood Still]]'', radio personality [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]] is seen making an announcement into a microphone labeled \"WMAL\".\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|sportscapitoldc.com}}\n{{AM station data|WSBN}}\n*[http://www.reelradio.com/gifts/wmaljings.html Unofficial WMAL history, with recordings of past WMAL station-ID jingles]\n\n{{Washington Radio}}\n{{Cumulus Media}}\n\n[[Category:Sports radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Washington, D.C.|SBN]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Cumulus Media radio stations]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins broadcasters]]\n[[Category:ESPN Radio stations]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Mrschimpf", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WSBN"}
{"title_page": "Mukesh Bhakar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| governor         = [[Kalraj Mishra]]\n| term_end1        = \n| 1blankname1      = [[Chief Minister of Rajasthan|Chief Minister]]\n| 1namedata1       = [[Ashok Gehlot]]\n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2 = President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2 = 7 April 2020\n| 1blankname2 = National President\n| 1namedata2 = [[Srinivas BV]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Ashok Chandna]]\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| profession       = [[Politician]]\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]. He represents As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rajpcc.com/mukeshbhakar|title=Indian National Congress Party|website=www.rajpcc.com}}</ref> in [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Ladnu|Ladnun]] of [[Nagaur district]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rajassembly.nic.in/MemberBioData.aspx|title=Rajasthan Legislative Assembly Member Information|website=rajassembly.nic.in}}</ref>. Bhakar was previously State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan, the student wing of [[Indian National Congress]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\n== Political life ==\nHe elected State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/RAJ-JAI-mukesh-bhakar-became-the-state-chief-of-nsui-4164425-NOR.html|title=NSUI \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0947\u0936\u093e\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0915\u094d\u0937 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u093e\u0915\u0930|date=31 January 2013|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>  During his tenure NSUI made come back in [[University of Rajasthan]] after 12 years in the Largest University of Rajasthan.<ref>https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/jaipur/news/RAJ-JAI-10-candidates-for-presidents-post-rajasthan-4719233-NOR.html.</ref> After completion of his term National president nominated him National Secretary. Congress Party gave him an opportunity to contest Rajasthan State assembly elections 2018, where he successfully managed a win by margin of 12947 votes against 3 times MLA [[Thakur Manohar Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/election-result-2018/rajasthan-election-result-2018/nagaur/ladnun/mukesh-bhakar/|title=Ladnun Congress Candidate Mukesh Bhakar, Mukesh Bhakar vs Manohar Singh, \u0932\u093e\u0921\u0928\u0942\u0902 \u0938\u0940\u091f \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u0915\u0930|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Nagaur district]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician (born 1988)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n{{Autobiography|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| governor         = [[Kalraj Mishra]]\n| term_end1        = \n| 1blankname1      = [[Chief Minister of Rajasthan|Chief Minister]]\n| 1namedata1       = [[Ashok Gehlot]]\n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2 = President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2 = 7 April 2020\n| 1blankname2 = National President\n| 1namedata2 = [[Srinivas BV]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Ashok Chandna]]\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| profession       = [[Politician]]\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]. He represents As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rajpcc.com/mukeshbhakar|title=Indian National Congress Party|website=www.rajpcc.com}}</ref> in [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Ladnu|Ladnun]] of [[Nagaur district]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rajassembly.nic.in/MemberBioData.aspx|title=Rajasthan Legislative Assembly Member Information|website=rajassembly.nic.in}}</ref>. Bhakar was previously State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan, the student wing of [[Indian National Congress]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\n== Political life ==\nHe elected State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/RAJ-JAI-mukesh-bhakar-became-the-state-chief-of-nsui-4164425-NOR.html|title=NSUI \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0947\u0936\u093e\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0915\u094d\u0937 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u093e\u0915\u0930|date=31 January 2013|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>  During his tenure NSUI made come back in [[University of Rajasthan]] after 12 years in the Largest University of Rajasthan.<ref>https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/jaipur/news/RAJ-JAI-10-candidates-for-presidents-post-rajasthan-4719233-NOR.html.</ref> After completion of his term National president nominated him National Secretary. Congress Party gave him an opportunity to contest Rajasthan State assembly elections 2018, where he successfully managed a win by margin of 12947 votes against 3 times MLA [[Thakur Manohar Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/election-result-2018/rajasthan-election-result-2018/nagaur/ladnun/mukesh-bhakar/|title=Ladnun Congress Candidate Mukesh Bhakar, Mukesh Bhakar vs Manohar Singh, \u0932\u093e\u0921\u0928\u0942\u0902 \u0938\u0940\u091f \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u0915\u0930|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n