42<ref name=\"4.01\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-september-26-2019/|title='Young Sheldon' adjusts up, 'A Million Little Things' and 'Evil' adjust down: Thursday final ratings|last=Rejent|first=Joseph|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| end4              = January 30, 2020\n| endrating4        = 2.32<ref name=\"4.13&4.14\">{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-jan-30-2020/|title=\u2018The Good Place\u2019 special adjusts down: Thursday final ratings|last=Welch|first=Alex|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 31, 2020|accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| season4           = 2019\u201320\n| rank4             = \n| viewers4          =\n\n}}\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:Ted Danson 2008 number 2.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ted Danson]]'s performance on the series has received critical acclaim.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#FCC938;\"|\n| 1\n| 92% (71 reviews)\n| 78 (32 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#A8BF4F;\"|\n| 2\n| 100% (58 reviews)\n| 87 (10 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#0A9CFD;\"|\n| 3\n| 98% (47 reviews)\n| 96 (5 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#5e545b;\"|\n| 4\n| 100% (21 reviews)\n| {{n/a}}\n|}\n\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season has a rating of 92%, based on 71 reviews, with an average rating of 7.74/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Kristen Bell and Ted Danson knock it out of the park with supremely entertaining, charming performances in this absurd, clever and whimsical portrayal of the afterlife.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/good_place/s01/|title=The Good Place: Season 1|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the first season has a score of 78 out of 100, based on reviews from 32 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-good-place/season-1|title=The Good Place - Season 1 Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe editors of ''[[TV Guide]]'' placed ''The Good Place'' second among the top ten picks for the most anticipated new shows of the 2016\u201317 season. In its review from writer Liam Matthews, \"NBC's new comedy has an impressive pedigree\" (referring to Mike Schur and stars, Kristen Bell and Ted Danson, the latter cited as \"arguably the greatest sitcom actor of all time\"). Matthews concludes, \"The hope is that their combined star power can restore NBC's tarnished comedy brand to its former glory. It won't be the next ''[[Friends]]'', but it's something even better: a network comedy that feels different than anything that's come before.\"<ref name=\"most exciting\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/most-anticipated-new-tv-shows-fall-2016-editors-picks/ |title=Our 10 Most Anticipated New TV Shows of Fall 2016 |work=[[TV Guide]] |first=Alexander |last=Zalben |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the second season has a rating of 100%, based on 58 reviews, with an average rating of 8.95/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"By voluntarily blowing up its premise, ''The Good Place'' sets up a second season that proves even funnier than its first.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/good_place/s02/|title=The Good Place: Season 2|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, the second season has a score of 87 out of 100, based on reviews from 10 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-good-place/season-2|title=The Good Place - Season 2 Reviews|work=Metacritic|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the third season has a rating of 98%, based on 47 reviews, with an average rating of 8.35/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Charming and curious as ever, ''The Good Place'' remains a delightfully insightful bright spot on the television landscape.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/good_place/s03/|title=The Good Place: Season 3|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, the third season has a score of 96 out of 100, based on reviews from five critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-good-place/season-3|title=The Good Place - Season 3 Reviews|work=Metacritic|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the fourth season has a rating of 100%, based on 21 reviews, with an average rating of 8.33/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"A wild philosophical ride to the very end, ''The Good Place'' brings it home with a forking good final season.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/good_place/s04/|title=The Good Place: Season 4|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral critics have commended the show for its exploration and creative use of [[ethics]] and [[philosophy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2017/12/09/how-to-be-good-tv-the-good-place/ |title=How-to-be-good TV: \"The Good Place\" |last=McFarland |first=Melanie |date=December 9, 2017 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"theconversation\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-complicated-morality-of-the-good-place-1788591741 |title=The Complicated Morality of The Good Place |last=Trendacosta |first=Katharine |date=November 5, 2016 |work=[[io9]]|access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> Featured topics include the [[trolley problem]] thought experiment (originally devised by [[Philippa Foot]]),<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> the [[categorical imperative]] (first formulated by [[Immanuel Kant]]),<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> [[T. M. Scanlon]]'s ''What We Owe to Each Other'',<ref name=\":6\" /> and the works of [[Aristotle]] and [[S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> Andrew P. Street of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that \"moral philosophy is the beating heart of the program\" and that the show \"made philosophy seem cool.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/jan/30/the-good-place-how-a-sitcom-made-philosophy-seem-cool |title=The Good Place: How a sitcom made philosophy seem cool |last=Street |first=Andrew P. |date=January 29, 2018 |website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> Elizabeth Yuko of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' noted that \"''The Good Place'' stands out for dramatizing actual ethics classes onscreen, without watering down the concepts being described, and while still managing to be entertaining.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/10/how-the-good-place-goes-beyond-the-trolley-problem/543393/ |title=How 'The Good Place' Goes Beyond 'The Trolley Problem' |last=Yuko |first=Elizabeth |date=October 21, 2017 |work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> For their part, several philosophers have celebrated the show's largely accurate popularization of their line of work<ref name=\"theconversation\"/> while noting some minor inaccuracies.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theringer.com/tv/2017/11/2/16596298/talking-to-philosopher-about-the-good-place-nbc |title=Talking to a Philosopher About 'The Good Place' |last=Herman |first=Alison |date=November 2, 2017 |work=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]|access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral critics have noted that ''The Good Place'' is notable for its eschewing of [[antihero]]es and cynical themes in favor of likable characters and a positive message. [[James Poniewozik]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' explained that \"the most refreshing thing about ''The Good Place'', in an era of artistic bleakness, is its optimism about human nature. It's made humane and sidesplittingly entertaining television out of the notion that people \u2013 and even the occasional immortal demon \u2013 are redeemable.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/31/arts/the-good-place-kristen-bell-ted-danson.html|title=How 'The Good Place' Became an Antihero Antidote|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=January 31, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref> Jenna Scherer of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that ''The Good Place'' proves that \"slapstick and banter can coexist alongside tragedy and hardship \u2013 that a show doesn't need to be self-serious to be serious-minded.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/how-the-good-place-turned-into-the-smartest-funniest-sitcom-on-tv-121942/|title=How 'The Good Place' Turned Into the Smartest, Funniest Sitcom on TV|last=Scherer|first=Jenna|date=February 2, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728223424/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/how-the-good-place-turned-into-the-smartest-funniest-sitcom-on-tv-121942/|archive-date=July 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Erik Adams of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' praised the show as portraying an \"uncommonly decent TV world\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/the-good-places-the-uncommonly-decent-tv-worlds-of-mic-1818561418|title=The good places: The uncommonly decent TV worlds of Michael Schur|last=Adams|first=Erik|date=September 21, 2017|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728222404/https://www.avclub.com/the-good-places-the-uncommonly-decent-tv-worlds-of-mic-1818561418|archive-date=July 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Stuart Heritage of ''The Guardian'' called ''The Good Place'' \"relentlessly optimistic\",<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/08/the-50-best-tv-shows-of-2017-no-8-the-good-place|title=The 50 best TV shows of 2017: No 8 The Good Place|last=Heritage|first=Stuart|date=December 8, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref> a quality which Stephanie Palumbo of ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' called \"a salve for despair in the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump era]]\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/01/the-good-places-optimism-is-a-salve-for-despair-in-the-trump-era.html|title='The Good Place's Optimism Is a Salve for Despair in the Trump Era|last=Palumbo|first=Stephanie|date=January 25, 2017|work=Vulture|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728223247/http://www.vulture.com/2017/01/the-good-places-optimism-is-a-salve-for-despair-in-the-trump-era.html|archive-date=July 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''The Good Place'' was ranked 69th on ''The Guardian''{{'}}s list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |date=September 13, 2019 |accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Critics' top-ten lists====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Publication !! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" | Rank\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-the-top-10-best-tv-shows-of-2016 |title=Best of 2016: Television Critic Top Ten Lists |website=[[Metacritic]] |first=Jason |last=Dietz |date=December 6, 2016 |accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> !! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-the-top-10-best-tv-shows-of-2017 |title=Best of 2017: Television Critic Top Ten Lists |website=Metacritic |first=Jason |last=Dietz |date=December 4, 2017 |accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> !! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-the-top-10-best-tv-shows-of-2018 |title=Best of 2018: Television Critic Top Ten Lists |website=Metacritic |first=Jason |last=Dietz |date=December 4, 2018 |accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | ''[[Adweek]]'' || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || 7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | [[American Film Institute]] || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || data-sort-value=\"11\" | {{small|Shortlisted}} || date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | ''[[Ars Technica]]'' || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || data-sort-value=\"11\" | {{small|Shortlisted}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | [[BuddyTV]] || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || 7 || date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || 6 || 4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || 6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | [[Decider (website)|Decider]] || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || 2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right\" | [[E!]] || data-sort-type=\"number\" date-sort-value=\"12\" {{n/a}} || 8 || data-sort-value=\"11\" |