-nominations-2019-globes-awards-nominees/ |title=Golden Globe Nominations: Versace, Mrs. Maisel, Sharp Objects, Barry and The Americans Lead TV Pack |website=TVLine |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Hugo Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation|Best Dramatic Presentation, Short Form]]\n|\"Janet(s)\", written by Josh Siegal & Dylan Morgan, directed by Morgan Sackett\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2019/08/2019-hugo-awards-announced/|title=2019 Hugo Awards Announced|website=The Hugo Awards|date=August 19, 2019|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Jeremy Bearimy\", written by Megan Amram, directed by Trent O'Donnell\n|{{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2019/04/2019-hugo-award-1944-retro-hugo-award-finalists/|title=2019 Hugo Award & 1944 Retro Hugo Award Finalists|website=The Hugo Awards|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[List of Peabody Award winners (2010\u20132019)|Peabody Awards]]\n|Entertainment honoree\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Place, The\" | ''The Good Place''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/peabody-awards-barry-killing-eve-hannah-gadsby-pose-entertainment-winners-list-1202598447/|title=Peabody Awards: 'Barry', 'Killing Eve', Hannah Gadsby, 'Pose' Among Entertainment Winners|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=April 18, 2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Place, The\" | ''The Good Place''\n| {{nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/09/22/emmys-2019-awards-winners-list/ |title=Emmys 2019: Game of Thrones Ties Record and Leads TV Pack; Fleabag, Chernobyl and Mrs. Maisel Win Big |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |website=TVLine |date=September 22, 2019 |accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series\n| data-sort-value=\"Rudolph, Maya\" | Maya Rudolph\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series\n| data-sort-value=\"Danson, Ted\" | Ted Danson\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Siegal, Josh & Dylan Morgan | Josh Siegal & Dylan Morgan (for \"Janet(s)\")\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[23rd Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n|[[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actor in a Musical or Comedy Series]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Danson, Ted\" |Ted Danson\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Satellite Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Musical or Comedy Series]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Place, The\" |''The Good Place''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardscircuit.com/2018/11/29/international-press-academy-announces-nominees-for-23rd-annual-satellite-awards/|title=International Press Academy Announces Nominees for 23rd Annual Satellite Awards|last1=Peterson|first1=Karen M.|date=November 29, 2018|website=Awards Circuit|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardscircuit.com/2019/01/04/a-star-is-born-roma-and-beale-street-win-big-at-the-satellite-awards/|title='A Star Is Born,' 'Roma,' and 'Beale Street' Win Big at the Satellite Awards|last1=St. Clair|first1=Matt|date=January 4, 2019|website=Awards Circuit|accessdate=January 5, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[45th Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Television Series|Best Fantasy Television Series]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Place, The\" | ''The Good Place''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mancuso |first1=Vinnie |title='Avengers: Endgame', 'Game of Thrones' Lead the 2019 Saturn Awards Nominations |url=https://collider.com/saturn-awards-nominations-2019/ |website=Collider |accessdate=July 17, 2019 |date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[35th TCA Awards|TCA Awards]]\n| Outstanding Achievement in Comedy\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Place, The\" | ''The Good Place''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/pose-russian-doll-hbo-lead-2019-tv-critic-awards-nominations-1219571 |title='Pose,' 'Russian Doll,' HBO Lead 2019 TV Critic Awards Nominations |website=The Hollywood Reporter |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=June 19, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Writers Guild of America Awards 2018|Writers Guild of America Awards]]\n|[[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Comedy Series|Television: Comedy Series]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Place, The\" |''The Good Place''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/writers-guild-awards-tv-nominations-2019-list-1202515496/|title=WGA Awards TV Nominations: 'The Handmaid's Tale', 'Barry', 'SNL' Make List|last1=Hipes|first1=Patrick|date=December 6, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2020\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[24th Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n|Best Actor in a Musical or Comedy Series\n| data-sort-value=\"Danson, Ted\" |Ted Danson\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|Best Musical or Comedy Series\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Place, The\" |''The Good Place''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.awardscircuit.com/2019/12/03/24th-satellite-awards-announce-nominations-ford-v-ferrari-leads-the-way/ |title=24th Satellite Awards Announce Nominations, 'Ford v Ferrari' Leads the Way |website=Awards Circuit |first=Karen M. |last=Peterson |date=December 3, 2019 |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|Art Directors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Art Directors Guild Award for Excellence in Production Design for a Half Hour Single-Camera Television Series|Excellence in Production Design for a Half-Hour Single-Camera Series]]\n| Ian Phillips (for \"Employee of the Bearimy\", \"Help Is Other People\")\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/awards/the-irishman-once-upon-a-time-the-mandalorian-art-directors-guild-nominations-1203429170/|title='The Irishman,' 'Once Upon a Time,' 'The Mandalorian' Among Art Directors Guild Nominations|last=Tangcay|first=Jazz|website=Variety|date=December 9, 2019|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Philosophical inspirations==\n{{original research|section|date=February 2020}}\n''The Good Place'' makes use of many different theories of [[moral philosophy]] and ethics through the character of Chidi Anagonye, the moral philosophy professor. Within the show, there is reference to [[John Locke]], [[Tim Scanlon]], [[Peter Singer]], and [[Derek Parfit]], and \"the show has covered everything from [[Jonathan Dancy]]'s theory of [[moral particularism]], to [[Aristotelian ethics|Aristotelian virtue ethics]], to [[Kantian ethics|Kantian deontology]], to [[moral nihilism]].\"<ref name=\"vox\">{{cite web |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |title=How The Good Place taught moral philosophy to its characters \u2014 and its creators |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2019/9/26/20874217/the-good-place-season-premiere-season-4-moral-philosophy |website=Vox |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref> UCLA philosophy professor, [[Pamela Hieronymi]], served as a consultant to the show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/how-ucla-philosophy-professor-pamela-hieronymi-helped-construct-the-good-place |title=How a UCLA philosophy professor helped construct \u2018The Good Place\u2019 |website=UCLA Newsroom |first=Jessica |last=Wolf |date=October 3, 2018 |accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref> She also made a cameo alongside political philosopher, [[Todd May]], in the final episode.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2020/1/31/21116261/the-good-place-series-finale-recap-whenever-youre-ready-season-4-door|title=The Good Place was groundbreaking TV. Did its finale measure up?|last=VanDerWerff|first=Emily Todd|date=2020-01-31|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nThe beginning of ''The Good Place'' takes its inspiration from the idiom \"Hell is other people\", from [[Jean-Paul Sartre]]'s play ''[[No Exit]]''. In the play, three people are trapped in Hell, represented as one room, and they torture one another psychologically while reflecting upon the sins that got them there.<ref name=\"vox\" /> The concept \"Hell is other people\" is an often-misunderstood philosophical idiom meant to reflect that \"Hell is other people because you are, in some sense, forever trapped within them, subject to their apprehension of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Ambrosino |first=Brandon |title=Hell is other people ... misquoting philosophers |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/11/17/7229547/philosophy-quotes-misunderstood-wittgenstein-sartre-descartes |website=Vox |date=November 17, 2014 |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"den of geek\">{{cite web |last=Mellor |first=Louisa |title=The 1944 Existentialist Play That Inspired The Good Place |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/the-good-place/275396/the-1944-existentialist-play-that-inspired-the-good-place |website=Den of Geek |date=August 4, 2018 |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe play ''No Exit'' acts as a direct inspiration for ''The Good Place's'' first season where it is revealed that the human-loving Good Place architect, Michael, is a demon sent from Hell to run an experiment on the idea that humans are their own best torturers. He selectively chooses a group of four people who he decides are perfectly offset to torture one another and, in the beginning, it appears to work. Chidi tortures Eleanor with his indecisiveness, inflexibility, and scholarly disposition; likewise Eleanor tortures Chidi by constantly putting him in situations where he must make decisions or go against the very moral tenets he espouses. Tahani tortures Eleanor by continuously reinforcing her superiority, Jason tortures Tahani by being unable to return her incessant need for validation (as he is initially the silent Buddhist monk Jianyu), and for Jason the mere fact he is forced to pretend he is someone other than himself is torture in itself. Each character is designed to bring out what they hate most about each other and themselves, resulting in the new form of torture Michael is experimenting with.<ref name=\"den of geek\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Fienberg |first=Daniel |title=Critic's Notebook: Twisty 'Good Place' Finale Sets Up a Second Season That NBC Needs to Order |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/fien-print/good-place-finale-critics-notebook-966705 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 4, 2018 |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe second philosophical inspiration of ''The Good Place'' is the question of whether studying moral philosophy can have a direct effect on how moral one can be. In season two, Chidi becomes a teacher to Eleanor, Jason, Tahani and the demon, Michael. The show does not definitively answer this question, as Eleanor often struggles to decide which moral philosophy is best to abide by in her situations, but the lessons do encourage the process of self-reflection. By encouraging Eleanor to reflect on the moral implications of an act, her challenges encourage moral her to develop her capacity to see her choices as moral ones.  Morality is also created in Michael not through Chidi's lessons, which Michael uses as a means of torture but, rather, through the relationships he develops with the characters.<ref>{{cite video |last=Pickard |first=Claire |title=The Philosophy of The Good Place \u2013 Wisecrack Edition |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=stHk4_VePds |website=YouTube |publisher=[[Wisecrack (company)|Wisecrack]] |date=September 22, 2018 |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe final major philosophical tenet of the show is named in one of the series' episodes, \"What We Owe to Each Other\", which is a philosophy book written by Tim Scanlon. According to the show's head writer Michael Schur, this \"book forms the spine of the entire show\".<ref name=\"vox\" /> The book presents the idea of [[Contractualism]]: the idea is that \"to act morally is to abide by principles that no one could reasonably reject\".<ref name=\"vox\"/> The show and the relationships between the characters act as an investigation into contractualism with the four main humans, Michael, and Janet forming their own society whereby they must act in ways that no one could reasonably reject even when that goes against the rules and tenets of higher powers. The overarching thesis of the show, greatly influenced by the contractualist theory is \"the point of morality... isn't to accumulate goodness points, as in the elaborate point system the organizers of ''The Good Place'' and its corresponding Bad Place employ to determine who goes to which upon death. It's to live up to our duties to each other.\"<ref name=\"vox\" />\n\n==''The Selection''==\nIn September 2019, prior to the release of the fourth season of ''The Good Place'', [[NBC]] released a six-episode [[web series]] on their website, app, and their [[YouTube]] channel, titled ''The Selection'', directed by [[Eric Kissack]]. The series, set during an [[Ellipsis (narrative device)|ellipsis]] taking place during the season 3 episode \"Chidi Sees the Time-Knife\", follows Michael's former demon boss Shawn as he and his underlings decide which four people to pick for Michael's new incarnation of \"the Good Place\". [[Marc Evan Jackson]], Josh Siegal, [[Bambadjan Bamba]], [[Amy Okuda]], and [[Jama Williamson]] form the main cast by reprising their roles from ''The Good Place'' as Shawn and his underlings, with [[Joe Mande]] reprising his role as Toddrick \"Todd\" Hemple in the third episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-good-place-preps-final-season-with-the-selection-digital-series-1202734356/ |title=\u2018The Good Place\u2019 Preps Viewers For Its Final Season With \u2018The Selection\u2019 Digital Series |website=Deadline |first=Bruce |last=Haring |date=September 13, 2019 |accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|display=''The Good Place''|d=Q22908690|c=category:The Good Place|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation, Short Form}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Comedy}}\n{{authority control|WORLDCATID=}} <!-- empty value to suppress WorldCat Identities link that 404s -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Good Place, The}}\n[[Category:The Good Place| ]]\n[[Category:2010s American comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Angels in television]]\n[[Category:Demons in television]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fantasy comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Fiction about memory erasure and alteration]]\n[[Category:Fiction about the afterlife]]\n[[Category:Heaven in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Hell in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning television programs]]\n[[Category:Philosophical fiction]]\n[[Category:Philosophy and culture]]\n[[Category:Philosophy television series]]\n[[Category:Television series about parallel universes]]\