{"title_page": "Natalie Bennett", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Naftali Bennett}}\n{{short description|Former Leader of the Green Party of England and Wales, Member of the House of Lords}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle\n|image       = Official portrait of Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle crop 2.jpg\n|caption     = Natalie Bennett pictured in 2019\n|office5         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5       =  7 October 2019<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n|term_end45       =\n|office2      = [[Leader of the Green Party of England and Wales]]\n|deputy2      = [[Will Duckworth]] (2012\u20132014)<br />[[Amelia Womack]] and [[Shahrar Ali]] (2014\u20132016)\n|term_start2  = 3 September 2012\n|term_end2    = 2 September 2016\n|predecessor2 = [[Caroline Lucas]]\n|successor2   = [[Jonathan Bartley]] and<br /> [[Caroline Lucas]] \n|birth_name  = Natalie Louise Bennett\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1966|2|10|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Eastwood, New South Wales|Eastwood]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|party       = {{Nowrap|[[Green Party of England and Wales]]}}\n|partner     = \n|alma_mater  = {{Nowrap|[[University of Sydney]], Australia <br />[[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]], Australia <br />[[University of Leicester]], UK}}\n}}\n\n'''Natalie Louise Bennett, Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-bennett-of-manor-castle/4719 |title=Contact information for Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle - MPS and Lords - UK Parliament |access-date=23 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008124803/https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-bennett-of-manor-castle/4719 |archive-date=8 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> (born 10 February 1966) is a <!--Please do not add \"Australian-born\" without discussion; see WP:OPENPARA and WP:BIRTHPLACE. Where she was born is not relevant to her notability-->British politician and [[journalist]]. She led the [[Green Party of England and Wales]] from September 2012 to September 2016.<ref name=\"new leader\">{{cite web |url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2012/09/03/new-leader-and-deputy-leader-announcement/ |title=New Leader and Deputy Leader announcement |date=3 September 2012 |publisher=Green Party |accessdate=23 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919193517/http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2012/09/03/new-leader-and-deputy-leader-announcement/ |archive-date=19 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite news|title=Natalie Bennett elected new Green Party leader in England and Wales. She beat three other candidates to the position in a poll of Green Party members.|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19462474|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903180137/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19462474|archive-date=3 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361 Green Party: Caroline Lucas and Jonathan Bartley elected as co-leaders] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324224832/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361 |date=24 March 2018 }}.<br />'They saw off competition from five others to succeed Natalie Bennett, who is stepping down after four years'.<br />[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news BBC News] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507000038/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news |date=7 May 2017 }}. Published 2 September 2016. Retrieved 8 September 2016.</ref> Bennett was given a peerage in [[2019 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours|Theresa May's 2019 resignation honours]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/resignation-honours-2019|title=Resignation Honours 2019|website=gov.uk|publisher=Cabinet Office|date=2019-09-10|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910023124/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/resignation-honours-2019|archive-date=10 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBorn and raised in [[Australia]], she began her career as a journalist with regional newspapers in [[New South Wales]] before leaving in 1995 for Thailand, where she worked for [[Australian Volunteers International]] and the ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' newspaper over the next four years. Since settling in Britain in 1999 she has contributed to the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent|Independent]]'' and ''[[The Times|Times]]'' newspapers. Her election as leader of the Greens came six years after she joined the party in January 2006.\n\n==Early life==\nBennett was born on 10 February 1966 in [[Eastwood, New South Wales|Eastwood]], a suburb of [[Sydney]], Australia,<ref name=\"Who's Who 2014\">{{cite web|title=BENNETT, Natalie Louise|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U257973|website=Who's Who 2014|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=10 February 2015|date=November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph - Natalie Bennett - a little green around the gills\">{{cite news|last1=Langley|first1=William|title=Natalie Bennett - a little green around the gills|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/green-party/11442084/Natalie-Bennett-a-little-green-around-the-gills.html|accessdate=3 April 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408195649/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/green-party/11442084/Natalie-Bennett-a-little-green-around-the-gills.html|archive-date=8 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> the daughter of John and Joy Bennett.<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U257973 \"Bennett, Natalie Louise\"], ''Who's Who 2014'', A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2014; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, Nov 2014. Retrieved 9 May 2015 (subscription required).</ref> She was born to [[working class]] teenage parents: a part-time secretary and an apprentice carpenter. Her mother was killed in a car crash in 1989.<ref name=\"BBC - From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader\">{{cite news|last1=Totaro|first1=Paola|title=Natalie Bennett: From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32493939|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=BBC News|date=30 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503200620/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32493939|archive-date=3 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHaving been awarded a [[scholarship]], she was educated at [[MLC School]], an [[Independent school|independent]] day school for girls in [[Burwood, New South Wales|Burwood]], [[New South Wales]].<ref name=\"Telegraph - Natalie Bennett - a little green around the gills\" /><ref name=\":0\">Ferraro, Carmela. [http://inside.org.au/force-of-nature/ \"Force of nature\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427235109/http://inside.org.au/force-of-nature/ |date=27 April 2014 }}. Inside Story. 17 April 2013. Retrieved 27 April 2014.</ref> She then took the degrees of [[Bachelor of Agricultural Science]] (BAgrSc Hons) at the [[University of Sydney]], [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA Hons) in Asian Studies at the [[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]] and [[Master of Arts]] (MA) in [[Mass Communication]] from the [[University of Leicester]], graduating from the latter in 2001.<ref name=\"Who's Who 2014\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/features/leicester-s-greenest-girl |title=Leicester's greenest girl |publisher=.le.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=4 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817035142/http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/features/leicester-s-greenest-girl |archive-date=17 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bbc profile\"/> She was the first member of her family to attend university.<ref name=\"BBC - From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader\" />\n\n==Journalism==\nBennett began her career in journalism in [[New South Wales]], where she worked for various regional newspapers including the ''[[Northern Daily Leader]]'' in [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]]. She left Australia in 1995,<ref name=\":0\" /> and lived for four years in Thailand where she worked for [[Australian Volunteers International]] in the Office of the National Commission of Women's Affairs, before moving to the ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' newspaper, where she was chief foreign sub-editor.\n\nShe settled in the United Kingdom in 1999, and said in a 2013 interview for the Australian ''Inside Story'' website about the country of her birth: \"I can\u2019t imagine going there by choice.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In Britain, Bennett has written for ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s \"Comment is Free\" section since 2006.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2007/jun/02/resource6 |title=Natalie Bennett Profile |work=The Guardian web site |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |accessdate=21 December 2009 |location=London |date=2 June 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203192555/http://www.theguardian.com/global/2007/jun/02/resource6 |archive-date=3 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bennett was also a blogger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/lifematters/stories/2006/1615781.htm |title=How to Run a Carnival of Feminists: Natalie Bennett |first=Kate |last=Evans |date=17 April 2006 |work=Life Matters |publisher=ABC Radio National |accessdate=21 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123205142/http://www.abc.net.au/rn/lifematters/stories/2006/1615781.htm |archive-date=23 November 2007 |url-status=live }} (web note of a broadcast interview)</ref> She was deputy editor and then editor of ''[[The Guardian Weekly]]'' from December 2007 until March 2012. She has also worked for the London-based ''[[The Independent|Independent]]'' and ''[[The Times|Times]]'' newspapers.<ref name=\"bbc profile\"/> In 2012, she took [[voluntary redundancy]] and left journalism.<ref name=\"BBC - From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader\" />\n\n==Political career==\nNatalie Bennett joined the Green Party on 1 January 2006.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later the same year she stood for the Greens in the [[2006 Camden Council election|Camden Council election]] in the Regent's Park ward and again in the [[2010 Camden Council election|Camden Council election of 2010]] in the [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]] ward, but was not elected on either occasion. She was the internal communications coordinator on the national executive of the party from September 2007 to August 2011.\n\nIn January 2010, she was selected to stand for the Parliamentary seat of [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Party name Natalie Bennett as Holborn and St Pancras election candidate|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2010/jan/green-party-name-natalie-bennett-holborn-and-st-pancras-election-candidate|work=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=22 April 2010|accessdate=23 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826191815/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2010/jan/green-party-name-natalie-bennett-holborn-and-st-pancras-election-candidate|archive-date=26 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> She came fourth with 2.7% of the vote.<ref name=\"bbc profile\">{{cite news|last=Rath|first=Kayte|title=Profile: Green Party leader Natalie Bennett|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19465606|work=BBC News|accessdate=23 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115200602/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19465606|archive-date=15 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> She stood next in the [[2012 London Assembly election|London Assembly elections of 2012]], as the fourth placed candidate on the London-wide list for the Green Party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Party leader Natalie Bennett turns fire on Labour|work=BBC News|date=7 September 2012|accessdate=23 December 2012|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19517696|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202194137/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19517696|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===House of Lords===\nBennett was nominated for a [[life peer]]age in September 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/shameless-theresa-gives-gongs-more-19915641|title=Shameless Theresa May gives gongs to more than 40 of her political cronies|last=Glaze|first=Ben|date=2019-09-09|website=mirror|access-date=2019-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921154930/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/shameless-theresa-gives-gongs-more-19915641|archive-date=21 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was created '''Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle''', of Camden in the London Borough of Camden, on 7 October 2019.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62794|date=11 October 2019|page=18260}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/former-green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-named-after-new-sheffield-home-as-she-is-elevated-to-house-of-lords-1-9986170/amp|title=Former Green Party leader Natalie Bennett named after new Sheffield home as she is elevated to House of Lords|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> She becomes the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]' second current member of the [[House of Lords]], joining [[Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb]]. She was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] to the Lords on 15 October 2019 by Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb and [[John Bird, Baron Bird]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction: Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle: 15 Oct 2019: House of Lords debates |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2019-10-15b.23.0 |website=TheyWorkForYou |accessdate=1 November 2019 |language=en |date=15 October 2019}}</ref> and made her [[maiden speech]] on 17 October 2019.<ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction= United Kingdom |title= Queen's Speech |url= https://hansard.parliament.uk/Lords/2019-10-17/debates/33FEA568-1FAF-4F3F-8DF4-B8DB96929A58/Queen%E2%80%99SSpeech#contribution-E4E1AC08-17AF-4BDC-A011-8B4E366881F3 |house= House of Lords |date= 17 October 2019 |column_start= 217 |column_end= 220 |speaker= Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle |position=}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and standpoints==\n[[File:Natalie Bennett Take Back Our World.jpg|thumb|upright|Bennett in \"Take Back Our World! - Global Justice Now\" in 2015.]]\n[[File:Natalie Bennett-IMG 4086.jpg|thumb|upright|Natalie Bennett campaigning in Cambridge during the general election of 2015.]]\nBennett has considered herself a feminist since she was a young child, claiming that it was her \"first politics\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Graham |first=Sarah |url=http://www.feministtimes.com/natalie-bennett-feminism-is |title=Natalie Bennett: Feminism is |publisher=Feministtimes.com |date=10 March 2014 |accessdate=4 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529161116/http://www.feministtimes.com/natalie-bennett-feminism-is/ |archive-date=29 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> She also founded the Green Party women's group and was a trustee of the [[Fawcett Society]] between 2010 and 2014. She became interested in environmental issues when she obtained a degree in Agricultural Sciences.<ref name=\"bbc profile\" /> She is in favour of abolishing the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|monarchy]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.theweek.co.uk/general-election-2015/62176/natalie-bennett-and-the-green-manifesto-zero-growth-free-condoms-no|title = Natalie Bennett and the Green manifesto: zero growth, free condoms, no monarchy|date = 12 March 2015|accessdate = 16 April 2015|website = [[The Week]]|publisher = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150416234559/http://www.theweek.co.uk/general-election-2015/62176/natalie-bennett-and-the-green-manifesto-zero-growth-free-condoms-no|archive-date = 16 April 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> In an April 2015 interview, she said that she supports the Green Party policy of an economic and cultural [[Boycotts of Israel|boycott of Israel]], and also thought that Britain should cease arms sales to Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sandy|last=Rashdy|title=Green leader Natalie Bennett backs cultural boycott of Israel|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|location=London|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=15 August 2015|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/134303/green-leader-natalie-bennett-backs-cultural-boycott-israel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710014850/http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/134303/green-leader-natalie-bennett-backs-cultural-boycott-israel|archive-date=10 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She has also voiced support for [[polygamy]] and [[polyamorous]] relationships.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duffy|first1=Nick|title=Green Party wants every teacher to be trained to teach LGBTIQA+ issues|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/01/green-party-wants-every-teacher-to-be-trained-to-teach-lgbtiq-issues/|accessdate=3 May 2015|newspaper=Pink News|date=1 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518074647/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/01/green-party-wants-every-teacher-to-be-trained-to-teach-lgbtiq-issues/|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Green Party leader===\nOn 3 September 2012, Bennett replaced [[Caroline Lucas]] as leader of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A new leader will not push the Green Party off the political fringe|newspaper=The Economist|date=8 September 2012|accessdate=23 December 2012|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21562254|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121216235010/http://www.economist.com/node/21562254|archive-date=16 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> 3,127 ballot papers were returned in the [[2012 Green Party of England and Wales leadership election|2012 Green Party leadership elections]], a turnout of 25.1%.<ref name=\"new leader\" /> This turnout was explained by Bennett in a BBC interview: \"if you hold an election in the month of August you kind of expect that turnout won't be particularly high\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Natalie Bennett elected as Green Party leader|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19463910|work=BBC News (Daily Politics video)|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905230049/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19463910|archive-date=5 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> On election as party leader Bennett told a press conference that the policies of the Green Party were \"the only viable way forward for British people, for the world\".<ref name=\"BBC1\" />\n\nIn May 2014 she was selected again to contest the Parliamentary seat of [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/05/04/natalie-bennett-selected-to-contest-holborn-and-st-pancras-at-2015-general-election/ | title=Natalie Bennett selected to contest Holborn and St Pancras at 2015 General Election | publisher=[[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] | date=4 May 2014 | accessdate=9 January 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026022923/http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/05/04/natalie-bennett-selected-to-contest-holborn-and-st-pancras-at-2015-general-election/ | archive-date=26 October 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> She was re-elected unopposed as leader of the party in [[2014 Green Party of England and Wales leadership election|September 2014]].\n\nIn February 2015, an interview with Bennett regarding the funding of house-building on the talk radio station [[LBC]] was described by her as \"absolutely excruciating\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-admits-lbc-radio-interview-was-absolutely-excruciating-10067138.html | title=Natalie Bennett admits LBC Radio interview was 'absolutely excruciating' | newspaper=[[The Independent]] | date=24 February 2015 | accessdate=25 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225064757/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-admits-lbc-radio-interview-was-absolutely-excruciating-10067138.html | archive-date=25 February 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> In a halting interview on LBC in which she struggled to explain how her party would pay for 500,000 new council homes it is pledging to build. She told Nick Ferrari the policy would cost \u00a32.7bn, prompting the presenter to ask: \u201cFive hundred thousand homes \u2013 \u00a32.7bn? What are they made of \u2013 plywood?\u201d\n\nIn January 2015 [[Ofcom]] ruled to exclude the Green Party from the televised debates surrounding the 2015 election, on the grounds that the party had not demonstrated \"significant past electoral support in General Elections\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://media.ofcom.org.uk/news/2015/major-parties-consultation/ |title=Ofcom |date=14 September 2016 |access-date=24 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927001811/http://media.ofcom.org.uk/news/2015/major-parties-consultation/ |archive-date=27 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> This ruling led to an upsurge in Green Party support after Bennett called the ruling  \"disgraceful and indefensible\" and [[David Cameron]] claimed that he was \"quite happy for there to be no debates at all\" if the Green Party was not included.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rt.com/uk/220851-greens-excluded-debate-ofcom/ |title=Cameron won't join election TV debates if Greens not included after Ofcom ruling \u2014 RT UK |publisher=Rt.com |date= |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817123045/http://www.rt.com/uk/220851-greens-excluded-debate-ofcom/ |archive-date=17 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/10/13/natalie-bennett-leaders-debates-will-not-be-a-fair-representation-of-politics-if-greens-are-excluded/ |title=Natalie Bennett: Leader's debates will not be a fair representation of politics if Greens are excluded |publisher=Green Party |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224155411/http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/10/13/natalie-bennett-leaders-debates-will-not-be-a-fair-representation-of-politics-if-greens-are-excluded/ |archive-date=24 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> This decision was later reversed, after which the Green Party's support increased again.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2015/01/23/leaders-debates-announced-green-party-statement/ |title=Leaders' Debates announced - Green Party statement |publisher=Green Party |date= |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031435/https://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/2015/01/23/leaders-debates-announced-green-party-statement/ |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[United Kingdom general election debates, 2015#The ITV Leaders' Debate (2 April)|seven-way debate]] ultimately took place on 2 April, with Bennett present.\n\nBennett came third in the election to the Labour and Conservative candidates, and in 2016, at the end of her second two-year term, did not stand for re-election as leader.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Joe|title=Green Party leader Natalie Bennett loses election bid, comes third|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/08/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-loses-election-bid-comes-third/|accessdate=29 May 2017|work=PinkNews|date=8 May 2015|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509000259/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/08/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-loses-election-bid-comes-third/|archive-date=9 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the party's 2016 autumn conference in Birmingham, Lucas and [[Jonathan Bartley]] were elected as co-leaders of the party in a job-share arrangement.<ref>'[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36299465 Natalie Bennett to step down as Green Party leader] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202040544/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36299465 |date=2 February 2019 }}'.<br /> BBC NEWS. Published 16 May 2016. Retrieved 16 May 2016.</ref><ref>'[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-to-quit-at-end-of-august-a7031121.html Green party leader Natalie Bennett to quit at end of August] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723112547/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-to-quit-at-end-of-august-a7031121.html |date=23 July 2016 }}'.<br /> ''The Independent''. Published 15 May 2016. Retrieved 16 May 2016.</ref><ref>'[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/natalie-bennett-to-step-down-as-green-party-leader Natalie Bennett to step down as Green party leader] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202022314/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/natalie-bennett-to-step-down-as-green-party-leader |date=2 December 2016 }}'.<br /> The Guardian [online]. Published 15 May 2016. Retrieved 16 May 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Green Party: Caroline Lucas and Jonathan Bartley elected as co-leaders|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361|work=BBC News|date=2 September 2016|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324224832/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361|archive-date=24 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2017 UK general election===\nOn 7 October 2016, it was announced that Bennett had been selected to contest the [[Sheffield Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Central]] constituency for the Green Party in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-37585844|title=Greens' Natalie Bennett to contest Sheffield Central seat|last=News|first=B. B. C.|work=BBC News|date=7 October 2016|access-date=7 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007135710/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-37585844|archive-date=7 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Bennett's candidacy saw a drop of 7.8% in the share of Green votes as well as a drop in its position from second to third (out of eight candidates) with 3,848 votes.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000919 BBC Election 2017 - Sheffield Central] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006001418/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000919 |date=6 October 2018 }}. Published 9 June 2017. Retrieved 15 June 2017.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nNatalie Bennett is single and lives in [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Natalie Bennett@ Why I am determined to turn Sheffield Green|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/natalie-bennett-why-i-am-determined-to-turn-sheffield-green-1-8289929|accessdate=18 April 2017|work=The Yorkshire Post|date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419101753/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/natalie-bennett-why-i-am-determined-to-turn-sheffield-green-1-8289929|archive-date=19 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> During her time as leader her partner was Jim Jepps, a left-wing activist who was a member of the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] (SWP) for approximately a decade before leaving the party around 2003.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lamden|first1=Tim|title=Green Party leader Natalie Bennett: That car crash interview will keep following me|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/green_party_leader_natalie_bennett_that_car_crash_interview_will_keep_following_me_1_4019300|accessdate=7 May 2016|work=Ham&High|date=2 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507121956/http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/green_party_leader_natalie_bennett_that_car_crash_interview_will_keep_following_me_1_4019300|archive-date=7 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jepps|first1=Jim|title=Five things I learned when leaving the SWP|url=http://www.jimjepps.net/five-things-i-learned-when-leaving-the-swp/|website=The nice badge man|accessdate=16 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416152241/http://www.jimjepps.net/five-things-i-learned-when-leaving-the-swp/|archive-date=16 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Editor, Thailand Country Study: Best Practice Guide on Sustainable Action Against Child Labour (1998) {{ISBN|974-8369-59-5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4337 |title=Thailand Country Study Towards a Best Practice Guide on Sustainable Action Against Child Labour |date=January 1998 |publisher=International Labour Organisation |accessdate=12 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508154548/http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4337 |archive-date=8 May 2013 |url-status=dead }} (Copy of the paper on Bennett's web site)</ref>\n*Editor, Women's Health and Development, Country Profile Thailand<ref>{{cite web |url=http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4343 |title=Women's Health and Development: Country Profile, Thailand:Authors |work=Women's Health and Development |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=12 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508164122/http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4343 |archive-date=8 May 2013 |url-status=dead }} (Copy of the paper on Bennett's web site)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Natalie Bennett}}\n* {{official website|https://www.natalie4sheffield.org/}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patrick Ensor]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Editor of ''[[The Guardian Weekly]]''|years=2007\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=Abby Deveney}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Caroline Lucas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]|years=2012\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonathan Bartley]]|after2=[[Caroline Lucas]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{GPEW|Leadership}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bennett, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British republicans]]\n[[Category:British social commentators]]\n[[Category:Green Party of England and Wales life peers]]\n[[Category:Green Party of England and Wales parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at MLC School]]\n[[Category:People from Somers Town, London]]\n[[Category:University of New England (Australia) alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n[[Category:The Independent people]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:Women newspaper editors]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Naftali Bennett}}\n{{short description|Former Leader of the Green Party of England and Wales, Member of the House of Lords}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle\n|image       = Official portrait of Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle crop 2.jpg\n|caption     = Natalie Bennett pictured in 2019\n|office5         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5       =  7 October 2019<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n|term_end45       =\n|office2      = [[Leader of the Green Party of England and Wales]]\n|deputy2      = [[Will Duckworth]] (2012\u20132014)<br />[[Amelia Womack]] and [[Shahrar Ali]] (2014\u20132016)\n|term_start2  = 3 September 2012\n|term_end2    = 2 September 2016\n|predecessor2 = [[Caroline Lucas]]\n|successor2   = [[Jonathan Bartley]] and<br /> [[Caroline Lucas]] \n|birth_name  = Natalie Louise Bennett\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1966|2|10|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Eastwood, New South Wales|Eastwood]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|party       = {{Nowrap|[[Green Party of England and Wales]]}}\n|partner     = \n|alma_mater  = {{Nowrap|[[University of Sydney]], Australia <br />[[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]], Australia <br />[[University of Leicester]], UK}}\n}}\n\n'''Natalie Louise Bennett, Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-bennett-of-manor-castle/4719 |title=Contact information for Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle - MPS and Lords - UK Parliament |access-date=23 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008124803/https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-bennett-of-manor-castle/4719 |archive-date=8 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> (born 10 February 1966) is a <!--Please do not add \"Australian-born\" without discussion; see WP:OPENPARA and WP:BIRTHPLACE. Where she was born is not relevant to her notability-->British politician and [[journalist]]. She led the [[Green Party of England and Wales]] from September 2012 to September 2016.<ref name=\"new leader\">{{cite web |url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2012/09/03/new-leader-and-deputy-leader-announcement/ |title=New Leader and Deputy Leader announcement |date=3 September 2012 |publisher=Green Party |accessdate=23 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919193517/http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2012/09/03/new-leader-and-deputy-leader-announcement/ |archive-date=19 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite news|title=Natalie Bennett elected new Green Party leader in England and Wales. She beat three other candidates to the position in a poll of Green Party members.|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19462474|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903180137/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19462474|archive-date=3 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361 Green Party: Caroline Lucas and Jonathan Bartley elected as co-leaders] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324224832/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361 |date=24 March 2018 }}.<br />'They saw off competition from five others to succeed Natalie Bennett, who is stepping down after four years'.<br />[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news BBC News] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507000038/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news |date=7 May 2017 }}. Published 2 September 2016. Retrieved 8 September 2016.</ref> Bennett was given a peerage in [[2019 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours|Theresa May\u2019s 2019 resignation honours]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/resignation-honours-2019|title=Resignation Honours 2019|website=gov.uk|publisher=Cabinet Office|date=2019-09-10|access-date=2019-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910023124/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/resignation-honours-2019|archive-date=10 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBorn and raised in [[Australia]], she began her career as a journalist with regional newspapers in [[New South Wales]] before leaving in 1995 for Thailand, where she worked for [[Australian Volunteers International]] and the ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' newspaper over the next four years. Since settling in Britain in 1999 she has contributed to the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent|Independent]]'' and ''[[The Times|Times]]'' newspapers. Her election as leader of the Greens came six years after she joined the party in January 2006.\n\n==Early life==\nBennett was born on 10 February 1966 in [[Eastwood, New South Wales|Eastwood]], a suburb of [[Sydney]], Australia,<ref name=\"Who's Who 2014\">{{cite web|title=BENNETT, Natalie Louise|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U257973|website=Who's Who 2014|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=10 February 2015|date=November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph - Natalie Bennett - a little green around the gills\">{{cite news|last1=Langley|first1=William|title=Natalie Bennett - a little green around the gills|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/green-party/11442084/Natalie-Bennett-a-little-green-around-the-gills.html|accessdate=3 April 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408195649/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/green-party/11442084/Natalie-Bennett-a-little-green-around-the-gills.html|archive-date=8 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> the daughter of John and Joy Bennett.<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U257973 \"Bennett, Natalie Louise\"], ''Who's Who 2014'', A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2014; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, Nov 2014. Retrieved 9 May 2015 (subscription required).</ref> She was born to [[working class]] teenage parents: a part-time secretary and an apprentice carpenter. Her mother was killed in a car crash in 1989.<ref name=\"BBC - From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader\">{{cite news|last1=Totaro|first1=Paola|title=Natalie Bennett: From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32493939|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=BBC News|date=30 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503200620/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32493939|archive-date=3 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHaving been awarded a [[scholarship]], she was educated at [[MLC School]], an [[Independent school|independent]] day school for girls in [[Burwood, New South Wales|Burwood]], [[New South Wales]].<ref name=\"Telegraph - Natalie Bennett - a little green around the gills\" /><ref name=\":0\">Ferraro, Carmela. [http://inside.org.au/force-of-nature/ \"Force of nature\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427235109/http://inside.org.au/force-of-nature/ |date=27 April 2014 }}. Inside Story. 17 April 2013. Retrieved 27 April 2014.</ref> She then took the degrees of [[Bachelor of Agricultural Science]] (BAgrSc Hons) at the [[University of Sydney]], [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA Hons) in Asian Studies at the [[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]] and [[Master of Arts]] (MA) in [[Mass Communication]] from the [[University of Leicester]], graduating from the latter in 2001.<ref name=\"Who's Who 2014\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/features/leicester-s-greenest-girl |title=Leicester's greenest girl |publisher=.le.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=4 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817035142/http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/features/leicester-s-greenest-girl |archive-date=17 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bbc profile\"/> She was the first member of her family to attend university.<ref name=\"BBC - From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader\" />\n\n==Journalism==\nBennett began her career in journalism in [[New South Wales]], where she worked for various regional newspapers including the ''[[Northern Daily Leader]]'' in [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]]. She left Australia in 1995,<ref name=\":0\" /> and lived for four years in Thailand where she worked for [[Australian Volunteers International]] in the Office of the National Commission of Women's Affairs, before moving to the ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' newspaper, where she was chief foreign sub-editor.\n\nShe settled in the United Kingdom in 1999, and said in a 2013 interview for the Australian ''Inside Story'' website about the country of her birth: \"I can\u2019t imagine going there by choice.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In Britain, Bennett has written for ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s \"Comment is Free\" section since 2006.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2007/jun/02/resource6 |title=Natalie Bennett Profile |work=The Guardian web site |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |accessdate=21 December 2009 |location=London |date=2 June 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203192555/http://www.theguardian.com/global/2007/jun/02/resource6 |archive-date=3 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bennett was also a blogger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/lifematters/stories/2006/1615781.htm |title=How to Run a Carnival of Feminists: Natalie Bennett |first=Kate |last=Evans |date=17 April 2006 |work=Life Matters |publisher=ABC Radio National |accessdate=21 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123205142/http://www.abc.net.au/rn/lifematters/stories/2006/1615781.htm |archive-date=23 November 2007 |url-status=live }} (web note of a broadcast interview)</ref> She was deputy editor and then editor of ''[[The Guardian Weekly]]'' from December 2007 until March 2012. She has also worked for the London-based ''[[The Independent|Independent]]'' and ''[[The Times|Times]]'' newspapers.<ref name=\"bbc profile\"/> In 2012, she took [[voluntary redundancy]] and left journalism.<ref name=\"BBC - From 'Jillaroo' to Green Party leader\" />\n\n==Political career==\nNatalie Bennett joined the Green Party on 1 January 2006.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later the same year she stood for the Greens in the [[2006 Camden Council election|Camden Council election]] in the Regent's Park ward and again in the [[2010 Camden Council election|Camden Council election of 2010]] in the [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]] ward, but was not elected on either occasion. She was the internal communications coordinator on the national executive of the party from September 2007 to August 2011.\n\nIn January 2010, she was selected to stand for the Parliamentary seat of [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Party name Natalie Bennett as Holborn and St Pancras election candidate|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2010/jan/green-party-name-natalie-bennett-holborn-and-st-pancras-election-candidate|work=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=22 April 2010|accessdate=23 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826191815/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2010/jan/green-party-name-natalie-bennett-holborn-and-st-pancras-election-candidate|archive-date=26 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> She came fourth with 2.7% of the vote.<ref name=\"bbc profile\">{{cite news|last=Rath|first=Kayte|title=Profile: Green Party leader Natalie Bennett|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19465606|work=BBC News|accessdate=23 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115200602/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19465606|archive-date=15 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> She stood next in the [[2012 London Assembly election|London Assembly elections of 2012]], as the fourth placed candidate on the London-wide list for the Green Party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Party leader Natalie Bennett turns fire on Labour|work=BBC News|date=7 September 2012|accessdate=23 December 2012|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19517696|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202194137/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19517696|archive-date=2 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===House of Lords===\nBennett was nominated for a [[life peer]]age in September 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/shameless-theresa-gives-gongs-more-19915641|title=Shameless Theresa May gives gongs to more than 40 of her political cronies|last=Glaze|first=Ben|date=2019-09-09|website=mirror|access-date=2019-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921154930/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/shameless-theresa-gives-gongs-more-19915641|archive-date=21 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and was created '''Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle''', of Camden in the London Borough of Camden, on 7 October 2019.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62794|date=11 October 2019|page=18260}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/former-green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-named-after-new-sheffield-home-as-she-is-elevated-to-house-of-lords-1-9986170/amp|title=Former Green Party leader Natalie Bennett named after new Sheffield home as she is elevated to House of Lords|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> She becomes the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]' second current member of the [[House of Lords]], joining [[Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb]]. She was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] to the Lords on 15 October 2019 by Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb and [[John Bird, Baron Bird]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction: Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle: 15 Oct 2019: House of Lords debates |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2019-10-15b.23.0 |website=TheyWorkForYou |accessdate=1 November 2019 |language=en |date=15 October 2019}}</ref> and made her [[maiden speech]] on 17 October 2019.<ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction= United Kingdom |title= Queen's Speech |url= https://hansard.parliament.uk/Lords/2019-10-17/debates/33FEA568-1FAF-4F3F-8DF4-B8DB96929A58/Queen%E2%80%99SSpeech#contribution-E4E1AC08-17AF-4BDC-A011-8B4E366881F3 |house= House of Lords |date= 17 October 2019 |column_start= 217 |column_end= 220 |speaker= Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle |position=}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and standpoints==\n[[File:Natalie Bennett Take Back Our World.jpg|thumb|upright|Bennett in \"Take Back Our World! - Global Justice Now\" in 2015.]]\n[[File:Natalie Bennett-IMG 4086.jpg|thumb|upright|Natalie Bennett campaigning in Cambridge during the general election of 2015.]]\nBennett has considered herself a feminist since she was a young child, claiming that it was her \"first politics\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Graham |first=Sarah |url=http://www.feministtimes.com/natalie-bennett-feminism-is |title=Natalie Bennett: Feminism is |publisher=Feministtimes.com |date=10 March 2014 |accessdate=4 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529161116/http://www.feministtimes.com/natalie-bennett-feminism-is/ |archive-date=29 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> She also founded the Green Party women's group and was a trustee of the [[Fawcett Society]] between 2010 and 2014. She became interested in environmental issues when she obtained a degree in Agricultural Sciences.<ref name=\"bbc profile\" /> She is in favour of abolishing the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|monarchy]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.theweek.co.uk/general-election-2015/62176/natalie-bennett-and-the-green-manifesto-zero-growth-free-condoms-no|title = Natalie Bennett and the Green manifesto: zero growth, free condoms, no monarchy|date = 12 March 2015|accessdate = 16 April 2015|website = [[The Week]]|publisher = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150416234559/http://www.theweek.co.uk/general-election-2015/62176/natalie-bennett-and-the-green-manifesto-zero-growth-free-condoms-no|archive-date = 16 April 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> In an April 2015 interview, she said that she supports the Green Party policy of an economic and cultural [[Boycotts of Israel|boycott of Israel]], and also thought that Britain should cease arms sales to Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sandy|last=Rashdy|title=Green leader Natalie Bennett backs cultural boycott of Israel|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|location=London|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=15 August 2015|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/134303/green-leader-natalie-bennett-backs-cultural-boycott-israel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710014850/http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/134303/green-leader-natalie-bennett-backs-cultural-boycott-israel|archive-date=10 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She has also voiced support for [[polygamy]] and [[polyamorous]] relationships.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duffy|first1=Nick|title=Green Party wants every teacher to be trained to teach LGBTIQA+ issues|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/01/green-party-wants-every-teacher-to-be-trained-to-teach-lgbtiq-issues/|accessdate=3 May 2015|newspaper=Pink News|date=1 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518074647/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/01/green-party-wants-every-teacher-to-be-trained-to-teach-lgbtiq-issues/|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Green Party leader===\nOn 3 September 2012, Bennett replaced [[Caroline Lucas]] as leader of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A new leader will not push the Green Party off the political fringe|newspaper=The Economist|date=8 September 2012|accessdate=23 December 2012|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21562254|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121216235010/http://www.economist.com/node/21562254|archive-date=16 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> 3,127 ballot papers were returned in the [[2012 Green Party of England and Wales leadership election|2012 Green Party leadership elections]], a turnout of 25.1%.<ref name=\"new leader\" /> This turnout was explained by Bennett in a BBC interview: \"if you hold an election in the month of August you kind of expect that turnout won't be particularly high\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Natalie Bennett elected as Green Party leader|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19463910|work=BBC News (Daily Politics video)|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905230049/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19463910|archive-date=5 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> On election as party leader Bennett told a press conference that the policies of the Green Party were \"the only viable way forward for British people, for the world\".<ref name=\"BBC1\" />\n\nIn May 2014 she was selected again to contest the Parliamentary seat of [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/05/04/natalie-bennett-selected-to-contest-holborn-and-st-pancras-at-2015-general-election/ | title=Natalie Bennett selected to contest Holborn and St Pancras at 2015 General Election | publisher=[[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] | date=4 May 2014 | accessdate=9 January 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026022923/http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/05/04/natalie-bennett-selected-to-contest-holborn-and-st-pancras-at-2015-general-election/ | archive-date=26 October 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> She was re-elected unopposed as leader of the party in [[2014 Green Party of England and Wales leadership election|September 2014]].\n\nIn February 2015, an interview with Bennett regarding the funding of house-building on the talk radio station [[LBC]] was described by her as \"absolutely excruciating\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-admits-lbc-radio-interview-was-absolutely-excruciating-10067138.html | title=Natalie Bennett admits LBC Radio interview was 'absolutely excruciating' | newspaper=[[The Independent]] | date=24 February 2015 | accessdate=25 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225064757/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-admits-lbc-radio-interview-was-absolutely-excruciating-10067138.html | archive-date=25 February 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> In a halting interview on LBC in which she struggled to explain how her party would pay for 500,000 new council homes it is pledging to build. She told Nick Ferrari the policy would cost \u00a32.7bn, prompting the presenter to ask: \u201cFive hundred thousand homes \u2013 \u00a32.7bn? What are they made of \u2013 plywood?\u201d\n\nIn January 2015 [[Ofcom]] ruled to exclude the Green Party from the televised debates surrounding the 2015 election, on the grounds that the party had not demonstrated \"significant past electoral support in General Elections\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://media.ofcom.org.uk/news/2015/major-parties-consultation/ |title=Ofcom |date=14 September 2016 |access-date=24 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927001811/http://media.ofcom.org.uk/news/2015/major-parties-consultation/ |archive-date=27 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> This ruling led to an upsurge in Green Party support after Bennett called the ruling  \"disgraceful and indefensible\" and [[David Cameron]] claimed that he was \"quite happy for there to be no debates at all\" if the Green Party was not included.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rt.com/uk/220851-greens-excluded-debate-ofcom/ |title=Cameron won't join election TV debates if Greens not included after Ofcom ruling \u2014 RT UK |publisher=Rt.com |date= |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817123045/http://www.rt.com/uk/220851-greens-excluded-debate-ofcom/ |archive-date=17 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/10/13/natalie-bennett-leaders-debates-will-not-be-a-fair-representation-of-politics-if-greens-are-excluded/ |title=Natalie Bennett: Leader's debates will not be a fair representation of politics if Greens are excluded |publisher=Green Party |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224155411/http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2014/10/13/natalie-bennett-leaders-debates-will-not-be-a-fair-representation-of-politics-if-greens-are-excluded/ |archive-date=24 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> This decision was later reversed, after which the Green Party's support increased again.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greenparty.org.uk/news/2015/01/23/leaders-debates-announced-green-party-statement/ |title=Leaders' Debates announced - Green Party statement |publisher=Green Party |date= |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031435/https://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/2015/01/23/leaders-debates-announced-green-party-statement/ |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[United Kingdom general election debates, 2015#The ITV Leaders' Debate (2 April)|seven-way debate]] ultimately took place on 2 April, with Bennett present.\n\nBennett came third in the election to the Labour and Conservative candidates, and in 2016, at the end of her second two-year term, did not stand for re-election as leader.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Joe|title=Green Party leader Natalie Bennett loses election bid, comes third|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/08/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-loses-election-bid-comes-third/|accessdate=29 May 2017|work=PinkNews|date=8 May 2015|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509000259/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/05/08/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-loses-election-bid-comes-third/|archive-date=9 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the party's 2016 autumn conference in Birmingham, Lucas and [[Jonathan Bartley]] were elected as co-leaders of the party in a job-share arrangement.<ref>'[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36299465 Natalie Bennett to step down as Green Party leader] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202040544/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36299465 |date=2 February 2019 }}'.<br /> BBC NEWS. Published 16 May 2016. Retrieved 16 May 2016.</ref><ref>'[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-to-quit-at-end-of-august-a7031121.html Green party leader Natalie Bennett to quit at end of August] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723112547/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/green-party-leader-natalie-bennett-to-quit-at-end-of-august-a7031121.html |date=23 July 2016 }}'.<br /> ''The Independent''. Published 15 May 2016. Retrieved 16 May 2016.</ref><ref>'[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/natalie-bennett-to-step-down-as-green-party-leader Natalie Bennett to step down as Green party leader] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202022314/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/natalie-bennett-to-step-down-as-green-party-leader |date=2 December 2016 }}'.<br /> The Guardian [online]. Published 15 May 2016. Retrieved 16 May 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Green Party: Caroline Lucas and Jonathan Bartley elected as co-leaders|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361|work=BBC News|date=2 September 2016|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324224832/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37251361|archive-date=24 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2017 UK general election===\nOn 7 October 2016, it was announced that Bennett had been selected to contest the [[Sheffield Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Central]] constituency for the Green Party in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-37585844|title=Greens' Natalie Bennett to contest Sheffield Central seat|last=News|first=B. B. C.|work=BBC News|date=7 October 2016|access-date=7 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007135710/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-37585844|archive-date=7 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Bennett's candidacy saw a drop of 7.8% in the share of Green votes as well as a drop in its position from second to third (out of eight candidates) with 3,848 votes.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000919 BBC Election 2017 - Sheffield Central] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006001418/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000919 |date=6 October 2018 }}. Published 9 June 2017. Retrieved 15 June 2017.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nNatalie Bennett is single and lives in [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Natalie Bennett@ Why I am determined to turn Sheffield Green|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/natalie-bennett-why-i-am-determined-to-turn-sheffield-green-1-8289929|accessdate=18 April 2017|work=The Yorkshire Post|date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419101753/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/natalie-bennett-why-i-am-determined-to-turn-sheffield-green-1-8289929|archive-date=19 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> During her time as leader her partner was Jim Jepps, a left-wing activist who was a member of the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] (SWP) for approximately a decade before leaving the party around 2003.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lamden|first1=Tim|title=Green Party leader Natalie Bennett: That car crash interview will keep following me|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/green_party_leader_natalie_bennett_that_car_crash_interview_will_keep_following_me_1_4019300|accessdate=7 May 2016|work=Ham&High|date=2 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507121956/http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/green_party_leader_natalie_bennett_that_car_crash_interview_will_keep_following_me_1_4019300|archive-date=7 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jepps|first1=Jim|title=Five things I learned when leaving the SWP|url=http://www.jimjepps.net/five-things-i-learned-when-leaving-the-swp/|website=The nice badge man|accessdate=16 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416152241/http://www.jimjepps.net/five-things-i-learned-when-leaving-the-swp/|archive-date=16 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Editor, Thailand Country Study: Best Practice Guide on Sustainable Action Against Child Labour (1998) {{ISBN|974-8369-59-5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4337 |title=Thailand Country Study Towards a Best Practice Guide on Sustainable Action Against Child Labour |date=January 1998 |publisher=International Labour Organisation |accessdate=12 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508154548/http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4337 |archive-date=8 May 2013 |url-status=dead }} (Copy of the paper on Bennett's web site)</ref>\n*Editor, Women's Health and Development, Country Profile Thailand<ref>{{cite web |url=http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4343 |title=Women's Health and Development: Country Profile, Thailand:Authors |work=Women's Health and Development |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=12 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508164122/http://philobiblon.co.uk/?page_id=4343 |archive-date=8 May 2013 |url-status=dead }} (Copy of the paper on Bennett's web site)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Natalie Bennett}}\n* {{official website|https://www.natalie4sheffield.org/}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patrick Ensor]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Editor of ''[[The Guardian Weekly]]''|years=2007\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=Abby Deveney}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Caroline Lucas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]]|years=2012\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonathan Bartley]]|after2=[[Caroline Lucas]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{GPEW|Leadership}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bennett, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British republicans]]\n[[Category:British social commentators]]\