{"title_page": "Tourniquet (Marilyn Manson song)", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tourniquet\n| cover      = Mmtourniquet.JPG\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]]\n| album      = [[Antichrist Superstar]]\n| released   = September 8, 1997\n| format     = [[Single (music)|12\" / CD single]]\n| recorded   = New Orleans, Louisiana, 1996\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Gothic rock]]\n| length     = 4:29 <small>(Single & album version)</small><br/>4:44 <small>(Extended fade version)</small>\n| label      = [[Nothing Records|Nothing]] / [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     = [[Marilyn Manson]] (lyrics)<br/>[[Jeordie White|Twiggy Ramirez]], [[Daisy Berkowitz]]  (music)\n| producer   = [[Trent Reznor]]<br/>[[Dave Ogilvie]]<br/>Marilyn Manson\n| prev_title = [[Long Hard Road Out of Hell]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[The Dope Show]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Marilyn Manson - Tourniquet.ogg\n | description = \"Tourniquet\"\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Tourniquet'''\" is the second major-label single by the band [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]], from the second studio album ''[[Antichrist Superstar]]''. The image this song conveys is that of the main character in a world of sorrow and self-pity, prior to his transformation into the [[Daniel 7|Little Horn]]. It was written by frontman Marilyn Manson, co-founder [[Daisy Berkowitz]] and longtime bassist and guitarist [[Twiggy Ramirez]]. Like many other songs from ''Antichrist Superstar'', the song's lyrics are based on a dream Manson had.\n\nThe song was used as the theme music for professional wrestler [[Jeff Hardy]] during his stint with [[Ring Of Honor]]. The song is also featured as downloadable content for Guitar Hero: Warriors of Rock as part of the \"February Mega Pack.\" The song also can be learned on guitar with Rocksmith 2014 Remastered. The song was part of the Marilyn Manson song pack that became available on July 25, 2017.\n\n==Background==\nManson told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'': \"I've always had these dreams about making a girl out of all these pieces of prosthetic limbs, and then taking my own hair and teeth that I saved from when I was a kid and very ritualistically creating this companion.\" Those dreams were the inspiration for \"Tourniquet\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123|title=Marilyn Manson: Sympathy for the Devil|author=Strauss, Neil|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 23, 1997|accessdate=January 13, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423144646/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123|archivedate=April 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Tourniquet\" is a [[gothic rock]] song<ref name=goth/> with a length of four minutes and thirty seconds.<ref>{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/tourniquet-mw0000378056|title=Tourniquet \u2013 Marilyn Manson |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> It begins with the [[backmasking|backwards]] message \"This is my lowest point of vulnerability\".<ref name=loudwire>{{cite magazine| url=http://loudwire.com/best-marilyn-manson-songs/| last=Heartmann| first=Graham| title=10 Best Marilyn Manson Songs| magazine=[[Loudwire]]| date=January 5, 2013| accessdate=December 26, 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727221155/http://loudwire.com/best-marilyn-manson-songs/| archivedate=July 27, 2016}}</ref> Like many Marilyn Manson songs from the first three albums, some of the lyrics to this song were previously a poem [[Marilyn Manson|Manson]] had written prior to the formation of the band. [[Lorraine Ali]] of ''Rolling Stone'' wrote that while the influence of [[Alice Cooper (band)|Alice Cooper]] is present throughout ''Antichrist Superstar'', it is \"full-blown\" on \"Tourniquet\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|last=Ali |first=Lorraine |authorlink=Lorraine Ali |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/antichrist-superstar-19961029 |title=Antichrist Superstar - Rolling Stone |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=October 29, 1996 |accessdate=March 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423164708/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/antichrist-superstar-19961029 |archivedate=April 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nFor [[MetalSucks]], Axl Rosenberg called \"Tourniquet\" and \"[[Lunchbox (song)|Lunchbox]]\" some of \"Manson's best early material\".<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2017/10/23/original-marilyn-manson-guitarist-scott-daisy-berkowitz-putesky-dead-at-49/| last=Rosenberg| first=Axl| title=Original Marilyn Manson Guitarist Scott \"Daisy Berkowitz\" Putesky Dead At 49|website=[[MetalSucks]]| date=October 23, 2017| accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] said that \"Not every [Marilyn Manson] single had a great hook -- 'Tourniquet' is a moody dirge, indicative of what awaits a listener on the album tracks\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lest-we-forget-the-best-of-mw0000396316 |title=Lest We Forget: The Best Of \u2013 Marilyn Manson |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> Matt Zakosek of ''[[The Chicago Maroon]]'' called the track \"weary Goth-rock junk\" and criticized its inclusion on the [[greatest hits album]] ''[[Lest We Forget: The Best Of]]'' (2004).<ref name=goth>{{cite web| url=https://www.chicagomaroon.com/article/2004/10/17/a-shocking-thing-about-manson-cd-it-doesnt-suck/| last=Zakosek| first=Matt| title=A shocking thing about Manson CD: It doesn't suck|website=[[The Chicago Maroon]]| date=October 17, 2004| accessdate=January 18, 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120234007/https://www.chicagomaroon.com/article/2004/10/17/a-shocking-thing-about-manson-cd-it-doesnt-suck/| archivedate=January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe video for \"Tourniquet\" was directed by [[Floria Sigismondi]], who also directed the video for \"[[The Beautiful People (song)|The Beautiful People]]\". Sigismondi says that directing the video got her to gain confidence in herself and her \"offbeat ideas\". In order to gain inspiration for the video, she went through a period of [[sleep deprivation]], and was elated to see her ideas for the video \"manifest into physical form.\" Sigismondi discussed the video's impact with Claire Lobenfeld of ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'', saying \"It was shocking to see that so many people responded to that [video's] imagery like they did. I'm sure there was a lot of different things at work there \u2013 the song, the lyrics, [Manson's] image \u2013 coupled with the video, but I do believe that in a way we all have the same rooted fears and dreams \u2013 part of that '[[collective unconscious]]'.\"<ref name=fact>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/10/11/floria-sigismondi-music-video-director-interview/| last=Lobenfeld | first=Caire| title=Bj\u00f6rk and Rihanna director Floria Sigismondi tells the stories behind her pioneering videos| magazine=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]| date=October 11, 2017| accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n'''Australian Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" - 7:24\n#\"The Horrible People\" - 5:12\n\n'''UK (CD I) / European Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" (edit) - 4:10\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" - 7:24\n\n'''UK (CD II) Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n#\"Lunchbox\" - 4:34\n#\"Next Motherfucker\" (Lunchbox) - 4:48\n\n===Promo===\n'''U.S. Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n\n'''UK 7\"'''\n*A-Side: \"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n*B-Side: \"[[The Perfect Drug]]\" - 5:15\n\n'''UK 12\"'''\n*A & B Side\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" - 7:24\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" (Edit) - 4:10\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''[[Musician]]s:'''\n* [[Marilyn Manson]] \u2014 [[singing|vocals]], lyrics\n* [[Scott Putesky|Daisy Berkowitz]] \u2014 guitar, music\n* [[Jeordie White|Twiggy Ramirez]] \u2014 bass guitar, music\n* [[Madonna Wayne Gacy]] \u2014 keyboards\n* [[Ginger Fish]] \u2014 drums\n{{col-break}}\n'''[[Record producer|Production]]:'''\n* [[Trent Reznor]] \u2014 producer\n* [[Dave Ogilvie|Dave \"Rave\" Ogilvie]] \u2014 producer\n* Marilyn Manson \u2014 co-producer\n* [[Sean Beavan]] \u2014 mixing\n* [[Chris Vrenna]] \u2014 editing and programming\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|MmfQ7gSaJgM|Tourniquet}}\n\n{{Marilyn Manson}}\n\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:Marilyn Manson (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Floria Sigismondi]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:1996 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Marilyn Manson]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jeordie White]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records singles]]\n[[Category:Gothic rock songs]]\n[[Category:Songs based on poems]]\n", "text_old": "{{more references|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tourniquet\n| cover      = Mmtourniquet.JPG\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]]\n| album      = [[Antichrist Superstar]]\n| released   = September 8, 1997\n| format     = [[Single (music)|12\" / CD single]]\n| recorded   = New Orleans, Louisiana, 1996\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Gothic rock]]\n| length     = 4:29 <small>(Single & album version)</small><br/>4:44 <small>(Extended fade version)</small>\n| label      = [[Nothing Records|Nothing]] / [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     = [[Marilyn Manson]] (lyrics)<br/>[[Jeordie White|Twiggy Ramirez]], [[Daisy Berkowitz]]  (music)\n| producer   = [[Trent Reznor]]<br/>[[Dave Ogilvie]]<br/>Marilyn Manson\n| prev_title = [[Long Hard Road Out of Hell]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[The Dope Show]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Marilyn Manson - Tourniquet.ogg\n | description = \"Tourniquet\"\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Tourniquet'''\" is the second major-label single by the band [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]], from the second studio album ''[[Antichrist Superstar]]''. The image this song conveys is that of the main character in a world of sorrow and self-pity, prior to his transformation into the [[Daniel 7|Little Horn]]. It was written by frontman Marilyn Manson, co-founder [[Daisy Berkowitz]] and longtime bassist and guitarist [[Twiggy Ramirez]]. Like many other songs from ''Antichrist Superstar'', the songs lyrics are based on a dream Manson had.\n\nThe song was used as the theme music for professional wrestler [[Jeff Hardy]] during his stint with [[Ring Of Honor]]. The song is also featured as downloadable content for Guitar Hero: Warriors of Rock as part of the \"February Mega Pack.\" The song also can be learned on guitar with Rocksmith 2014 Remastered. The song was part of the Marilyn Manson song pack that became available on July 25, 2017.\n\n==Background==\nManson told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'': \"I've always had these dreams about making a girl out of all these pieces of prosthetic limbs, and then taking my own hair and teeth that I saved from when I was a kid and very ritualistically creating this companion.\" Those dreams were the inspiration for \"Tourniquet\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123|title=Marilyn Manson: Sympathy for the Devil|author=Strauss, Neil|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 23, 1997|accessdate=January 13, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423144646/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sympathy-for-the-devil-marilyn-manson-19970123|archivedate=April 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Tourniquet\" is a [[gothic rock]] song<ref name=goth/> with a length of four minutes and thirty seconds.<ref>{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/tourniquet-mw0000378056|title=Tourniquet \u2013 Marilyn Manson |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> It begins with the [[backmasking|backwards]] message \"This is my lowest point of vulnerability\".<ref name=loudwire>{{cite magazine| url=http://loudwire.com/best-marilyn-manson-songs/| last=Heartmann| first=Graham| title=10 Best Marilyn Manson Songs| magazine=[[Loudwire]]| date=January 5, 2013| accessdate=December 26, 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727221155/http://loudwire.com/best-marilyn-manson-songs/| archivedate=July 27, 2016}}</ref> Like many Marilyn Manson songs from the first three albums, some of the lyrics to this song were previously a poem [[Marilyn Manson|Manson]] had written prior to the formation of the band. [[Lorraine Ali]] of ''Rolling Stone'' wrote that while the influence of [[Alice Cooper (band)|Alice Cooper]] is present throughout ''Antichrist Superstar'', it is \"full-blown\" on \"Tourniquet\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|last=Ali |first=Lorraine |authorlink=Lorraine Ali |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/antichrist-superstar-19961029 |title=Antichrist Superstar - Rolling Stone |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=October 29, 1996 |accessdate=March 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423164708/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/antichrist-superstar-19961029 |archivedate=April 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nFor [[MetalSucks]], Axl Rosenberg called \"Tourniquet\" and \"[[Lunchbox (song)|Lunchbox]]\" some of \"Manson's best early material\".<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2017/10/23/original-marilyn-manson-guitarist-scott-daisy-berkowitz-putesky-dead-at-49/| last=Rosenberg| first=Axl| title=Original Marilyn Manson Guitarist Scott \"Daisy Berkowitz\" Putesky Dead At 49|website=[[MetalSucks]]| date=October 23, 2017| accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] said that \"Not every [Marilyn Manson] single had a great hook -- 'Tourniquet' is a moody dirge, indicative of what awaits a listener on the album tracks\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lest-we-forget-the-best-of-mw0000396316 |title=Lest We Forget: The Best Of \u2013 Marilyn Manson |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> Matt Zakosek of ''[[The Chicago Maroon]]'' called the track \"weary Goth-rock junk\" and criticized its inclusion on the [[greatest hits album]] ''[[Lest We Forget: The Best Of]]'' (2004).<ref name=goth>{{cite web| url=https://www.chicagomaroon.com/article/2004/10/17/a-shocking-thing-about-manson-cd-it-doesnt-suck/| last=Zakosek| first=Matt| title=A shocking thing about Manson CD: It doesn't suck|website=[[The Chicago Maroon]]| date=October 17, 2004| accessdate=January 18, 2018| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120234007/https://www.chicagomaroon.com/article/2004/10/17/a-shocking-thing-about-manson-cd-it-doesnt-suck/| archivedate=January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe video for \"Tourniquet\" was directed by [[Floria Sigismondi]], who also directed the video for \"[[The Beautiful People (song)|The Beautiful People]]\". Sigismondi says that directing the video got her to gain confidence in herself and her \"offbeat ideas\". In order to gain inspiration for the video, she went through a period of [[sleep deprivation]], and was elated to see her ideas for the video \"manifest into physical form.\" Sigismondi discussed the video's impact with Claire Lobenfeld of ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'', saying \"It was shocking to see that so many people responded to that [video's] imagery like they did. I'm sure there was a lot of different things at work there \u2013 the song, the lyrics, [Manson's] image \u2013 coupled with the video, but I do believe that in a way we all have the same rooted fears and dreams \u2013 part of that '[[collective unconscious]]'.\"<ref name=fact>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/10/11/floria-sigismondi-music-video-director-interview/| last=Lobenfeld | first=Caire| title=Bj\u00f6rk and Rihanna director Floria Sigismondi tells the stories behind her pioneering videos| magazine=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]| date=October 11, 2017| accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n'''Australian Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" - 7:24\n#\"The Horrible People\" - 5:12\n\n'''UK (CD I) / European Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" (edit) - 4:10\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" - 7:24\n\n'''UK (CD II) Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n#\"Lunchbox\" - 4:34\n#\"Next Motherfucker\" (Lunchbox) - 4:48\n\n===Promo===\n'''U.S. Release'''\n#\"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n\n'''UK 7\"'''\n*A-Side: \"Tourniquet\" - 4:29\n*B-Side: \"[[The Perfect Drug]]\" - 5:15\n\n'''UK 12\"'''\n*A & B Side\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" - 7:24\n#\"The Tourniquet Prosthetic Dance Mix\" (Edit) - 4:10\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''[[Musician]]s:'''\n* [[Marilyn Manson]] \u2014 [[singing|vocals]], lyrics\n* [[Scott Putesky|Daisy Berkowitz]] \u2014 guitar, music\n* [[Jeordie White|Twiggy Ramirez]] \u2014 bass guitar, music\n* [[Madonna Wayne Gacy]] \u2014 keyboards\n* [[Ginger Fish]] \u2014 drums\n{{col-break}}\n'''[[Record producer|Production]]:'''\n* [[Trent Reznor]] \u2014 produc