{"title_page": "Kamlesh Patel, Baron Patel of Bradford", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}\n[[File:Official portrait of Lord Patel of Bradford crop 2.jpg|thumb|Lord Patel]]'''Kamlesh Kumar Patel, Baron Patel of Bradford''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (born 28 September 1960) is a [[life peer|member]] of the [[House of Lords]].\n\nA qualified Social Worker, he worked in inner city Bradford and then established a number of Third Sector agencies working with those misusing drugs and those with mental health problems; later moving to academia working with a number of universities.\n\nHaving been appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1999 Birthday Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55513 |date=12 June 1999 |page=12 |supp=y}}</ref> he was created a [[life peer]] with the title '''Baron Patel of Bradford''', of [[Bradford]] in the County of [[West Yorkshire]] on 8 June 2006.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58027 |date=26 June 2006 |page=8671}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2018, Lord Patel of Bradford was appointed by the Secretary of State for Education and the Secretary of State for Health & Social Care as the Chair of Social Work England.  Social Work England will be the new regulator for all child, family and adult social workers in England.\n\nLord Patel of Bradford was previously chair of the [[Mental Health Act Commission]].<ref>[http://www.mhac.org.uk/?q=node/10 Mental Health Act Commission - MHAC Board]</ref>  He was a Commissioner of the [[Healthcare Commission]] and The National Treatment Agency for Substance Misuse.  He has authored a number of national reports including The Patel Report into Prison Drug Treatment.\n\nLord Patel is also Senior Independent Director of the England Wales Cricket Board (ECB), appointed in 2016.\n\nVice President of the British Board of Film Classification, appointed in May 2018 and resigned in May 2018 <ref>:[//beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/00117289/officers]</ref>\n\nHe is Vice Patron of the Royal Society for Public Health and the Institute of Healthcare Management; and Patron/Chairman of a number of not for profit organisations working in the health, education, social care and criminal justice sectors.\n\n'''Academic/Professional Qualifications''' \n\n\u2022 Diploma in Social Work DipSW University of Huddersfield. (1987) \n\u2022 Certificate of Qualification in Social Work CQSW University of Huddersfield. (1987) \n\u2022 Doctor of Letters (Honoris Causa) Manchester Metropolitan University. (2007) \n\u2022 Doctor of Civil Law (Honoris Causa) University of Huddersfield. (2008) \n\u2022 Professor University of Central Lancashire. (2001) \n\u2022 Professorial Fellow of Public Health: Royal Society of Public Health London. (2012) \n\u2022 Professorial Fellow of Mental Health: The Institute of Mental Health Nottingham. (2012) \n\u2022 Doctor of Health (Honorary Degree) University of Bradford. (2017) \n\u2022 Honorary Fellowship of the American Public Health Association. (2017) \n\u2022 Doctor of Science (Honorary Degree) University of Southampton (July 2018) \n\n'''Awards'''\n\n\u2022 OBE Awarded Order of British Empire in the Queen's Birthday Honours (1999) for \u201cServices to Ethnic Minority Health Issues\u201d. \n\u2022 Long service medal (Special Constable) \u2013 West Yorkshire Police (1991) \n\u2022 Awarded Plaque of Recognition by the High Commissioner of India and Chairman of the Committee of Honour for \u201ccontributions to the enhancement of human welfare and international understanding\u201d Indian High Commission London. (1999) \n\u2022 Awarded Glory of India Award and Certificate of Excellence by the India International Friendship Society London (2009) \n\u2022 Awarded Annual Award of Achievement for services to Education by The India International Foundation: London (2009) \n\u2022 GG2 Leadership Awards - Man of the Year Award for consistent lifetime achievement and contribution to public sector services (2015) AMG Awards London \n\u2022 Yorkshire Man of the Year: Award for lifetime contribution to the County of Yorkshire (2016) Yorkshire Society \n\n'''GOVERNMENT''' \n\n\u2022 Life Peer: House of Lords (Independent): Baron Patel of Bradford. (June 2006). \n\n\u2022 Minister: (Labour) Governments Whips Office House of Lords, Government Frontbench Spokesperson (2008 \u2013 2009) for: \n- Department of Communities & Local Government\n- Ministry of Justice\n- Cabinet Office \n- Attorney General's Office. \n\n\u2022 Shadow Front Bench Minister: (Communities), House of Lords (May 2010\u20132012). \n\u2022 Member: Select Committee on the Mental Capacity Act 2005 (2013-2015) \n\u2022 Member: Monitors\u2019 Fair Playing Field Review Implementation Group (2013-2015) \n\u2022 UK Member: UNICEF's Global Task Force on Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (2006-2010) - an international Task Force that included every major global charity in the world working on water, sanitation and hygiene to develop a strategy with the aim of meeting one of the Millennium Development Goals. \n\u2022 Senior Ministerial Advisor: to the Secretary of State (Communities & Local Government), (2008) \u2013 advising on the impact and effectiveness of the Government's PREVENT strategy for addressing the growth of extremism. \n\u2022 National Strategic Director: National Institute for Mental Health England (2002-2004) \n\u2022 National Director: The Department of Health Delivering Race Equality in mental health care programme (DRE). (2004-2006) \n\u2022 Chairman: of DRE Board (2004-2006) - a major multi-million pound Government national strategy and action plan that was implemented across England and Wales. DRE was one of the largest mental health race equality programmes ever undertaken and was based on Lord Patel's 10 years of action research. \n\u2022 Member: Labour Party Drugs Working Group (non-political advisory appointment) (1989-1990).\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mmu.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/2007/ Manchester Metropolitan University's Honorands for 2007]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel Of Bradford}}\n[[Category:People's peers]] <!--only title-->\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]<!--only title-->\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society for Public Health]]\n[[Category:People educated at Belle Vue Boys' Grammar School, Bradford]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}\n[[File:Official portrait of Lord Patel of Bradford crop 2.jpg|thumb|Lord Patel]]'''Kamlesh Kumar Patel, Baron Patel of Bradford''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (born 28 September 1960) is a [[life peer|member]] of the [[House of Lords]].\n\nA qualified Social Worker, he worked in inner city Bradford and then established a number of Third Sector agencies working with those misusing drugs and those with mental health problems; later moving to academia working with a number of universities.\n\nHaving been appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1999 Birthday Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55513 |date=12 June 1999 |page=12 |supp=y}}</ref> he was created a [[life peer]] with the title '''Baron Patel of Bradford''', of [[Bradford]] in the County of [[West Yorkshire]] on 8 June 2006.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58027 |date=26 June 2006 |page=8671}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2018, Lord Patel of Bradford was appointed by the Secretary of State for Education and the Secretary of State for Health & Social Care as the Chair of Social Work England.  Social Work England will be the new regulator for all child, family and adult social workers in England.\n\nLord Patel of Bradford was previously chair of the [[Mental Health Act Commission]].<ref>[http://www.mhac.org.uk/?q=node/10 Mental Health Act Commission - MHAC Board]</ref>  He was a Commissioner of the [[Healthcare Commission]] and The National Treatment Agency for Substance Misuse.  He has authored a number of national reports including The Patel Report into Prison Drug Treatment.\n\nLord Patel is also Senior Independent Director of the England Wales Cricket Board (ECB), appointed in 2016.\n\nVice President of the British Board of Film Classification, appointed in May 2018 and resigned in May 2018 <ref>:[//beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/00117289/officers]</ref>\n\nHe is Vice Patron of the Royal Society for Public Health and the Institute of Healthcare Management; and Patron/Chairman of a number of not for profit organisations working in the health, education, social care and criminal justice sectors.\n\n'''Academic/Professional Qualifications''' \n\n\u2022 Diploma in Social Work DipSW University of Huddersfield. (1987) \n\u2022 Certificate of Qualification in Social Work CQSW University of Huddersfield. (1987) \n\u2022 Doctor of Letters (Honoris Causa) Manchester Metropolitan University. (2007) \n\u2022 Doctor of Civil Law (Honoris Causa) University of Huddersfield. (2008) \n\u2022 Professor University of Central Lancashire. (2001) \n\u2022 Professorial Fellow of Public Health: Royal Society of Public Health London. (2012) \n\u2022 Professorial Fellow of Mental Health: The Institute of Mental Health Nottingham. (2012) \n\u2022 Doctor of Health (Honorary Degree) University of Bradford. (2017) \n\u2022 Honorary Fellowship of the American Public Health Association. (2017) \n\u2022 Doctor of Science (Honorary Degree) University of Southampton (July 2018) \n\n'''Awards'''\n\n\u2022 OBE Awarded Order of British Empire in the Queen\u2019s Birthday Honours (1999) for \u201cServices to Ethnic Minority Health Issues\u201d. \n\u2022 Long service medal (Special Constable) \u2013 West Yorkshire Police (1991) \n\u2022 Awarded Plaque of Recognition by the High Commissioner of India and Chairman of the Committee of Honour for \u201ccontributions to the enhancement of human welfare and international understanding\u201d Indian High Commission London. (1999) \n\u2022 Awarded Glory of India Award and Certificate of Excellence by the India International Friendship Society London (2009) \n\u2022 Awarded Annual Award of Achievement for services to Education by The India International Foundation: London (2009) \n\u2022 GG2 Leadership Awards - Man of the Year Award for consistent lifetime achievement and contribution to public sector services (2015) AMG Awards London \n\u2022 Yorkshire Man of the Year: Award for lifetime contribution to the County of Yorkshire (2016) Yorkshire Society \n\n'''GOVERNMENT''' \n\n\u2022 Life Peer: House of Lords (Independent): Baron Patel of Bradford. (June 2006). \n\n\u2022 Minister: (Labour) Governments Whips Office House of Lords, Government Frontbench Spokesperson (2008 \u2013 2009) for: \n- Department of Communities & Local Government\n- Ministry of Justice\n- Cabinet Office \n- Attorney General\u2019s Office. \n\n\u2022 Shadow Front Bench Minister: (Communities), House of Lords (May 2010\u20132012). \n\u2022 Member: Select Committee on the Mental Capacity Act 2005 (2013-2015) \n\u2022 Member: Monitors\u2019 Fair Playing Field Review Implementation Group (2013-2015) \n\u2022 UK Member: UNICEF\u2019s Global Task Force on Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (2006-2010) - an international Task Force that included every major global charity in the world working on water, sanitation and hygiene to develop a strategy with the aim of meeting one of the Millennium Development Goals. \n\u2022 Senior Ministerial Advisor: to the Secretary of State (Communities & Local Government), (2008) \u2013 advising on the impact and effectiveness of the Government\u2019s PREVENT strategy for addressing the growth of extremism. \n\u2022 National Strategic Director: National Institute for Mental Health England (2002-2004) \n\u2022 National Director: The Department of Health Delivering Race Equality in mental health care programme (DRE). (2004-2006) \n\u2022 Chairman: of DRE Board (2004-2006) - a major multi-million pound Government national strategy and action plan that was implemented across England and Wales. DRE was one of the largest mental health race equality programmes ever undertaken and was based on Lord Patel\u2019s 10 years of action research. \n\u2022 Member: Labour Party Drugs Working Group (non-political advisory appointment) (1989-1990).\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mmu.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/2007/ Manchester Metropolitan University's Honorands for 2007]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel Of Bradford}}\n[[Category:People's peers]] <!--only title-->\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]<!--only title-->\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society for Public Health]]\n[[Category:People educated at Belle Vue Boys' Grammar School, Bradford]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamlesh_Patel,_Baron_Patel_of_Bradford"}
{"title_page": "Deborah Bull, Baroness Bull", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2017}}\n{{one source|date=March 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| honorific-prefix = \n| name        = The Baroness Bull\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]\n| image       = Official portrait of Baroness Bull crop 2.jpg\n| caption     =\n| office2     = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start2 = 11 July 2018<ref name=LG /><br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| term_end2   =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1963|03|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Derby]], England\n| nationality = British\n| occupation  = {{hlist|Ballet dancer|writer|broadcaster|creative director}}\n| education   = [[Royal Ballet School]]\n| party       = [[Crossbench]]\n}}\n\n'''Deborah Bull, Baroness Bull''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 22 March 1963) is an English dancer, writer, and broadcaster and former creative director of the [[Royal Opera House]]. Deborah joined [[King's College London]] as Director, Cultural Partnerships in 2012. In 2015 she was appointed as the university's Assistant Principal (London) and in 2018 was named Vice President & Vice-Principal (London).\n\nBorn in [[Derby]], and brought up in [[Kent]] and [[Lincolnshire]], she studied dance from the age of seven, first locally, and then, on the recommendation of her teacher, at the [[Royal Ballet School]]. Whilst at the school she won the 1980 [[Prix de Lausanne]], the prestigious international ballet competition.\n\n== Ballet career ==\nShe was invited to join [[The Royal Ballet]] in 1981, having toured with the company as a student during the summer. The teachers that Bull identified as the \"resident teachers\" were [[Brian Shaw]], [[Alexander Agadzhanov]], [[Betty Anderton]] and the Norwegian [[Gerd Larsen]]. Bull particularly admired Larsen's ability to introduce mime.<ref name=bull>{{cite book|last=Bull|first=Deborah|title=Everyday dancer|date=2011|isbn=0571260942|pages=19\u201320|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0571260942}}</ref> Bull was promoted through the ranks and gained principal status in 1992, immediately following the company's opening performance in Japan, at which she danced the role of Gamzatti in La Bayadere.\n\nDuring her twenty years in The Royal Ballet, she danced a wide range of work throughout the repertoire. Her leading roles in the classics included Odette/Odile in ''Swan Lake'', Aurora in ''The Sleeping Beauty'' and Kitri in ''Don Quixote'', and she created roles for [[Ashley Page]], [[David Bintley]], [[Michael Corder]], Emma Diamond, [[Wayne McGregor]], [[Glen Tetley]] and [[Twyla Tharp]]. She received particular praise for her performances in the works of [[George Balanchine]] and [[William Forsythe (choreographer)|William Forsythe]]. In 1995 Forsythe staged for her the first performance in this country of his ballet ''Steptext'', and she was subsequently nominated for a 1996 Olivier Award in the 'Outstanding Achievement In Dance' Category for her interpretation. She was named as 1996 Dancer of the Year by both ''The Sunday Express'' and ''The Independent on Sunday'', who praised her work both on and off the stage, saying 'here is a dancer whose intelligence and courage - for once - don't reside entirely in the tips of her toes'.\n\nAway from The Royal Ballet, she toured Italy, North America and Canada with [[Wayne Eagling]]'s group, 'Stars of the Royal Ballet', and was invited to join [[Irek Mukhamedov]] for the debut performances of his company 'Irek Mukhamedov and Friends' in 1992. She danced at the 1993 and 1995 Harrogate International Festival, and in April 1996 was invited to perform in the first 'Diamonds of World Ballet' Gala at the Kremlin Palace, Moscow. She has toured Japan with Tetsuya Kumakawa and in the summers of 1994 and 1995 she organised, staged and starred in ''An Evening of British Ballet'' at the Sintra Festival in Portugal. In March 2001, she was invited to star in the triple bill Nijinsky Ritrovato at the Rome Opera House, dancing the Chosen Maiden in ''Rite of Spring'' and alongside Carla Fracci in ''Jeux''.\n\n== Artists\u2019 Development Initiative ==\nIn addition to her work with The Royal Ballet, she founded in 1998 the Artists\u2019 Development Initiative at the Royal Opera House, a programme designed to open up the resources and expertise within the theatre to small-scale companies and independent artists. Over its first two years, ADI worked with over 250 artists from outside the Royal Opera House and facilitated collaborations across art forms and between independent choreographers and classical dancers. ADI shared the 2001 ''Time Out'' Award for Outstanding Achievement in Dance with [[Wayne McGregor]] for Symbiont(s), premiered in the Clore Studio Upstairs in June 2000.\n\n== ROH2 ==\nShe retired from The Royal Ballet in August 2001 to take up a new position at the Royal Opera House in January 2002, as Creative Director, [[ROH2]], developing a range of small-scale and experimental artistic initiatives and overseeing the programme in the theatre's alternative performance spaces. In 2004, her remit expanded to include the delivery of a strategy for the ROH's work away from the main stage, including an alternative performance programme, opera and dance development initiatives, Big Screen live relays from the main stage, an \u2018On the Road\u2019 programme and daytime activities in the building. In addition, she managed ROH Collections, the Royal Opera House's extensive archives, and was focused on the organisation's Olympic planning and audience engagement strategies. In 2008, she was made Creative Director of the Royal Opera House, a post she held until 2012.\n\n== Publishing ==\nIn addition to her work as a dancer, she has regularly written and lectured on the arts. In January 1996 she debated at the Oxford Union, opposing the motion 'This House Believes the National Lottery Gives Too Much Money to the Elitist Arts'. Her address was described by [[Grey Ruthven, 2nd Earl of Gowrie|Lord Gowrie]], her debating partner, as 'the best speech I have heard on the Arts in 30 years'. The motion was heavily defeated, a triumph which the ''Evening Standard'' attributed largely to 'the eloquence of a ballerina, unaccustomed to public speaking', describing her speech as 'cogently argued and delivered with generosity of spirit'.\n\nIn October 1996 she was invited by Lord Gowrie to deliver the Arts Council Annual Lecture at the Royal Society for the Arts, 'From Private Patronage to Public Purse'.\n\nShe has written articles for ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', ''[[Classic FM Magazine]]'', ''[[New Statesman]]'' and ''[[The Spectator]]'', and reviewed for ''The Telegraph'', ''[[The Literary Review]]'' and several dance magazines. From 1999 to 2001 she wrote a regular column, Private View, for ''The Telegraph''.\n\nAside from the Arts, she has a passionate interest in health and fitness, and has taught nutrition to the students of the Royal Ballet School as well as chairing the [[Prix de Lausanne]]\u2019s annual seminars on dance related health matters.\n\nShe has published three books. ''The Vitality Plan'', ([[Dorling Kindersley]], January 1998) was published simultaneously in the United States as ''Totally Fit'', and has since been translated into seven different languages. ''Dancing Away'' ([[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]], October 1998) is a diary of The Royal Ballet's first year \u2018on the road\u2019, as the Royal Opera House underwent its extensive and controversial redevelopment. To mark publication, Deborah was commissioned to read five extracts from the book on [[BBC Radio 4]]. ''Dancing Away'' was described by ''[[The Spectator]]'' as \u2018arguably the most amusing and fascinating dance book ever published\u2019. ''The Faber Pocket Guide to Ballet'', jointly with Luke Jennings, was published in 2004, describing important historical and repertoire ballets with a 'View from the Wings' by Bull of her personal thoughts on dancing in a piece. A second book for [[Faber and Faber|Faber]]'', The Everyday Dancer'', appeared in 2011.\n\n==Broadcasting career==\n===Television===\nHer first programme for television, ''Dance Ballerina, Dance'', was screened at Christmas 1998 as part of BBC 2's ''Dance Night'', an evening devoted entirely to dance which she co-presented along with the comedian [[Alexei Sayle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/dance-event-of-the-week-dance-night-monday-bbc2-1194361.html|title=Dance; Event of the week - Dance Night, Monday BBC2|date=26 December 1998|newspaper=Independent|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> ''Travels With My Tutu'', written and presented by Bull, was screened over Christmas 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/522e03cc9d994257b7d2127400192385|title=Travels with My Tutu - BBC Two England - 15 December 2000 - BBC Genome|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> This four part BBC2 series explored breakdance, jive, belly dance and tango and attracted record audiences.\n\nShe has presented live on [[BBC Two]] from the Royal Opera House (''[[Copp\u00e9lia]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/e197134e70604860861530a6027b6598|title=Copp\u00e9lia - BBC Two England - 19 February 2000 - BBC Genome|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> and ''The Nutcracker'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/cfd8ed9746884d49b345be09ed0458fd|title=The Royal Ballet in The Nutcracker - BBC Two England - 30 December 2000 - BBC Genome|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> both in 2000) and from [[Sadler's Wells Theatre|Sadler's Wells]] (Rambert Dance Company), as well as a live [[The Proms|Proms]] performance on [[BBC One]] in 2004. In June 2001, she presented the [[Eurovision Young Dancers 2001]] competition from the [[Linbury Studio Theatre]], broadcast to 18 European nations as well as BBC2 and [[BBC Knowledge]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/eurovision-young-dancers-competition-and-the-vote-from-norway-is-9257964.html|title=Eurovision Young Dancers competition: and the vote from Norway is...|date=21 June 2001|newspaper=Independent|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> She was also the UK's commentator for the contest in {{Escyr|1999|Dancers}}, {{Escyr|2003|Dancers}} and {{Escyr|2005|Dancers}}. Her three part, award-winning series for BBC2, ''[[The Dancer's Body]]'', was screened in September and October 2002.\n\nIn March 2017, Bull was one of the judges who decided which of the finalists in the ballet category of the ''[[BBC Young Dancer|BBC Young Dancer 2017]]'' competition would make it through to the overall final.<ref name=\"BBC Young Dancer 2017\">{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08kgywv|title= Ballet Final: BBC Young Dancer 2017|author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= [[BBC Online]] |publisher= BBC | accessdate= 31 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Radio===\nShe has made programmes for, and contributes regularly to, BBC Radio 4 including ''Dancing Away'' (1998), ''Leaving Barons Court'' (1999), ''Breaking the Law'' (2001) and ''Law in Order'' (2002), ''A Dance Through Time'' (2004), ''Happy Feet'' (2008) and ''Hothouse Kids'' (2009). She presented ''Sounds of Dance'', a four-part series for [[BBC Radio 3]] from December 2003 to January 2004.\n\nIn 2012, Bull presented the five-part [[BBC Radio 4]] series, ''Dance Nation'', on English dance.<ref name=\"BBC Dance Nation 2012\">{{cite episode| title= Deborah Bull's Dance Nation| series= Deborah Bull's Dance Nation| serieslink= | credits= Presenter: Deborah Bull; Producer:  Hannah Rosenfelder| network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01mvzll | airdate= September 2012| accessdate= 31 March 2017 }}</ref> She was the castaway on BBC Radio 4's ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in May the following year.<ref name=\"Desert Island Discs\">{{cite episode| title= Deborah Bull| series= [[Desert Island Discs]]| credits= Presenter: [[Kirsty Young]]; Producer:  Cathy Drysdale |network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01slqck| airdate= 31 May 2013| accessdate= 1 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== Public service ==\nShe was a member of the [[Arts Council England]] from 1998 to 2005 and a Governor of the BBC from 2003 to 2006. Additionally, she is a patron of the [[National Osteoporosis Society]], Foundation for Community Dance and Escape Artists (a theatre company of paroled and ex-prisoners), sits on the Board of the [[Prix de Lausanne]] and is an Honorary Vice President of Voices of British Ballet. \n\nShe was a judge for the 2010 [[Man Booker Prize]]. She has been awarded Honorary Doctorates by [[University of Derby]] (1998), [[Sheffield Hallam University]] (2001), [[University of Kent|Kent University]] (2010) and the [[Open University]] (2005) and was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the Queen's [[1999 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55513 |date=12 June 1999 |page=8 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, it was announced that Bull had been appointed the first Executive Director of [[King's College London]]'s King's Cultural Institute, and would be taking up the role in March 2012.<ref name=\"KCL December 2011\">{{cite web |url= http://www.kcl.ac.uk/newsevents/news/newsrecords/2011/12December/Kings-College-London-appoints-Deborah-Bull-Executive-Director-Kings-Cultural-Institute.aspx|title= Deborah Bull joins King's College London |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 5 December 2011 |website= www.kcl.ac.uk |publisher= [[King's College London]]| accessdate= 1 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBull was nominated for a [[life peer]]age by the [[House of Lords Appointments Commission]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brickcourt.co.uk/document-uploads/HOLAC_080618.doc|title=Three new non-party-political peers}}</ref> She was created '''Baroness Bull''', of Aldwych in the City of Westminster, on 11 July.<ref name=\"LG\">{{London Gazette|issue=62352|date=16 July 2018|page=12576}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.deborahbull.com}}\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01slqck Deborah Bull] on ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in 2013\n*[https://archive.is/20121223022337/http://www.kent.ac.uk/news/homepagestories/honorary-degrees-nov10/2010/  Honorary Degree (University of Kent)]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-prec|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Rosie Boycott|The Baroness Boycott]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Order of precedence in England and Wales#Ladie|Ladies]]|years=}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Suzanne Heywood|The Lady Heywood of Whitehall]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bull, Deborah}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal Ballet School]]\n[[Category:Principal dancers of The Royal Ballet]]\n[[Category:People from Derby]]\n[[Category:English ballerinas]]\n[[Category:BBC Governors]]\n[[Category:People's peers]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Prix de Lausanne winners]]\n[[Category:Royal Opera House]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2017}}\n{{one source|date=March 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| honorific-prefix = \n| name        = The Baroness Bull\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]\n| image       = Official portrait of Baroness Bull crop 2.jpg\n| caption     =\n| office2     = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start2 = 11 July 2018<ref name=LG /><br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| term_end2   =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1963|03|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Derby]], England\n| nationality = British\n| occupation  = {{hlist|Ballet dancer|writer|broadcaster|creative director}}\n| education   = [[Royal Ballet School]]\n| party       = [[Crossbench]]\n}}\n\n'''Deborah Bull, Baroness Bull''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 22 March 1963) is an English dancer, writer, and broadcaster and former creative director of the [[Royal Opera House]]. Deborah joined [[King's College London]] as Director, Cultural Partnerships in 2012. In 2015 she was appointed as the university's Assistant Principal (London) and in 2018 was named Vice President & Vice-Principal (London).\n\nBorn in [[Derby]], and brought up in [[Kent]] and [[Lincolnshire]], she studied dance from the age of seven, first locally, and then, on the recommendation of her teacher, at the [[Royal Ballet School]]. Whilst at the school she won the 1980 [[Prix de Lausanne]], the prestigious international ballet competition.\n\n== Ballet career ==\nShe was invited to join [[The Royal Ballet]] in 1981, having toured with the company as a student during the summer. The teachers that Bull identified as the \"resident teachers\" were [[Brian Shaw]], [[Alexander Agadzhanov]], [[Betty Anderton]] and the Norwegian [[Gerd Larsen]]. Bull particularly admired Larsen's ability to introduce mime.<ref name=bull>{{cite book|last=Bull|first=Deborah|title=Everyday dancer|date=2011|isbn=0571260942|pages=19\u201320|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0571260942}}</ref> Bull was promoted through the ranks and gained principal status in 1992, immediately following the company's opening performance in Japan, at which she danced the role of Gamzatti in La Bayadere.\n\nDuring her twenty years in The Royal Ballet, she danced a wide range of work throughout the repertoire. Her leading roles in the classics included Odette/Odile in ''Swan Lake'', Aurora in ''The Sleeping Beauty'' and Kitri in ''Don Quixote'', and she created roles for [[Ashley Page]], [[David Bintley]], [[Michael Corder]], Emma Diamond, [[Wayne McGregor]], [[Glen Tetley]] and [[Twyla Tharp]]. She received particular praise for her performances in the works of [[George Balanchine]] and [[William Forsythe (choreographer)|William Forsythe]]. In 1995 Forsythe staged for her the first performance in this country of his ballet ''Steptext'', and she was subsequently nominated for a 1996 Olivier Award in the 'Outstanding Achievement In Dance' Category for her interpretation. She was named as 1996 Dancer of the Year by both ''The Sunday Express'' and ''The Independent on Sunday'', who praised her work both on and off the stage, saying 'here is a dancer whose intelligence and courage - for once - don't reside entirely in the tips of her toes'.\n\nAway from The Royal Ballet, she toured Italy, North America and Canada with [[Wayne Eagling]]'s group, 'Stars of the Royal Ballet', and was invited to join [[Irek Mukhamedov]] for the debut performances of his company 'Irek Mukhamedov and Friends' in 1992. She danced at the 1993 and 1995 Harrogate International Festival, and in April 1996 was invited to perform in the first 'Diamonds of World Ballet' Gala at the Kremlin Palace, Moscow. She has toured Japan with Tetsuya Kumakawa and in the summers of 1994 and 1995 she organised, staged and starred in ''An Evening of British Ballet'' at the Sintra Festival in Portugal. In March 2001, she was invited to star in the triple bill Nijinsky Ritrovato at the Rome Opera House, dancing the Chosen Maiden in ''Rite of Spring'' and alongside Carla Fracci in ''Jeux''.\n\n== Artists\u2019 Development Initiative ==\nIn addition to her work with The Royal Ballet, she founded in 1998 the Artists\u2019 Development Initiative at the Royal Opera House, a programme designed to open up the resources and expertise within the theatre to small-scale companies and independent artists. Over its first two years, ADI worked with over 250 artists from outside the Royal Opera House and facilitated collaborations across art forms and between independent choreographers and classical dancers. ADI shared the 2001 ''Time Out'' Award for Outstanding Achievement in Dance with [[Wayne McGregor]] for Symbiont(s), premiered in the Clore Studio Upstairs in June 2000.\n\n== ROH2 ==\nShe retired from The Royal Ballet in August 2001 to take up a new position at the Royal Opera House in January 2002, as Creative Director, [[ROH2]], developing a range of small-scale and experimental artistic initiatives and overseeing the programme in the theatre\u2019s alternative performance spaces. In 2004, her remit expanded to include the delivery of a strategy for the ROH's work away from the main stage, including an alternative performance programme, opera and dance development initiatives, Big Screen live relays from the main stage, an \u2018On the Road\u2019 programme and daytime activities in the building. In addition, she managed ROH Collections, the Royal Opera House's extensive archives, and was focused on the organisation\u2019s Olympic planning and audience engagement strategies. In 2008, she was made Creative Director of the Royal Opera House, a post she held until 2012.\n\n== Publishing ==\nIn addition to her work as a dancer, she has regularly written and lectured on the arts. In January 1996 she debated at the Oxford Union, opposing the motion 'This House Believes the National Lottery Gives Too Much Money to the Elitist Arts'. Her address was described by [[Grey Ruthven, 2nd Earl of Gowrie|Lord Gowrie]], her debating partner, as 'the best speech I have heard on the Arts in 30 years'. The motion was heavily defeated, a triumph which the ''Evening Standard'' attributed largely to 'the eloquence of a ballerina, unaccustomed to public speaking', describing her speech as 'cogently argued and delivered with generosity of spirit'.\n\nIn October 1996 she was invited by Lord Gowrie to deliver the Arts Council Annual Lecture at the Royal Society for the Arts, 'From Private Patronage to Public Purse'.\n\nShe has written articles for ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', ''[[Classic FM Magazine]]'', ''[[New Statesman]]'' and ''[[The Spectator]]'', and reviewed for ''The Telegraph'', ''[[The Literary Review]]'' and several dance magazines. From 1999 to 2001 she wrote a regular column, Private View, for ''The Telegraph''.\n\nAside from the Arts, she has a passionate interest in health and fitness, and has taught nutrition to the students of the Royal Ballet School as well as chairing the [[Prix de Lausanne]]\u2019s annual seminars on dance related health matters.\n\nShe has published three books. ''The Vitality Plan'', ([[Dorling Kindersley]], January 1998) was published simultaneously in the United States as ''Totally Fit'', and has since been translated into seven different languages. ''Dancing Away'' ([[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]], October 1998) is a diary of The Royal Ballet's first year \u2018on the road\u2019, as the Royal Opera House underwent its extensive and controversial redevelopment. To mark publication, Deborah was commissioned to read five extracts from the book on [[BBC Radio 4]]. ''Dancing Away'' was described by ''[[The Spectator]]'' as \u2018arguably the most amusing and fascinating dance book ever published\u2019. ''The Faber Pocket Guide to Ballet'', jointly with Luke Jennings, was published in 2004, describing important historical and repertoire ballets with a 'View from the Wings' by Bull of her personal thoughts on dancing in a piece. A second book for [[Faber and Faber|Faber]]'', The Everyday Dancer'', appeared in 2011.\n\n==Broadcasting career==\n===Television===\nHer first programme for television, ''Dance Ballerina, Dance'', was screened at Christmas 1998 as part of BBC 2's ''Dance Night'', an evening devoted entirely to dance which she co-presented along with the comedian [[Alexei Sayle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/dance-event-of-the-week-dance-night-monday-bbc2-1194361.html|title=Dance; Event of the week - Dance Night, Monday BBC2|date=26 December 1998|newspaper=Independent|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> ''Travels With My Tutu'', written and presented by Bull, was screened over Christmas 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/522e03cc9d994257b7d2127400192385|title=Travels with My Tutu - BBC Two England - 15 December 2000 - BBC Genome|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> This four part BBC2 series explored breakdance, jive, belly dance and tango and attracted record audiences.\n\nShe has presented live on [[BBC Two]] from the Royal Opera House (''[[Copp\u00e9lia]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/e197134e70604860861530a6027b6598|title=Copp\u00e9lia - BBC Two England - 19 February 2000 - BBC Genome|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> and ''The Nutcracker'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/cfd8ed9746884d49b345be09ed0458fd|title=The Royal Ballet in The Nutcracker - BBC Two England - 30 December 2000 - BBC Genome|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> both in 2000) and from [[Sadler's Wells Theatre|Sadler's Wells]] (Rambert Dance Company), as well as a live [[The Proms|Proms]] performance on [[BBC One]] in 2004. In June 2001, she presented the [[Eurovision Young Dancers 2001]] competition from the [[Linbury Studio Theatre]], broadcast to 18 European nations as well as BBC2 and [[BBC Knowledge]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/eurovision-young-dancers-competition-and-the-vote-from-norway-is-9257964.html|title=Eurovision Young Dancers competition: and the vote from Norway is...|date=21 June 2001|newspaper=Independent|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> She was also the UK's commentator for the contest in {{Escyr|1999|Dancers}}, {{Escyr|2003|Dancers}} and {{Escyr|2005|Dancers}}. Her three part, award-winning series for BBC2, ''[[The Dancer's Body]]'', was screened in September and October 2002.\n\nIn March 2017, Bull was one of the judges who decided which of the finalists in the ballet category of the ''[[BBC Young Dancer|BBC Young Dancer 2017]]'' competition would make it through to the overall final.<ref name=\"BBC Young Dancer 2017\">{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08kgywv|title= Ballet Final: BBC Young Dancer 2017|author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= [[BBC Online]] |publisher= BBC | accessdate= 31 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Radio===\nShe has made programmes for, and contributes regularly to, BBC Radio 4 including ''Dancing Away'' (1998), ''Leaving Barons Court'' (1999), ''Breaking the Law'' (2001) and ''Law in Order'' (2002), ''A Dance Through Time'' (2004), ''Happy Feet'' (2008) and ''Hothouse Kids'' (2009). She presented ''Sounds of Dance'', a four-part series for [[BBC Radio 3]] from December 2003 to January 2004.\n\nIn 2012, Bull presented the five-part [[BBC Radio 4]] series, ''Dance Nation'', on English dance.<ref name=\"BBC Dance Nation 2012\">{{cite episode| title= Deborah Bull's Dance Nation| series= Deborah Bull's Dance Nation| serieslink= | credits= Presenter: Deborah Bull; Producer:  Hannah Rosenfelder| network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01mvzll | airdate= September 2012| accessdate= 31 March 2017 }}</ref> She was the castaway on BBC Radio 4's ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in May the following year.<ref name=\"Desert Island Discs\">{{cite episode| title= Deborah Bull| series= [[Desert Island Discs]]| credits= Presenter: [[Kirsty Young]]; Producer:  Cathy Drysdale |network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio 4]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01slqck| airdate= 31 May 2013| accessdate= 1 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== Public service ==\nShe was a member of the [[Arts Council England]] from 1998 to 2005 and a Governor of the BBC from 2003 to 2006. Additionally, she is a patron of the [[National Osteoporosis Society]], Foundation for Community Dance and Escape Artists (a theatre company of paroled and ex-prisoners), sits on the Board of the [[Prix de Lausanne]] and is an Honorary Vice President of Voices of British Ballet. \n\nShe was a judge for the 2010 [[Man Booker Prize]]. She has been awarded Honorary Doctorates by [[University of Derby]] (1998), [[Sheffield Hallam University]] (2001), [[University of Kent|Kent University]] (2010) and the [[Open University]] (2005) and was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the Queen's [[1999 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55513 |date=12 June 1999 |page=8 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, it was announced that Bull had been appointed the first Executive Director of [[King's College London]]'s King's Cultural Institute, and would be taking up the role in March 2012.<ref name=\"KCL December 2011\">{{cite web |url= http://www.kcl.ac.uk/newsevents/news/newsrecords/2011/12December/Kings-College-London-appoints-Deborah-Bull-Executive-Director-Kings-Cultural-Institute.aspx|title= Deborah Bull joins King's College London |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 5 December 2011 |website= www.kcl.ac.uk |publisher= [[King's College London]]| accessdate= 1 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBull was nominated for a [[life peer]]age by the [[House of Lords Appointments Commission]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brickcourt.co.uk/document-uploads/HOLAC_080618.doc|title=Three new non-party-political peers}}</ref> She was created '''Baroness Bull''', of Aldwych in the City of Westminster, on 11 July.<ref name=\"LG\">{{London Gazette|issue=62352|date=16 July 2018|page=12576}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.deborahbull.com}}\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01slqck Deborah Bull] on ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in 2013\n*[https://archive.is/20121223022337/http://www.kent.ac.uk/news/homepagestories/honorary-degrees-nov10/2010/  Honorary Degree (University of Kent)]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-prec|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Rosie Boycott|The Baroness Boycott]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Order of precedence in England and Wales#Ladie|Ladies]]|years=}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Suzanne Heywood|The Lady Heywood of Whitehall]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bull, Deborah}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal Ballet School]]\n[[Category:Principal dancers of The Royal Ballet]]\n[[Category:People from Derby]]\n[[Category:English ballerinas]]\n[[Category:BBC Governors]]\n[[Category:People's peers]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Prix de Lausanne winners]]\n[[Category:Royal Opera House]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eROH2:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deborah_Bull,_Baroness_Bull"}
{"title_page": "John Walton, Baron Walton of Detchant", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n | name               = The Lord Walton of Detchant\n | honorific-suffix   = [[Knight bachelor|Kt]]\n | image              = The Lord Walton of Detchant.png\n | caption            = In a House of Lords debate in 2015.\n | order              = \n | office             = President of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]] \n | term_start         = 1984\n | term_end           = 1986 \n | predecessor        = [[James Watt (surgeon)|Sir James Watt]]\n | successor          = [[Gordon Robson|Sir Gordon Robson]]\n | order2             = \n | office2            = [[Master (college)|Warden]] of [[Green College, Oxford]]\n | term_start2        = 1983 \n | term_end2          = 1989\n | predecessor2       = \n | successor2         = \n | order3             = \n | office3            = President of the [[General Medical Council]]\n | term_start3        = 1982\n | term_end3          = 1989\n | predecessor3       = \n | successor3         = \n | order4             = \n | office4            = President of the [[British Medical Association]]\n | term_start4        = 1980\n | term_end4          = 1982\n | predecessor4       = \n | successor4         = \n<!-- Personal -->\n | birth_name      = John Nicholas Walton\n | birth_date      = {{Birth date|1922|9|16|df=y}}\n | birth_place     = \n | death_date      = {{Death date and age|2016|4|21|1922|9|16|df=y}}\n | death_place     = \n | resting_place   = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship     = United Kingdom\n | nationality     = British\n | party           = None ([[crossbencher]])\n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = \n | alma_mater      = [[University of Durham]]\n | occupation      = \n | profession      = \n | known_for       = \n | cabinet         = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | religion        =  <!-- Do not insert religious denominations in this parameter by themselves; always enter the religion first -->\n | awards          = [[Knight Bachelor]] (1979) <br /> [[Life Peer]] (1989) <br /> [[Member of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n}}\n'''John Nicholas Walton, Baron Walton of Detchant''' [[Knight bachelor|Kt]] (16 September 1922 \u2013 21 April 2016<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/47812/page/4623 Notice of knighthood bestowed on John Nicholas Walton], the gazette.co.uk; accessed 27 April 2016.</ref>) was a British [[neuroscientist]], academic, and [[life peer]] who sat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]].\n\n==Life==\n{{moresources|section|date=April 2016}}\nLord Walton qualified from [[Newcastle University Medical School|Newcastle Medical School]] (then part of the University of Durham). Walton was President of the [[British Medical Association]] (BMA) from 1980\u201382, President of the [[General Medical Council]] (GMC) 1982-89 and President of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]] from 1984\u201386. He was also appointed second Warden of [[Green College, Oxford]] in 1983, where he stayed until 1989. Green College merged with [[Templeton College, Oxford]] in 2008 to become [[Green Templeton College, Oxford|Green Templeton College]], located on the site that was previously Green College.\n\nHaving been [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1979,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47812|date=6 April 1979|page=4623}}</ref> Walton was created a [[life peer]] on 24 July 1989 as '''Baron Walton of Detchant''', ''of [[Detchant]] in the [[County of Northumberland]]''<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=51823|date=27 July 1989|page=8725}}</ref> and sat as a [[crossbencher]]. In 1992 he became a member of the Science and Technology Committee, leaving in 1996, returning in 1997 and leaving again in 2001. From 1993-94 he was Chair of the Medical Ethics committee. He was Secretary of the Rare Diseases Group from 2009 until his death.\n\nHe was a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26849/artikkel/vis.html?tid=40128|title=Gruppe 7: Medisinske fag|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=7 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927171110/http://www.dnva.no/c26849/artikkel/vis.html?tid=40128|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was Patron of [[The Little Foundation]], Honorary Life President of the [[Muscular Dystrophy Campaign]], Vice President of [[Parkinson's UK]] and Honorary Chairman of the United Kingdom Medical Students' Association (UKMSA).{{cn|date=April 2016}}\n\n==Death==\nLord Walton of Detchant died on 21 April 2016, aged 93.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-walton-of-detchant/1716 Notice of death of Lord Walton of Detchant], parliament.uk; accessed 27 April 2016.</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Walton of Detchant Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|crest =  Issuant from Clouds proper a Sea-Horse Argent the Piscine Part proper crined and finned Or holding between the forelegs a Cross Formy quadrate fitchy at the foot Purpure\n|coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = Paly wavy Argent and Gules a Castle triple towered Purpure on a Chief of the last three Crosses Formy quadrate Gold\n|supporters = Dexter: a Boar Gold suspended from the neck by a Riband Purpure a Clarion pipes downwards Gules; Sinister: a Greyling Goose proper\n|motto ='''DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT''' <br /> [[French language|French]]: ''GOD DEFEND THE RIGHT'' \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-john-walton-1 Profile], hansard.millbanksystems.com\n* [http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cats/5/2288.htm Profile], aim25.ac.uk\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110814205651/http://dodonline.co.uk/engine.asp?lev1=4&lev2=38&menu=98&biog=y&id=26509&group=5&Page=Lord%20Walton%20of%20Detchant%20:%20Political%20Biography Profile], dodonline.co.uk\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080527152041/http://www.brookes.ac.uk/about/history/hon_grads/profiles/john_walton Profile], brookes.ac.uk\n* [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/accessions/2002/02digests/medic.htm Profile], nationalarchives.gov.uk\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111021080346/http://www.ukmsa.org/?p=21 Profile], ukmsa.org\n* {{History of Modern Biomedicine Research Group ID}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walton, John, Baron Walton of Detchant}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Members of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:English neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Newcastle University]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the British Medical Association]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Royal Society of Medicine]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Wardens of Green College, Oxford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n | name               = The Lord Walton of Detchant\n | honorific-suffix   = [[Knight bachelor|Kt]]\n | image              = The Lord Walton of Detchant.png\n | caption            = In a House of Lords debate in 2015.\n | order              = \n | office             = President of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]] \n | term_start         = 1984\n | term_end           = 1986 \n | predecessor        = [[James Watt (surgeon)|Sir James Watt]]\n | successor          = [[Gordon Robson|Sir Gordon Robson]]\n | order2             = \n | office2            = [[Master (college)|Warden]] of [[Green College, Oxford]]\n | term_start2        = 1983 \n | term_end2          = 1989\n | predecessor2       = \n | successor2         = \n | order3             = \n | office3            = President of the [[General Medical Council]]\n | term_start3        = 1982\n | term_end3          = 1989\n | predecessor3       = \n | successor3         = \n | order4             = \n | office4            = President of the [[British Medical Association]]\n | term_start4        = 1980\n | term_end4          = 1982\n | predecessor4       = \n | successor4         = \n<!-- Personal -->\n | birth_name      = John Nicholas Walton\n | birth_date      = {{Birth date|1922|9|16|df=y}}\n | birth_place     = \n | death_date      = {{Death date and age|2016|4|21|1922|9|16|df=y}}\n | death_place     = \n | resting_place   = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship     = United Kingdom\n | nationality     = British\n | party           = None ([[crossbencher]])\n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = \n | alma_mater      = [[University of Durham]]\n | occupation      = \n | profession      = \n | known_for       = \n | cabinet         = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | religion        =  <!-- Do not insert religious denominations in this parameter by themselves; always enter the religion first -->\n | awards          = [[Knight Bachelor]] (1979) <br /> [[Life Peer]] (1989) <br /> [[Member of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n}}\n'''John Nicholas Walton, Baron Walton of Detchant''' [[Knight bachelor|Kt]] (16 September 1922 \u2013 21 April 2016<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/47812/page/4623 Notice of knighthood bestowed on John Nicholas Walton], the gazette.co.uk; accessed 27 April 2016.</ref>) was a British [[neuroscientist]], academic, and [[life peer]] who sat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]].\n\n==Life==\n{{moresources|section|date=April 2016}}\nLord Walton qualified from [[Newcastle University Medical School|Newcastle Medical School]] (then part of the University of Durham). Walton was President of the [[British Medical Association]] (BMA) from 1980-82, President of the [[General Medical Council]] (GMC) 1982-89 and President of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]] from 1984-86. He was also appointed second Warden of [[Green College, Oxford]] in 1983, where he stayed until 1989. Green College merged with [[Templeton College, Oxford]] in 2008 to become [[Green Templeton College, Oxford|Green Templeton College]], located on the site that was previously Green College.\n\nHaving been [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1979,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47812|date=6 April 1979|page=4623}}</ref> Walton was created a [[life peer]] on 24 July 1989 as '''Baron Walton of Detchant''', ''of [[Detchant]] in the [[County of Northumberland]]''<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=51823|date=27 July 1989|page=8725}}</ref> and sat as a [[crossbencher]]. In 1992 he became a member of the Science and Technology Committee, leaving in 1996, returning in 1997 and leaving again in 2001. From 1993-94 he was Chair of the Medical Ethics committee. He was Secretary of the Rare Diseases Group from 2009 until his death.\n\nHe was a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26849/artikkel/vis.html?tid=40128|title=Gruppe 7: Medisinske fag|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=7 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927171110/http://www.dnva.no/c26849/artikkel/vis.html?tid=40128|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was Patron of [[The Little Foundation]], Honorary Life President of the [[Muscular Dystrophy Campaign]], Vice President of [[Parkinson's UK]] and Honorary Chairman of the United Kingdom Medical Students' Association (UKMSA).{{cn|date=April 2016}}\n\n==Death==\nLord Walton of Detchant died on 21 April 2016, aged 93.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-walton-of-detchant/1716 Notice of death of Lord Walton of Detchant], parliament.uk; accessed 27 April 2016.</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Walton of Detchant Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|crest =  Issuant from Clouds proper a Sea-Horse Argent the Piscine Part proper crined and finned Or holding between the forelegs a Cross Formy quadrate fitchy at the foot Purpure\n|coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = Paly wavy Argent and Gules a Castle triple towered Purpure on a Chief of the last three Crosses Formy quadrate Gold\n|supporters = Dexter: a Boar Gold suspended from the neck by a Riband Purpure a Clarion pipes downwards Gules; Sinister: a Greyling Goose proper\n|motto ='''DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT''' <br /> [[French language|French]]: ''GOD DEFEND THE RIGHT'' \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-john-walton-1 Profile], hansard.millbanksystems.com\n* [http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cats/5/2288.htm Profile], aim25.ac.uk\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110814205651/http://dodonline.co.uk/engine.asp?lev1=4&lev2=38&menu=98&biog=y&id=26509&group=5&Page=Lord%20Walton%20of%20Detchant%20:%20Political%20Biography Profile], dodonline.co.uk\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080527152041/http://www.brookes.ac.uk/about/history/hon_grads/profiles/john_walton Profile], brookes.ac.uk\n* [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/accessions/2002/02digests/medic.htm Profile], nationalarchives.gov.uk\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111021080346/http://www.ukmsa.org/?p=21 Profile], ukmsa.org\n* {{History of Modern Biomedicine Research Group ID}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walton, John, Baron Walton of Detchant}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Members of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:English neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Newcastle University]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the British Medical Association]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Royal Society of Medicine]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Wardens of Green College, Oxford]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1980-82 \u2192 1980\u201382 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Walton,_Baron_Walton_of_Detchant"}
{"title_page": "2019 Champion of Champions", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Snooker tournament, held November 2019}}\n{{Infobox individual snooker tournament\n|tournament_name=2019 ManBetX [[Champion of Champions (snooker)|Champion of Champions]]\n|logo=\n|dates=4\u201310 November 2019\n|venue=[[Ricoh Arena]]\n|location=[[Coventry]]\n|country=[[England]]\n|organisation=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]\n|format=Non-[[Snooker world rankings|ranking]] event\n|Total prize fund=[[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]440,000\n|winners_share=\u00a3150,000\n|defending_champion=\n|highest_break={{flagathlete|[[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]|NIR}} (140)\n|winner={{flagathlete|[[Neil Robertson]]|AUS}}\n|runner_up={{flagathlete|[[Judd Trump]]|ENG}}\n|score=10\u20139\n|previous=[[2018 Champion of Champions|2018]]\n|next=[[2020 Champion of Champions|2020]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2019 Champion of Champions''' (also known as the '''2019 ManBetX Champion of Champions''' for sponsorship reasons) was a professional [[snooker]] tournament that took place between 4 and 10 November 2019 at the [[Ricoh Arena]] in [[Coventry]], England. It was the ninth [[Champion of Champions (snooker)|Champion of Champions]] event, the first of which was held in [[1978 Champion of Champions|1978]]. The tournament featured 16 participants who had won World Snooker events throughout the prior snooker season. In 2019, winners of both the [[World Seniors Championship]] and [[Women's World Snooker Championship|Women's World Championship]] competed at the tournament for the first time. As an invitational event, the Champion of Champions tournament carried no [[snooker world rankings|world ranking]] points.\n\n[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] was the defending champion, having defeated [[Kyren Wilson]] 10\u20139 in the final of the [[2018 Champion of Champions|2018 event]]. O'Sullivan lost 5\u20136 to [[Neil Robertson]] in the semi-finals. Robertson defeated [[2019 World Snooker Championship|reigning world champion]] [[Judd Trump]] 10\u20139 in the final to win the championship, having required {{cuegloss|snooker|foul shots}} in the penultimate frame to avoid losing the match. There were 20 [[century break]]s during the tournament, eight of which were made in the final. [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] compiled the highest break of the tournament, a 140, in his semi-final loss to Trump. The tournament's total prize fund was [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]440,000, the winner receiving \u00a3150,000.\n\n==Format==\nThe [[Champion of Champions (snooker)|Champion of Champions]] is an invitational [[snooker]] tournament, first held in 1978,<ref name=\"timespre\" /> and annually since [[2013 Champion of Champions|2013]].<ref name=\"vnrml\" /><ref name=\"lyYHz\" /> As an invitational event, it does not carry any [[snooker world rankings|world ranking]] points.<ref name=\"CPmTD\" /> The 2019 Champion of Champions, which took place from 4&nbsp;to 10 November 2019 at the [[Ricoh Arena]] in [[Coventry]], England,<ref name=\"coverage\" /> featured 16&nbsp;winners of events from the previous 12&nbsp;months on the [[World Snooker Tour]].<ref name=\"womens\" /> The [[World Women's Snooker Championship]] and the [[World Seniors Championship]] were added to the list of eligible events for 2019, the winners of these two championships being allowed to participate in the Champion of Champions for the first time.<ref name=\"womens\" /><ref name=\"s1AI7\" /> The tournament was organised by [[Matchroom Sport]] and broadcast on [[ITV4]].<ref name=\"coverage\" />\n\nThe 16 qualifiers were split into four groups of four players; each group competed on a different day, with the group finals (event quarter-finals) played on the same day as the corresponding first-round matches. The two semi-finals were played on separate days \u2013 8&nbsp;and 9 November \u2013 with the final on 10 November. The length of the matches varied throughout the competition, those in the opening round being best-of-7 {{cuegloss|frames}}, group finals and semi-finals best-of-11-frames, and the two-session final played as a best-of-19-frames match.<ref name=\"snoo_Cham\" /> [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] automatically qualified for the event, having defeated [[Kyren Wilson]] in the [[2018 Champion of Champions]] final 10\u20139.<ref name=\"3lUvb\" /><ref name=\"4tv9q\" />\n\n===Prize fund===\nThe event featured a prize fund of [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]440,000, an increase of \u00a370,000 over the 2018 Champion of Champions tournament.<ref name=\"IVqQJ\" /> The winner's prize money was increased from the previous year by \u00a350,000, to \u00a3150,000.<ref name=\"cham_Priz\" />\n\nThe breakdown of prize money for the 2019 event was:<ref name=\"cham_Priz\" /><ref name=\"4yljh\" />\n\n* Winner: \u00a3150,000\n* Runner-up: \u00a360,000\n* Semi-final: \u00a330,000\n* Group runner-up: \u00a317,500\n* First round loser: \u00a312,500\n* Total: \u00a3440,000\n\n===Qualification===\nQualification for the 2019 Champion of Champions event was determined by the winners of 26 tournaments over a one-year period, from the 2018 Champion of Champions to the [[2019 World Open (snooker)|2019 World Open]], thereby including tournaments from both the [[2018\u201319 snooker season|2018\u201319]] and [[2019\u201320 snooker season|2019\u201320]] snooker seasons.<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /> The tournaments were placed into six groups dependent on the size of the event, with the previous year's Champion of Champions and the [[Triple Crown (snooker)|Triple Crown]] events listed in the first group, and tournaments in the same group were listed chronologically.<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /> The winners of the first 16 tournaments on the list were guaranteed a place in the championship. In the event of any of these players meeting multiple qualification criteria, the winners of subsequent tournaments on the list (in the order shown below) would be offered a place in the Champion of Champions.<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /><ref name=\"wpbs_Cham\" /> [[Judd Trump]] qualified for the event by winning six of the first 16 tournaments, the most won by any player.<ref name=\"2019qualification\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 310px;\" | Tournament !! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 160px;\" | Date of tournament final !! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 200px;\" | Winner\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2018 Champion of Champions]] || align=\"center\" |11 November 2018 || {{flagathlete|[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2018 UK Championship]] || align=\"center\"|9 December 2018 || {{flagathlete|[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]|ENG}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Masters (snooker)|2019 Masters]] || align=\"center\"|20 January 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Judd Trump]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 World Snooker Championship|2019 World Championship]] || align=\"center\"|6 May 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Judd Trump]]|ENG}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 German Masters]] || align=\"center\"|3 February 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Kyren Wilson]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 World Grand Prix]] || align=\"center\"|10 February 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Judd Trump]]|ENG}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Indian Open]] || align=\"center\"|3 March 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Matthew Selt]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Players Championship (snooker)|2019 Players Championship]] || align=\"center\"|10 March 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]|ENG}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Championship League]] || align=\"center\"|14 March 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Martin Gould]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Tour Championship]] || align=\"center\"|24 March 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]|ENG}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 China Open (snooker)|2019 China Open]] || align=\"center\"|7 April 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Neil Robertson]]|AUS}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 International Championship (snooker)|2019 International Championship]] || align=\"center\"|11 August 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Judd Trump]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Shanghai Masters]] || align=\"center\"|15 September 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]|ENG}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 China Championship]] || align=\"center\"|29 September 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Shaun Murphy]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\" \n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 World Open (snooker)|2019 World Open]] || align=\"center\"|3 November 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Judd Trump]]|ENG}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\" \n| align=\"center\"| [[2018 Northern Ireland Open]] || align=\"center\"|18 November 2018 || {{flagathlete|[[Judd Trump]]|ENG}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\"| [[2018 Scottish Open (snooker)|2018 Scottish Open]] || align=\"center\"|16 December 2018 || {{flagathlete|[[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]|NIR}}\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\" \n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Welsh Open (snooker)|2019 Welsh Open]] || align=\"center\"|17 February 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Neil Robertson]]|AUS}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 English Open (snooker)|2019 English Open]] || align=\"center\"|20 October 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Mark Selby]]|ENG}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Gibraltar Open]] || align=\"center\"|17 March 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Stuart Bingham]]|ENG}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 World Snooker Championship|2019 World Championship]] (runner-up) || align=\"center\"|6 May 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[John Higgins]]|SCO}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Riga Masters]] || align=\"center\"|28 July 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Yan Bingtao]]|CHN}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=2| [[2019 World Cup (snooker)|2019 World Cup]] || align=\"center\" rowspan=2|30 June 2019 ||  style=\"background:lightgrey\"|{{flagathlete|[[John Higgins]]|SCO}}\n|- \n| {{flagathlete|[[Stephen Maguire]]|SCO}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Snooker Shoot Out|2019 Shoot Out]] || align=\"center\"|24 February 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh|Thepchaiya {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}}]]|THA}}\n|-\n|-style=\"background:lightgrey\"\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 Six-red World Championship]] || align=\"center\"|7 September 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Stephen Maguire]]|SCO}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\"| [[World Women's Snooker Championship|2019 World Women's Snooker Championship]] || align=\"center\"|23 June 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Reanne Evans]]|ENG}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 World Seniors Championship]] || align=\"center\"|18 August 2019 || {{flagathlete|[[Jimmy White]]|ENG}}\n|-\n|}\n\n:{|class=\"wikitable\" span = 50 style=\"font-size:85%;\n|-\n|style=\"background:lightgrey\": #cfc;\" width=10|\n|Player had already qualified by winning a previous event\n|}\n\n==Summary==\nThe event featured 16 participants, split into four groups of four players. There were eight [[seed (sports)|seed]]ed players, based on the [[world snooker rankings]], and each of the top four seeds was placed into a separate group. As defending champion, [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] was seeded first, world champion [[Judd Trump]] second, [[Mark Selby]] third and [[Neil Robertson]] fourth.<ref name=\"seeds\" /> Each group was played over the course of a single day, as a [[single-elimination tournament|single-elimination]], rather than a [[round-robin tournament|round-robin]] competition.<ref name=\"cham_GROU\" /><ref name=\"cham_Fixt\" />\n\n===Group stages===\n[[File:Reanne Evans PHC 2017-2.jpg|thumb|alt=Reanne Evans ready to play a shot with the rest|[[Reanne Evans]] was the first woman to play at the event.]]\nThe championship began on 4 November 2019, with players from group four competing in the first round. The opening match was between Neil Robertson and [[2019 Championship League]] winner [[Martin Gould]].<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /> Robertson defeated Gould 4\u20130, the highest {{cuegloss|break}} of the match being just 67.<ref name=\"lBDSi\" /> In the other group four match, [[2019 China Championship]] winner [[Shaun Murphy]] played [[Reanne Evans]], the [[2019 World Women's Snooker Championship|2019 World Women's Snooker champion]].<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /> Speaking to the press before the match, Evans reflected that whilst it was an honour to play in the competition despite not being on the World Snooker Tour, there was still a disparity between the men's and women's games.<ref name=\"9aMLP\" /> She also commented that the prize money for appearing at the event was double that of any she had received before, despite having won the women's world championship on 12 occasions.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nMurphy developed an early lead by winning the first three frames of the match, before Evans took the next three to force a {{cuegloss|deciding frame}}. She went {{cuegloss|in-off}} whilst playing a {{cuegloss|safety shot}} in the final frame, allowing Murphy to make a break of 130 and win the match 4\u20133. Murphy praised Evans afterwards, saying that he really hoped \"we see more of Reanne on the main event\".<ref name=\"BBC Reanne\" /> He also remarked later that the audience were supporting Evans and even his wife was \"reluctant to wish [him] good luck today\".<ref name=\"BBC Reanne\" /> Murphy and Robertson competed in the group four final. Murphy again took the first three frames of the match, before Robertson drew level at 3\u20133 after a break of 100 and two breaks of 90 plus. The two players shared the next four frames, both experiencing issues with the table {{cuegloss|table roll|running off}}, to tie the match at 5\u20135. Robertson took the deciding frame to win 6\u20135.<ref name=\"R227m\" />\n\nThe group three matches were played on 5 November, three-time world champion Mark Selby defeating first-time ranking event winner [[Yan Bingtao]] 4\u20130.<ref name=\"group 3\" /> The [[2018 Scottish Open (snooker)|2018 Scottish Open]] winner [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] defeated the [[2019 Indian Open]] winner [[Matthew Selt]] in the other group three first-round match.<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /><ref name=\"group 3\" /> In the group three final, Allen recovered from 1\u20132 behind to defeat Selby 6\u20132.<ref name=\"group 3\" /> The group two matches, played on 6 November, featured a first-round encounter between the [[2019 World Snooker Championship|reigning world champion]] Judd Trump and the six-red and World Cup winner [[Stephen Maguire]].<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /> Trump won the first two frames of the match, Maguire scoring just four points. Trump also took frames three and four, making three breaks of over 50, to win the match 4\u20130.<ref name=\"euro group 2\" /> The [[2019 Snooker Shoot Out]] winner [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh|Thepchaiya {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}}]] played [[Kyren Wilson]] in the other group two first-round match. {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}} won three of the first four frames, with breaks of 63, 51 and 90, before Wilson made breaks of 102 and 98 to force a deciding frame. {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}} won the match 4\u20133 to progress to the group two final,<ref name=\"euro group 2\" /> which was a rematch of the [[2019 World Open (snooker)|2019 World Open]] final, held the previous week, between Trump and {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}}.<ref name=\"pd5Sf\" /> Trump won the first four frames of the match, scoring two centuries; {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}} won frame five but Trump then pulled ahead to 5\u20131. After {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}} replied with breaks of 61 and 66, Trump took the ninth frame to win the match 6\u20133.<ref name=\"euro group 2\" />\n\nThe group one matches took place on 7 November. World number three Ronnie O'Sullivan played [[2019 World Seniors Championship]] winner [[Jimmy White]] in the first match.<ref name=\"2019qualification\" /> White took the first three frames, before O'Sullivan won the next two.<ref name=\"White/O'Sullivan\"/> During frame six, White suffered a {{cuegloss|kick}} at a crucial point where he could have won the match, allowing O'Sullivan to force a deciding frame, which he won.<ref name=\"White/O'Sullivan\">{{Cite news |title=Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Jimmy White 4\u20133 in the Champion of Champions |newspaper=[[BBC Sport]] |date=7 November 2019 |access-date=18 November 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50335557 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108175029/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50335557 |archive-date=8 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"O5izV\" /> Two former world champions, [[John Higgins]] and [[Stuart Bingham]], met in the other group one first-round match, which Higgins won 4\u20132.<ref name=\"O5izV\" /> O'Sullivan defeated Higgins 6\u20133 in the group one final.<ref name=\"O5izV\" /> O'Sullivan's {{cuegloss|average shot time}} during the match was just 13 seconds per shot.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Yates, Phil<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Robertson triumphs in Champion of Champions |magazine=Snooker Scene |page=16 |location=Halesowen |publisher=Snooker Scene Ltd |date=December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Knockout stages===\n[[File:Daniel Wells and Neil Robertson at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2013-01-30 03.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph shows one man leaning over a snooker table to line up a shot while another man stands behind him watching. | [[Neil Robertson]] won the event, defeating [[Judd Trump]] 10\u20139 in the final.]]\nThe semi-finals were played as best-of-11-frames matches. The first semi-final was held on 8 November between Ronnie O'Sullivan and Neil Robertson.<ref name=\"Y2XQD\" /> The pair had met in the finals of two events in the [[2019 Coral Cup]] series\u2014the [[2019 Tour Championship|Tour Championship]] and the [[2019 Players Championship (snooker)|Players Championship]]\u2014with O'Sullivan winning on both occasions.<ref name=\"av9gi\" /> The match was even throughout, with no more than one frame separating the two players.<ref name=\"O'Sullivan/Robertson\"/> Robertson compiled a break of 108 in frame five to open up a 3\u20132 lead, O'Sullivan winning three of the next four frames to lead 5\u20134. Robertson won frame 10 with a break of 135, the highest of the tournament at that point, to force a deciding frame.<ref name=\"O'Sullivan/Robertson\">{{Cite news |title=Champion of Champions: Neil Robertson beats Ronnie O'Sullivan in semi-final |newspaper=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 November 2019 |access-date=29 November 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50355241 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110175129/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50355241 |archive-date=10 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> O'Sullivan gained the first chance of the final frame, but {{cuegloss|miscued}} on the {{cuegloss|black ball}}, allowing Robertson to make a break of 90 to win the match 6\u20135.<ref name=\"O'Sullivan/Robertson\"/> Robertson later commented that the match was \"definitely one of the best matches [he had] been involved in\".<ref name=\"O'Sullivan/Robertson\"/>\n\nMark Allen and Judd Trump met in the second semi-final on 9 November.<ref name=\"semi2\" /> Trump won the first three frames of the match, but Allen took the next four, including the tournament's highest break of 140, to lead 4\u20133.<ref name=\"b20d9\" /><ref name=\"semi2\" /> Trump made a break of 86 to tie the match, and then clinched frame nine after a {{cuegloss|fluke}} when potting a {{cuegloss|red ball}}.<ref name=\"semi2\" /> With a break of 98 in frame 10, Trump won the match 6\u20134.<ref name=\"semi2\" />\n\nThe final between Trump and Robertson was played as a best-of-19-frames match over two sessions on 10 November.<ref name=\"N6DqY\" /> The referee for the final was Desislava Bozhilova.<ref name=\"snooker.org\" /> Robertson won the first two frames of the match, including a break of 112 in the second frame, and took an early 3\u20131 lead.<ref name=\"eurosport final\" /> Trump then made three consecutive centuries in frames five to seven, totalling 367 points without reply, to go ahead 4\u20133.<ref name=\"eurosport final\" /> Breaks of 96 and 111 gave Robertson the next two frames to retake the lead at 5\u20134 between the two sessions.<ref name=\"eurosport final\" /><ref name=\"BBC final\" />\n\nTrump took the first frame of the second session, but Robertson replied with a break of 104.<ref name=\"snooker.org\" /> Trump won the next two frames to go ahead 7\u20136, and retained the lead until Robertson made a break of 135 in the 16th frame to tie the match at 8\u20138.<ref name=\"snooker.org\" /><ref name=\"eurosport final\" /> Trump required foul shots from his opponent to win frame 17, and went ahead once again.<ref name=\"eurosport final\" /> Robertson needed a {{cuegloss|snooker}} in frame 18 to avoid losing the match; he succeeded and forced a {{cuegloss|re-spotted black}}, which he potted to draw level at 9\u20139.<ref name=\"BBC final\" /> He then made a break of 137 in the deciding frame to win the match 10\u20139. This was Robertson's second Champion of Champions victory, having won the event in [[2015 Champion of Champions|2015]].<ref name=\"snoo_188B\" /> He later commented: \"I can't believe the pair of us playing a match like that. It's the best match I've ever been involved in\".<ref name=\"BBC final\" /> With a total of eight [[century break]]s (five of which were compiled by Robertson), the final included a record number of centuries for a best-of-19-frames match.<ref name=\"snooker.org\" /><ref name=\"snoo_Neil\" /> There were 784,000 viewers on ITV4 across the two sessions of the final.<ref name=\"auto\" /> This was the second-highest non-terrestrial viewing figure for the day, behind a Premier League football match between [[Liverpool F.C.]] and [[Manchester City F.C.]] on [[Sky Sports]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==Main draw==\nBelow is the main draw for the event. Numbers in brackets show the four seeded players. Players in bold denote match winners.<ref name=\"snoo_Cham\" /><ref name=\"or2bp\" />\n{{16TeamBracket\n| RD1= '''Last 16 (Group semi-finals)''' <br/>Best of 7 frames\n| RD2= '''Quarter-finals (Group finals)''' <br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD3= '''Semi-finals''' <br/>Best of 11 frames\n| RD4= '''Final''' <br/>Best of 19 frames\n| subgroup1='''Group 1''' (7 November) \n| subgroup2='''Group 4''' (4 November)\n| subgroup3='''Group 3''' (5 November)\n| subgroup4='''Group 2''' (6 November)\n\n| RD1-seed01=\n| RD1-team01={{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] (1)'''\n| RD1-score01='''4'''\n| RD1-seed02=\n| RD1-team02={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Jimmy White]]\n| RD1-score02=3\n| RD1-seed03=\n| RD1-team03={{flagicon|SCO}} '''[[John Higgins]]'''\n| RD1-score03='''4'''\n| RD1-seed04=\n| RD1-team04={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Stuart Bingham]]\n| RD1-score04=2\n\n| RD1-seed05=\n| RD1-team05={{flagicon|AUS}} '''[[Neil Robertson]] (4)'''\n| RD1-score05='''4''' \n| RD1-seed06=\n| RD1-team06={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Martin Gould]]\n| RD1-score06=0\n| RD1-seed07=\n| RD1-team07={{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Shaun Murphy]]'''\n| RD1-score07='''4'''\n| RD1-seed08=\n| RD1-team08={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Reanne Evans]]\n| RD1-score08=3\n\n| RD1-seed09=\n| RD1-team09={{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Mark Selby]] (3)'''\n| RD1-score09='''4'''\n| RD1-seed10=\n| RD1-team10={{flagicon|CHN}} [[Yan Bingtao]]\n| RD1-score10=0\n| RD1-seed11=\n| RD1-team11={{flagicon|NIR}} '''[[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]'''\n| RD1-score11='''4'''\n| RD1-seed12=\n| RD1-team12={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Matthew Selt]]\n| RD1-score12=2\n\n| RD1-seed13=\n| RD1-team13={{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Judd Trump]] (2)'''\n| RD1-score13='''4'''\n| RD1-seed14=\n| RD1-team14={{flagicon|SCO}} [[Stephen Maguire]]\n| RD1-score14=0\n| RD1-seed15=\n| RD1-team15={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Kyren Wilson]]\n| RD1-score15=3\n| RD1-seed16=\n| RD1-team16={{flagicon|THA}} '''[[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh|Thepchaiya {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}}]]'''\n| RD1-score16='''4'''\n\n| RD2-seed01=\n| RD2-team01={{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] (1)'''\n| RD2-score01='''6'''\n| RD2-seed02=\n| RD2-team02={{flagicon|SCO}} [[John Higgins]]\n| RD2-score02=3\n\n| RD2-seed03=\n| RD2-team03='''{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Neil Robertson]] (4)'''\n| RD2-score03='''6'''\n| RD2-seed04=\n| RD2-team04={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Shaun Murphy]]\n| RD2-score04=5\n\n| RD2-seed05=\n| RD2-team05={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Mark Selby]] (3)\n| RD2-score05=2\n| RD2-seed06=\n| RD2-team06={{flagicon|NIR}} '''[[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]'''\n| RD2-score06='''6'''\n\n| RD2-seed07=\n| RD2-team07={{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Judd Trump]] (2)'''\n| RD2-score07='''6'''\n| RD2-seed08=\n| RD2-team08={{flagicon|THA}} [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh|Thepchaiya {{nowrap|Un-Nooh}}]]\n| RD2-score08=3\n\n| RD3-seed01=\n| RD3-team01={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] (1)\n| RD3-score01=5\n| RD3-seed02=\n| RD3-team02={{flagicon|AUS}} '''[[Neil Robertson]] (4)'''\n| RD3-score02='''6'''\n\n| RD3-seed03=\n| RD3-team03={{flagicon|NIR}} [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]\n| RD3-score03=4\n| RD3-seed04=\n| RD3-team04={{flagicon|ENG}} '''[[Judd Trump]] (2)'''\n| RD3-score04='''6'''\n\n| RD4-seed01=\n| RD4-team01='''{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Neil Robertson]] (4)'''\n| RD4-score01='''10'''\n| RD4-seed02=\n| RD4-team02={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Judd Trump]] (2)\n| RD4-score02=9\n}}\n\n===Final===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffd700\" | '''Final:''' Best of 19 frames. Referee: Desislava Bozhilova<br/>[[Ricoh Arena]], [[Coventry]], England, 10 November 2019\n|-\n| width=\"230\" align=\"right\" | '''[[Neil Robertson]]''' (4)<br/>{{AUS}}\n| width=\"100\" align=\"center\" | '''10'''\u20139\n| width=\"230\" align=\"left\" | [[Judd Trump]] (2)<br/>{{ENG}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" style=\"font-size: 100%\" | ''Afternoon:'' {{nobr|'''69'''\u201347}}, {{nobr|'''112'''\u20130 (112)}}, {{nobr|8\u2013'''86''' (86)}}, {{nobr|'''71'''\u201350 (56)}}, {{nobr|0\u2013'''121''' (121)}}, {{nobr|0\u2013'''127''' (127)}}, {{nobr|0\u2013'''119''' (119)}}, {{nobr|'''96'''\u20130 (96)}}, {{nobr|'''124'''\u20130 (111)}} <br/>''Evening:'' {{nobr|36\u2013'''75'''}}, {{nobr|'''104'''\u20130 (104)}}, {{nobr|58\u2013'''70'''}}, {{nobr|7\u2013'''84''' (84)}}, {{nobr|'''91'''\u201336 (81)}}, {{nobr|41\u2013'''75''' (62)}}, {{nobr|'''135'''\u20130 (135)}}, {{nobr|60\u2013'''62'''}}, {{nobr|'''76'''\u201369 (Trump 69),{{efn|Robertson won the frame on a [[Rules of snooker#The end of a frame|re-spotted black]].}}}} {{nobr|'''137'''\u20130 (137)}}\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | '''137'''\n| align=\"center\" | Highest break\n| 127\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | '''5'''\n| align=\"center\" | Century breaks\n| 3\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | '''8'''\n| align=\"center\" | 50+ breaks\n| 7\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Century breaks==\nA total of 20 {{cuegloss|century break|century breaks}} were made during the competition. Mark Allen made the highest break of the tournament, a 140 in frame five in his semi-final match against Trump.<ref name=\"b20d9\" />\n\n* 140, 108, 106 [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]\n* 137, 135, 135, 112, 111, 108, 104, 100 [[Neil Robertson]]\n* 130 [[Shaun Murphy]]\n* 128, 127, 121, 119, 114, 102 [[Judd Trump]]\n* 104 [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n* 102 [[Kyren Wilson]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"timespre\">{{cite news |newspaper=The Times |date=2 November 1978 |page=13 |title=Snooker \u2013 World champion in semi-final faces Fagan}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"womens\">{{Cite web |title=World women's snooker championship added to manbetx champion of champions qualifying list |work=Champion of Champions Snooker |date=18 July 2019 |access-date=4 November 2019 |url=http://www.championofchampionssnooker.co.uk/world-womens-snooker-championship-added-manbetx-champion-champions-qualifying-list/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719103